 them\",\n        \"bullets\": [\n          \"Which of the 93 Fur-released DEGs are operationally required\\u2014not merely incidentally derepressed?\",\n          \"Do constitutive sphingolipids and a repurposed Lpt apparatus suffice, or does rescue require new biosynthesis?\",\n          \"Why can *A. baumannii*, *N. meningitidis*, and *M. catarrhalis* not use the same route?\"\n        ],\n        \"image_path\": \"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_2/working/05_images/intro-pos1.png\",\n        \"provenance\": {\n          \"model\": \"gemini-3-pro-image-preview\",\n          \"cost_usd\": 0.0612425,\n          \"channel\": \"A\",\n          \"approved_at\": \"2026-06-08T23:05:45Z\"\n        }\n      },\n      \"id\": 3,\n      \"position\": 3\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"claim_evidence\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"Three evidence streams trace the \\u0394*fur* signal from regulon to envelope rescue\",\n        \"bullets\": [\n          \"Fur-signal isolation: 4580\\u21924584\\u21924599 strain contrast cross-referenced to Leaden 2018 \\u0394*fur* RNA-seq (\\u03c1=0.315, 93 DEGs)\",\n          \"Regulon triage: hypergeometric fitness enrichment of the 32-gene Fur-released subset against 33.25% genome-background rate (198 Caulobacter RB-TnSeq experiments)\",\n          \"Envelope characterization: transcript DE + single-replicate OM proteome + NCBI annotation-presence across 4 species, each claim evaluated at pre-registered bars\"\n        ],\n        \"image_path\": \"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_2/working/05_images/intro-pos2.png\",\n        \"provenance\": {\n          \"model\": \"gemini-3-pro-image-preview\",\n          \"cost_usd\": 0.05867625,\n          \"channel\": \"A\",\n          \"approved_at\": \"2026-06-08T23:26:06Z\"\n        }\n      },\n      \"id\": 4,\n      \"position\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"section_divider\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"punchline\": \"\\u0394fur derepression, not iron limitation, drives the lipid A-loss-permissive envelope state.\",\n        \"substory_number\": 1\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"This section stakes the load-bearing claim of the talk: the Fur transcription factor, through constitutive derepression of its regulon rather than through any iron-starvation response, creates the envelope state that makes lipid A loss viable in Caulobacter crescentus. Everything downstream in the talk \\u2014 the fitness-based subset ranking, the two-phase ChvI response, the sphingolipid substitution, the peptidoglycan reorganization \\u2014 is built on this premise. If the audience takes one structural idea from S1, it is that the driver is genetic (the \\u0394fur allele) not physiological (iron deprivation).\\n\\nThe primary evidence is a cross-study concordance. Our 4584-vs-4580 transcriptome correlates with Leaden et al. 2018's published \\u0394fur RNA-seq across their 93 differentially expressed genes at Spearman \\u03c1 = 0.315, p = 2.08e-03, with 71% sign concordance. That concordance is the fingerprint of the Fur-derepression program operating constitutively in our strain \\u2014 amplified by the dual \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB release, but directionally aligned with Leaden's \\u0394fur-alone signal. It anchors the driver claim.\\n\\nThree analyses carry this section in order. The strain-design contrast \\u2014 4580 \\u2192 4584 \\u2192 4599 \\u2014 leads, because the audience cannot interpret any expression contrast without understanding what each deletion does. The Leaden concordance scatter (NB01 cell 5) follows as the direct cross-study evidence. The iron-limitation discrimination from Leaden's own internal comparison and Zik et al. 2022's genetic-necessity result close the section by ruling out iron status as the explanation and establishing that \\u0394fur is required for, not merely correlated with, lipid A-loss viability.\\n\\nOne scope caveat to carry into the subsequent slides: the transcriptome was collected under a single PYE-rich growth condition. The Fur derepression we observe is constitutive to the \\u0394fur allele, but its magnitude under iron-deplete or minimal-medium conditions has not been measured in this project. Iron-limitation experiments are absent from the Caulobacter Fitness Browser compendium. REPORT \\u00a7Limitations names this single-condition boundary explicitly. It is the key partial-evidence constraint on the iron-discrimination result; the strain-design logic and Zik 2022 anchoring, by contrast, are direct evidence whose scope is the Ryan-lab genetic system. The first content slide walks through the 4580 \\u2192 4584 \\u2192 4599 strain logic before any expression data appears.\",\n      \"id\": 5,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n      \"position\": 5\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"workflow_diagram\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"Three-strain series isolates the \\u0394fur derepression signal in the lipid A-loss state\",\n        \"diagram\": {\n          \"kind\": \"boxes_and_arrows\",\n          \"nodes\": [\n            {\n              \"id\": \"s4580\",\n              \"label\": \"4580 \\u0394rsaA (reference baseline)\",\n              \"shape\": \"parallelogram\",\n              \"x\": 0.9,\n              \"y\": 1.8,\n              \"w\": 2.47,\n              \"h\": 0.9\n            },\n            {\n              \"id\": \"s4584\",\n              \"label\": \"4584 \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB \\u0394rsaA (dual-release, lipid A-replete)\",\n              \"shape\": \"rectangle\",\n              \"x\": 3.77,\n              \"y\": 1.8,\n              \"w\": 2.47,\n              \"h\": 0.9\n            },\n            {\n              \"id\": \"s4599\",\n              \"label\": \"4599 + \\u0394lpxC (lipid A-deficient rescue)\",\n              \"shape\": \"parallelogram\",\n              \"x\": 6.64,\n              \"y\": 1.8,\n              \"w\": 2.47,\n              \"h\": 0.9\n            }\n          ],","numLines":200,"startLine":1,"totalLines":817}}}
