{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01JMFEVnkBPFm3HtrQEUSnnk","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Report: The regulatory and proteomic architecture of Δ*fur*-permitted lipid A loss in *Caulobacter crescentus*\n2\t\n3\t## Key Findings\n4\t\n5\t![Master synthesis figure — 4-panel summary of all five mechanism layers](figures/NB07_synthesis_master.png)\n6\t\n7\t### Finding 1 — Δ*fur* Δ*sspB* is a dual-release switch (Δ*fur* arm statistically supported; Δ*sspB* arm hypothesis-only)\n8\t\n9\tThe 4584-vs-4580 contrast (Δ*fur* Δ*sspB* Δ*rsaA* vs Δ*rsaA*) correlates with Leaden 2018's Δ*fur* signal at Spearman ρ = 0.315, p = 2.08e-03 over 93 Leaden Δ*fur* DEGs, with 71% sign concordance — confirming Fur derepression as a major driver. 53 of those 93 Leaden Δ*fur* DEGs are *buffered* in our data (logFC ~0 in 4584-vs-4580 despite -5 to -9 in Leaden), and the buffered set is dominated by the **cbb3 / cyd / *fix*-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon** (CCNA_01466-01476, *ccoNOPQ*, *cydCDA*, *fixG/H/I*). The transcript-level Δ*sspB* buffering effect on the respiratory chain is real, but **whether these specific genes are mechanistically critical for the Δ*lpxc* rescue is not established by the fitness data alone** (see Finding 2 and Limitations). The \"dual-release switch\" framing should be read as: Δ*fur*-arm = supported; Δ*sspB*-arm respiratory protection = plausible hypothesis, not statistically distinguished from genome background.\n10\t\n11\t*(Notebook: 01_leaden2018_fur_signature.ipynb)*\n12\t\n13\t### Finding 2 — Fur-released TBDT subset shows marginal enrichment for envelope-stress phenotypes; SspB-buffered set does NOT exceed background (H2 partially supported)\n14\t\n15\tCaulobacter RB-TnSeq fitness data (`kescience_fitnessbrowser`, orgId=`Caulo`, 198 experiments) ranks the Fur-released gene sets by phenotypic importance under envelope stress (the iron-limitation arm could not be tested — zero iron-limitation experiments in the compendium; H2 was descoped to envelope-axis-only per the plan's preflight rule).\n16\t\n17\tThe **genome background** phenotype-bearing rate (|fitness *t*| > 4 in ≥ 2 envelope-stress experiments) is **33.25%** (n=3943 Caulobacter genes; K=1311 phenotype-bearing). The pre-registered ≥10% threshold sits below this background rate, so threshold-passing is by itself uninformative about *specific* mechanistic importance. Hypergeometric enrichment against the background:\n18\t\n19\t| Gene set | n | phenotype-bearing | % | Background-corrected enrichment | Verdict |\n20\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n21\t| Path A (concordant_strong, clean Fur signature) | 32 | 17 | 53.1% | **fold = 1.60×, p = 0.016** | marginally enriched |\n22\t| Path B (SspB-buffered, cbb3/*fix*-rich) | 26 | 9 | 34.6% | fold = 1.04×, p = 0.515 | **indistinguishable from background** |\n23\t\n24\t**Path A** (Fur-released TBDTs and iron-uptake systems) shows marginal but real enrichment, with **ChvT (CCNA_03108)** \\|*t*\\| = 43.7 under envelope stress and other Fur-derepressed TBDTs (CCNA_02910, 00210, 02048, 00028) \\|*t*\\| 9-28. **Path B (the SspB-buffered respiratory chain) shows no enrichment relative to background.** The Δ*sspB*-buffering effect on these genes is real at the transcript level (NB01) but the fitness data do not provide independent support that this specific set is mechanistically critical for the Δ*lpxc* rescue. The \"respiratory ATP required\" framing in earlier drafts of this report has been demoted from established finding to working hypothesis.\n25\t\n26\t*(Notebook: 02_caulo_fitness_ranking.ipynb)*\n27\t\n28\t### Finding 3 — ChvI engages in two phases: early cooperator + late consequence (H1 supported)\n29\t\n30\tThe published ChvI regulons (Stein 2021 + Quintero-Yanes 2022; union = 488 ChvI-induced genes in the tested universe) partition into three disjoint sets:\n31\t- **unique-to-early** — 20 genes induced in 4584-vs-4580 but NOT 4599-vs-4584; includes the lasso peptide cyclase CCNA_02794 +8.6, the ApbE iron-sulfur cluster repair protein +3.8, and *imuB* SOS DNA polymerase +1.5 (corroborating Leaden 2018's SOS-activation finding under Δ*fur*).\n32\t- **both phases** — 10 genes induced in both contrasts (cooperative continuation); includes **ChvI itself (CCNA_00237, logFC +1.45 in 4584-vs-4580)** — autoregulation — the SIMPL family CCNA_02378 (+1.9 → +3.9) and the **amelogenin/CpxP-related CCNA_03997** (CpxP being the *E. coli* envelope-stress chaperone partner of CpxA).\n33\t- **late-consequence** — 49 genes induced *only* after lipid A is lost in 4599-vs-4584, including the **LolA-family OM lipoprotein carrier CCNA_03820 (+2.89)** — exactly the gene Uchendu et al. 2026 showed induced under Δ*spt* (sphingolipid loss); seeing it under Δ*lpxc* (lipid A loss) too means LolA is a generic OM-stress response in Caulobacter — plus the **Pal-like CCNA_00784 (+2.08)** of the Tol-Pal envelope-integrity complex, *zot*-like membrane perturber, *osrP* stress protein, multiple TBDTs.\n34\t\n35\t(Note: the \"early\" label in earlier drafts conflated the 20 unique-to-early genes with the 10 both-phase genes, summing to 30. The disjoint partition is 20 + 10 + 49 = 79 ChvI-induced genes engaged in our data.)\n36\t\n37\tPre-registered phase-structure threshold (≥10 genes per cohort) passes strongly. The reframed SigU coherence check on the late cohort returned 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment — below the 50% relaxed criterion. **Caulobacter SigU is uncharacterized in the published literature** (PaperBLAST scout returned zero substantive snippets for CCNA_02977); the late cohort's biological coherence cannot be validated against a non-existent gold standard. Phase-structure half of H1 is supported; SigU-as-driver is partial pending future SigU-induction RNA-seq.\n38\t\n39\t*(Notebook: 03_chvi_phase_partition_sigU.ipynb)*\n40\t\n41\t### Finding 4 — Sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive; transcript-level Lpt apparatus stable/up with protein-level discordance; CtpA rejected at pre-registered bar; *lptC2* pilot observation (H3 partially supported)\n42\t\n43\tH3 was tested against three pre-registered sub-claims. The CtpA verdict has been corrected from earlier draft \"BORDERLINE\" to **REJECTED at the pre-registered bar** in response to adversarial review:\n44\t\n45\t| Sub-claim | Result | Verdict |\n46\t|---|---|---|\n47\t| CtpA / CCNA_03113 upregulation in 4599-vs-4584 | logFC +0.58, pvalue=0.048, FDR=0.109 (transcript); NOT detected in OM proteome | **REJECTED at pre-registered bar** |\n48\t| Sphingolipid biosynthesis pathway constitutive (not induced) | 0/6 biosynthesis genes UP; *spt* DOWN -0.64 FDR 0.002; *sphk* DOWN -0.40 FDR 0.02 | SUPPORTED strongly |\n49\t| Canonical Lpt apparatus maintained (transcript) | 0 components DOWN at transcript; **MsbA-like CCNA_00307 +0.89 FDR 0.01**, **LptC-related CCNA_03716 +0.56 FDR 0.005** | SUPPORTED at transcript level (but see protein-level discordance below) |\n50\t\n51\tThe pre-registered CtpA BORDERLINE criterion required *both* `0.05 < pvalue < 0.15` AND protein detected. Observed pvalue = 0.048 (fails lower bound), and CtpA was not detected in OM proteome — so BORDERLINE was *not* met. The notebook itself outputs `CTPA VERDICT: REJECTED`. The cumulative 4599-vs-4580 contrast (logFC +0.76, FDR 0.035) is significant but **conflates Δ*fur* + Δ*sspB* and Δ*lpxc* effects**, whereas the pre-registered 4599-vs-4584 contrast was designed to isolate the Δ*lpxc*-specific response. The cumulative finding is reported here as a supplemental observation consistent with CtpA being Fur-regulated; it is not evidence for lipid-A-loss-driven CtpA induction.\n52\t\n53\t**Protein-level discordance for the Lpt apparatus.** Of the canonical Lpt components actually detected in the OM proteome — **LptD** and **LptE** — both *decline* in the rescued strain relative to the intermediate AND to WT baseline:\n54\t\n55\t| Protein | log2(4672/4659) | log2(4672/4580) |\n56\t|---|---|---|\n57\t| LptD (CCNA_01760) | **−0.47** | −0.62 |\n58\t| LptE (CCNA_03866) | **−0.78** | −0.68 |\n59\t\n60\tMsbA-like CCNA_00307 was detected only in the rescued strain (abundance 300 in 4672, NaN in others) — direction relative to WT is uncomputable. **The transcript upregulation of MsbA-like and LptC-related is consistent with the Uchendu 2026 shared-component model, but the two Lpt proteins directly measured go in the opposite direction.** Single-replicate OM proteome cannot resolve this; replicated proteomics are required to determine whether the canonical Lpt apparatus is functionally maintained, replaced, or downregulated at the protein level in the Δ*lpxc* state.\n61\t\n62\t***lptC2* pilot observation (single replicate, requires replication)**: the Uchendu 2026 Caulobacter-specific sphingolipid IM transporter CCNA_01226 shows transcript -0.60 (FDR 0.034) but PROTEIN log2(4672/4659) = +1.08. **Importantly, lptC2 protein was already DOWN −0.42 log2 in the intermediate strain (4659/4580), so the net protein change in the rescued strain versus WT baseline is +0.66 log2 (≈1.58×), not +1.08.** The 4672/4659 step is partially a recovery from a prior decrease. CCNA_01217 (Zik 2022 sphingolipid biosynthesis required for CHIR-090 tolerance) shows protein log2 = +0.77 in 4672 vs 4659 (or +0.74 vs WT). These are single-replicate observations consistent with — but not statistically establishing — post-transcriptional stabilization of sphingolipid-transport machinery when LpxC competition for the shared LptB ATPase disappears. Status: *suggestive pilot observation requiring replicated proteomics*.\n63\t\n64\t*(Notebook: 04_sphingolipid_lpt_panel.ipynb)*\n65\t\n66\t### Finding 5 — Peptidoglycan remodeling: specific lytic engagement + broad basal shutdown (H4 supported; framing tightened post-review)\n67\t\n68\tThe pre-registered PG-remodeling gene set (53 loci, locked before DE analysis) shows **28 genes meeting the H4 threshold** (≥3 required) — 25 transcript-significant in 4599-vs-4584 (FDR<0.05) plus 6 OM-proteome \\|log2\\|>1, deduplicated to 28 unique loci. Direction is **predominantly downregulation (20 DOWN) punctuated by specific inductions (5 UP transcript + 3 UP protein)** — earlier draft framing of \"coordinated bidirectional reorganization\" overstated the bidirectionality. Two members of the gene set are likely regex false-positives (CCNA_00565 γ-glutamyltranspeptidase — a glutathione enzyme, matched on \"transpeptidase\"; CCNA_01833 glucosylceramidase — a ceramide enzyme, matched because \"ceramidase\" contains \"amidase\"). Their inclusion does not change the H4 verdict (well above the ≥3 threshold) but they are flagged here so downstream interpretation does not rest on them.\n69\t\n70\t**UP (specific activities engaged in 4599)**:\n71\t- **SdpA CCNA_01252 +4.8 log2 protein** — soluble lytic murein transglycosylase\n72\t- **Pal CCNA_00784 +2.08 transcript AND +2.84 protein** — peptidoglycan-associated OM lipoprotein (Tol-Pal envelope-integrity complex). **Also a top late-cohort ChvI gene from NB03** — strong cross-notebook convergence.\n73\t- PleA, PbpX (multimodular transpeptidase-transglycosylase), CCNA_01754 transglycosylase-associated\n74\t\n75\t**DOWN (basal division/elongation machinery)**:\n76\t- FtsI penicillin-binding (cell division)\n77\t- **PbpZ -1.08 transcript, PbpC -1.15 protein, D,D-transpeptidase -1.27 protein** (cell elongation)\n78\t- *murD*, *mviN/murJ* biosynthesis/flippase\n79\t- LdpD/E/F M23-family endopeptidases (multiple)\n80\t- *amiC* amidase, *ripA* hydrolase\n81\t- Membrane-bound transglycosylase A **-2.47 log2 protein**\n82\t\n83\tInterpretation: the cell shuts down normal division/elongation PG turnover while engaging a specific subset of lytic transglycosylases and Pal-Tol anchoring factors. **Pal up at both transcript and protein** is the most mechanistically suggestive: Tol-Pal normally relies on LPS-mediated Mg²⁺-bridged OM-LPS-Pal stacking for OM-IM cohesion; with no LPS, the cell upregulates Pal to compensate via direct protein anchoring.\n84\t\n85\t*(Notebook: 05_pg_remodeling.ipynb)*\n86\t\n87\t### Finding 6 — The sphingolipid pathway and ChvG-ChvI are uniquely *Caulobacter*: structural unavailability explains species specificity\n88\t\n89\tComparative PaperBLAST presence/absence across *C. crescentus*, *A. baumannii*, *N. meningitidis*, *M. catarrhalis* shows that the sphingolipid biosynthesis pathway is **Caulobacter-unique**: *spt* (serine palmitoyltransferase), *bcerS* (bacterial ceramide synthase), and sphingosine kinase are absent in the other three species. **ChvG-ChvI is also Caulobacter-restricted** — consistent with the published alphaproteobacterial restriction of this envelope-stress regulatory circuit (Greenwich et al. 2023). The other three species cannot use the Caulobacter Δ*fur* + anionic-sphingolipid rescue because they lack the substitute lipid machinery. The published alternative routes align with what each species' genome encodes: A. baumannii has PBP1A and Ld-transpeptidases for the Kang 2021 PG-remodeling route; N. meningitidis has a large capsule biosynthesis locus (9 PaperBLAST hits) for the Steeghs 2001 capsule-substitution route; A. baumannii and N. meningitidis have late acyltransferases (lpxX/lpxL, 8 and 3 hits) for the Gao 2008 acylation-truncation route. *Caulobacter has none of these alternatives* — the sphingolipid substitution is its only viable path.\n90\t\n91\t*(Notebook: 06_comparative_species.ipynb)*\n92\t\n93\t## Results\n94\t\n95\t### Hypothesis scorecard\n96\t\n97\t| Hypothesis | Sub-claim | Pre-registered threshold | Observed | Verdict |\n98\t|---|---|---|---|---|\n99\t| **H1** ChvI cooperator + consequence | Phase structure | ≥10 genes per cohort | unique-early=20, both=10, late=49 | PASS |\n100\t| **H1** | SigU drives late cohort | ≥50% envelope/transport/regulator + Fisher p<1e-3 | 24.5% (literature gap, reframed) | PARTIAL |\n101\t| **H2** Critical Fur regulon subset | Path A (concordant_strong) | ≥10% phenotype-bearing | 17/32 = 53% (fold 1.60×, p=0.016 vs background 33.25%) | PASS (marginal enrichment) |\n102\t| **H2** | Path B (SspB-buffered) | ≥10% phenotype-bearing | 9/26 = 35% (fold 1.04×, p=0.515 — NOT enriched vs background) | THRESHOLD-PASSED but **not enriched**; arm demoted to hypothesis |\n103\t| **H2 (preflight)** | iron-limitation experiments ≥3 | ≥3 in Caulo FB | 0 | FAIL → descoped to envelope-only |\n104\t| **H3** Sphingolipid + Lpt repurposing | CtpA upregulation in 4599-vs-4584 | FDR<0.05 OR ≥2× protein; BORDERLINE = 0.05<pvalue<0.15 AND protein detected | logFC +0.58, pvalue=0.048, FDR=0.109; protein NOT detected | **REJECTED at pre-registered bar** (cumulative 4599-vs-4580 FDR=0.035 noted as supplemental) |\n105\t| **H3** | Sphingolipid pathway constitutive | 0 biosynthesis gene UP at FDR<0.05 | 0 up; spt/sphk slightly DOWN | PASS strongly |\n106\t| **H3** | Canonical Lpt maintained (transcript) | 0 components DOWN at FDR<0.05 | 0 down; MsbA-like and LptC-related UP at transcript | PASS at transcript |\n107\t| **H3** | Canonical Lpt at protein level (post-hoc check) | (not pre-registered) | LptD log2(4672/4659) = −0.47; LptE = −0.78 | DISCORDANT with transcript; single replicate |\n108\t| **H3** | (pilot) *lptC2* protein induction | (post-hoc) | transcript -0.60 (FDR 0.034); protein log2 +1.08 vs intermediate, +0.66 vs WT — single replicate | PILOT OBSERVATION (needs replication) |\n109\t| **H4** PG remodeling | ≥3 enzymes engaged | ≥3 FDR<0.05 transcript OR \\|log2\\|>1 protein | 28 unique loci (25 transcript, 6 protein) | PASS strongly |\n110\t| **H4** | (post-hoc) Pal-Tol engagement | (post-hoc) | Pal +2.08 transcript, +2.84 protein | NOTABLE FINDING — interpretation see I5 reframe |\n111\t| **Comparative** | Sphingolipid pathway Caulobacter-unique | (PaperBLAST presence/absence + NB06b NCBI confirmation) | spt: PB(7,0,0,0) + NCBI(7,0,0,0); cerR: PB(1,1,0,0) + NCBI(6,0,0,0) | **CONFIRMED by NCBI annotation in NB06b** + independent literature (Olea-Ozuna 2020/2024) |\n112\t| **Comparative** | ChvG-ChvI alphaproteobacterial only | (PaperBLAST + NB06b NCBI) | NCBI: ChvG(5,0,0,0), ChvI(6,0,0,0) | **CONFIRMED** (consistent with Greenwich 2023) |\n113\t| **Method check** | NB06 PaperBLAST false-negative rate | (NB06b NCBI cross-check) | LpxA/C/D/B/K all 0 in PB Cc, 11-18 in NCBI Cc | **PB false-negative rate ~80% for Caulobacter lipid A genes**; biological claims unaffected because they depend on absences in *comparator* species, where NCBI confirms |\n114\t| **H2 (recalibrated)** | Path A hypergeometric enrichment vs background | (NB02b: p<0.05 AND fold≥1.5×) | fold=1.60×, p=0.016 | SUPPORTED |\n115\t| **H2 (recalibrated)** | Path B hypergeometric enrichment vs background | (NB02b: p<0.05 AND fold≥1.5×) | fold=1.04×, p=0.515 | NOT SUPPORTED |\n116\t\n117\t### Phase A — orientation findings (NB00) that motivated the analysis plan\n118\t\n119\t![Sphingolipid locus heatmap from orientation notebook — neither induced nor strongly suppressed across the strain series](figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png)\n120\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57c7cd12-ce3b-4c50-865d-721855d63587","uuid":"7c23bb66-1a64-4548-9441-f975b62e89cb","timestamp":"2026-06-08T23:42:56.079Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/REPORT.md","content":"# Report: The regulatory and proteomic architecture of Δ*fur*-permitted lipid A loss in *Caulobacter crescentus*\n\n## Key Findings\n\n![Master synthesis figure — 4-panel summary of all five mechanism layers](figures/NB07_synthesis_master.png)\n\n### Finding 1 — Δ*fur* Δ*sspB* is a dual-release switch (Δ*fur* arm statistically supported; Δ*sspB* arm hypothesis-only)\n\nThe 4584-vs-4580 contrast (Δ*fur* Δ*sspB* Δ*rsaA* vs Δ*rsaA*) correlates with Leaden 2018's Δ*fur* signal at Spearman ρ = 0.315, p = 2.08e-03 over 93 Leaden Δ*fur* DEGs, with 71% sign concordance — confirming Fur derepression as a major driver. 53 of those 93 Leaden Δ*fur* DEGs are *buffered* in our data (logFC ~0 in 4584-vs-4580 despite -5 to -9 in Leaden), and the buffered set is dominated by the **cbb3 / cyd / *fix*-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon** (CCNA_01466-01476, *ccoNOPQ*, *cydCDA*, *fixG/H/I*). The transcript-level Δ*sspB* buffering effect on the respiratory chain is real, but **whether these specific genes are mechanistically critical for the Δ*lpxc* rescue is not established by the fitness data alone** (see Finding 2 and Limitations). The \"dual-release switch\" framing should be read as: Δ*fur*-arm = supported; Δ*sspB*-arm respiratory protection = plausible hypothesis, not statistically distinguished from genome background.\n\n*(Notebook: 01_leaden2018_fur_signature.ipynb)*\n\n### Finding 2 — Fur-released TBDT subset shows marginal enrichment for envelope-stress phenotypes; SspB-buffered set does NOT exceed background (H2 partially supported)\n\nCaulobacter RB-TnSeq fitness data (`kescience_fitnessbrowser`, orgId=`Caulo`, 198 experiments) ranks the Fur-released gene sets by phenotypic importance under envelope stress (the iron-limitation arm could not be tested — zero iron-limitation experiments in the compendium; H2 was descoped to envelope-axis-only per the plan's preflight rule).\n\nThe **genome background** phenotype-bearing rate (|fitness *t*| > 4 in ≥ 2 envelope-stress experiments) is **33.25%** (n=3943 Caulobacter genes; K=1311 phenotype-bearing). The pre-registered ≥10% threshold sits below this background rate, so threshold-passing is by itself uninformative about *specific* mechanistic importance. Hypergeometric enrichment against the background:\n\n| Gene set | n | phenotype-bearing | % | Background-corrected enrichment | Verdict |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Path A (concordant_strong, clean Fur signature) | 32 | 17 | 53.1% | **fold = 1.60×, p = 0.016** | marginally enriched |\n| Path B (SspB-buffered, cbb3/*fix*-rich) | 26 | 9 | 34.6% | fold = 1.04×, p = 0.515 | **indistinguishable from background** |\n\n**Path A** (Fur-released TBDTs and iron-uptake systems) shows marginal but real enrichment, with **ChvT (CCNA_03108)** \\|*t*\\| = 43.7 under envelope stress and other Fur-derepressed TBDTs (CCNA_02910, 00210, 02048, 00028) \\|*t*\\| 9-28. **Path B (the SspB-buffered respiratory chain) shows no enrichment relative to background.** The Δ*sspB*-buffering effect on these genes is real at the transcript level (NB01) but the fitness data do not provide independent support that this specific set is mechanistically critical for the Δ*lpxc* rescue. The \"respiratory ATP required\" framing in earlier drafts of this report has been demoted from established finding to working hypothesis.\n\n*(Notebook: 02_caulo_fitness_ranking.ipynb)*\n\n### Finding 3 — ChvI engages in two phases: early cooperator + late consequence (H1 supported)\n\nThe published ChvI regulons (Stein 2021 + Quintero-Yanes 2022; union = 488 ChvI-induced genes in the tested universe) partition into three disjoint sets:\n- **unique-to-early** — 20 genes induced in 4584-vs-4580 but NOT 4599-vs-4584; includes the lasso peptide cyclase CCNA_02794 +8.6, the ApbE iron-sulfur cluster repair protein +3.8, and *imuB* SOS DNA polymerase +1.5 (corroborating Leaden 2018's SOS-activation finding under Δ*fur*).\n- **both phases** — 10 genes induced in both contrasts (cooperative continuation); includes **ChvI itself (CCNA_00237, logFC +1.45 in 4584-vs-4580)** — autoregulation — the SIMPL family CCNA_02378 (+1.9 → +3.9) and the **amelogenin/CpxP-related CCNA_03997** (CpxP being the *E. coli* envelope-stress chaperone partner of CpxA).\n- **late-consequence** — 49 genes induced *only* after lipid A is lost in 4599-vs-4584, including the **LolA-family OM lipoprotein carrier CCNA_03820 (+2.89)** — exactly the gene Uchendu et al. 2026 showed induced under Δ*spt* (sphingolipid loss); seeing it under Δ*lpxc* (lipid A loss) too means LolA is a generic OM-stress response in Caulobacter — plus the **Pal-like CCNA_00784 (+2.08)** of the Tol-Pal envelope-integrity complex, *zot*-like membrane perturber, *osrP* stress protein, multiple TBDTs.\n\n(Note: the \"early\" label in earlier drafts conflated the 20 unique-to-early genes with the 10 both-phase genes, summing to 30. The disjoint partition is 20 + 10 + 49 = 79 ChvI-induced genes engaged in our data.)\n\nPre-registered phase-structure threshold (≥10 genes per cohort) passes strongly. The reframed SigU coherence check on the late cohort returned 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment — below the 50% relaxed criterion. **Caulobacter SigU is uncharacterized in the published literature** (PaperBLAST scout returned zero substantive snippets for CCNA_02977); the late cohort's biological coherence cannot be validated against a non-existent gold standard. Phase-structure half of H1 is supported; SigU-as-driver is partial pending future SigU-induction RNA-seq.\n\n*(Notebook: 03_chvi_phase_partition_sigU.ipynb)*\n\n### Finding 4 — Sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive; transcript-level Lpt apparatus stable/up with protein-level discordance; CtpA rejected at pre-registered bar; *lptC2* pilot observation (H3 partially supported)\n\nH3 was tested against three pre-registered sub-claims. The CtpA verdict has been corrected from earlier draft \"BORDERLINE\" to **REJECTED at the pre-registered bar** in response to adversarial review:\n\n| Sub-claim | Result | Verdict |\n|---|---|---|\n| CtpA / CCNA_03113 upregulation in 4599-vs-4584 | logFC +0.58, pvalue=0.048, FDR=0.109 (transcript); NOT detected in OM proteome | **REJECTED at pre-registered bar** |\n| Sphingolipid biosynthesis pathway constitutive (not induced) | 0/6 biosynthesis genes UP; *spt* DOWN -0.64 FDR 0.002; *sphk* DOWN -0.40 FDR 0.02 | SUPPORTED strongly |\n| Canonical Lpt apparatus maintained (transcript) | 0 components DOWN at transcript; **MsbA-like CCNA_00307 +0.89 FDR 0.01**, **LptC-related CCNA_03716 +0.56 FDR 0.005** | SUPPORTED at transcript level (but see protein-level discordance below) |\n\nThe pre-registered CtpA BORDERLINE criterion required *both* `0.05 < pvalue < 0.15` AND protein detected. Observed pvalue = 0.048 (fails lower bound), and CtpA was not detected in OM proteome — so BORDERLINE was *not* met. The notebook itself outputs `CTPA VERDICT: REJECTED`. The cumulative 4599-vs-4580 contrast (logFC +0.76, FDR 0.035) is significant but **conflates Δ*fur* + Δ*sspB* and Δ*lpxc* effects**, whereas the pre-registered 4599-vs-4584 contrast was designed to isolate the Δ*lpxc*-specific response. The cumulative finding is reported here as a supplemental observation consistent with CtpA being Fur-regulated; it is not evidence for lipid-A-loss-driven CtpA induction.\n\n**Protein-level discordance for the Lpt apparatus.** Of the canonical Lpt components actually detected in the OM proteome — **LptD** and **LptE** — both *decline* in the rescued strain relative to the intermediate AND to WT baseline:\n\n| Protein | log2(4672/4659) | log2(4672/4580) |\n|---|---|---|\n| LptD (CCNA_01760) | **−0.47** | −0.62 |\n| LptE (CCNA_03866) | **−0.78** | −0.68 |\n\nMsbA-like CCNA_00307 was detected only in the rescued strain (abundance 300 in 4672, NaN in others) — direction relative to WT is uncomputable. **The transcript upregulation of MsbA-like and LptC-related is consistent with the Uchendu 2026 shared-component model, but the two Lpt proteins directly measured go in the opposite direction.** Single-replicate OM proteome cannot resolve this; replicated proteomics are required to determine whether the canonical Lpt apparatus is functionally maintained, replaced, or downregulated at the protein level in the Δ*lpxc* state.\n\n***lptC2* pilot observation (single replicate, requires replication)**: the Uchendu 2026 Caulobacter-specific sphingolipid IM transporter CCNA_01226 shows transcript -0.60 (FDR 0.034) but PROTEIN log2(4672/4659) = +1.08. **Importantly, lptC2 protein was already DOWN −0.42 log2 in the intermediate strain (4659/4580), so the net protein change in the rescued strain versus WT baseline is +0.66 log2 (≈1.58×), not +1.08.** The 4672/4659 step is partially a recovery from a prior decrease. CCNA_01217 (Zik 2022 sphingolipid biosynthesis required for CHIR-090 tolerance) shows protein log2 = +0.77 in 4672 vs 4659 (or +0.74 vs WT). These are single-replicate observations consistent with — but not statistically establishing — post-transcriptional stabilization of sphingolipid-transport machinery when LpxC competition for the shared LptB ATPase disappears. Status: *suggestive pilot observation requiring replicated proteomics*.\n\n*(Notebook: 04_sphingolipid_lpt_panel.ipynb)*\n\n### Finding 5 — Peptidoglycan remodeling: specific lytic engagement + broad basal shutdown (H4 supported; framing tightened post-review)\n\nThe pre-registered PG-remodeling gene set (53 loci, locked before DE analysis) shows **28 genes meeting the H4 threshold** (≥3 required) — 25 transcript-significant in 4599-vs-4584 (FDR<0.05) plus 6 OM-proteome \\|log2\\|>1, deduplicated to 28 unique loci. Direction is **predominantly downregulation (20 DOWN) punctuated by specific inductions (5 UP transcript + 3 UP protein)** — earlier draft framing of \"coordinated bidirectional reorganization\" overstated the bidirectionality. Two members of the gene set are likely regex false-positives (CCNA_00565 γ-glutamyltranspeptidase — a glutathione enzyme, matched on \"transpeptidase\"; CCNA_01833 glucosylceramidase — a ceramide enzyme, matched because \"ceramidase\" contains \"amidase\"). Their inclusion does not change the H4 verdict (well above the ≥3 threshold) but they are flagged here so downstream interpretation does not rest on them.\n\n**UP (specific activities engaged in 4599)**:\n- **SdpA CCNA_01252 +4.8 log2 protein** — soluble lytic murein transglycosylase\n- **Pal CCNA_00784 +2.08 transcript AND +2.84 protein** — peptidoglycan-associated OM lipoprotein (Tol-Pal envelope-integrity complex). **Also a top late-cohort ChvI gene from NB03** — strong cross-notebook convergence.\n- PleA, PbpX (multimodular transpeptidase-transglycosylase), CCNA_01754 transglycosylase-associated\n\n**DOWN (basal division/elongation machinery)**:\n- FtsI penicillin-binding (cell division)\n- **PbpZ -1.08 transcript, PbpC -1.15 protein, D,D-transpeptidase -1.27 protein** (cell elongation)\n- *murD*, *mviN/murJ* biosynthesis/flippase\n- LdpD/E/F M23-family endopeptidases (multiple)\n- *amiC* amidase, *ripA* hydrolase\n- Membrane-bound transglycosylase A **-2.47 log2 protein**\n\nInterpretation: the cell shuts down normal division/elongation PG turnover while engaging a specific subset of lytic transglycosylases and Pal-Tol anchoring factors. **Pal up at both transcript and protein** is the most mechanistically suggestive: Tol-Pal normally relies on LPS-mediated Mg²⁺-bridged OM-LPS-Pal stacking for OM-IM cohesion; with no LPS, the cell upregulates Pal to compensate via direct protein anchoring.\n\n*(Notebook: 05_pg_remodeling.ipynb)*\n\n### Finding 6 — The sphingolipid pathway and ChvG-ChvI are uniquely *Caulobacter*: structural unavailability explains species specificity\n\nComparative PaperBLAST presence/absence across *C. crescentus*, *A. baumannii*, *N. meningitidis*, *M. catarrhalis* shows that the sphingolipid biosynthesis pathway is **Caulobacter-unique**: *spt* (serine palmitoyltransferase), *bcerS* (bacterial ceramide synthase), and sphingosine kinase are absent in the other three species. **ChvG-ChvI is also Caulobacter-restricted** — consistent with the published alphaproteobacterial restriction of this envelope-stress regulatory circuit (Greenwich et al. 2023). The other three species cannot use the Caulobacter Δ*fur* + anionic-sphingolipid rescue because they lack the substitute lipid machinery. The published alternative routes align with what each species' genome encodes: A. baumannii has PBP1A and Ld-transpeptidases for the Kang 2021 PG-remodeling route; N. meningitidis has a large capsule biosynthesis locus (9 PaperBLAST hits) for the Steeghs 2001 capsule-substitution route; A. baumannii and N. meningitidis have late acyltransferases (lpxX/lpxL, 8 and 3 hits) for the Gao 2008 acylation-truncation route. *Caulobacter has none of these alternatives* — the sphingolipid substitution is its only viable path.\n\n*(Notebook: 06_comparative_species.ipynb)*\n\n## Results\n\n### Hypothesis scorecard\n\n| Hypothesis | Sub-claim | Pre-registered threshold | Observed | Verdict |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **H1** ChvI cooperator + consequence | Phase structure | ≥10 genes per cohort | unique-early=20, both=10, late=49 | PASS |\n| **H1** | SigU drives late cohort | ≥50% envelope/transport/regulator + Fisher p<1e-3 | 24.5% (literature gap, reframed) | PARTIAL |\n| **H2** Critical Fur regulon subset | Path A (concordant_strong) | ≥10% phenotype-bearing | 17/32 = 53% (fold 1.60×, p=0.016 vs background 33.25%) | PASS (marginal enrichment) |\n| **H2** | Path B (SspB-buffered) | ≥10% phenotype-bearing | 9/26 = 35% (fold 1.04×, p=0.515 — NOT enriched vs background) | THRESHOLD-PASSED but **not enriched**; arm demoted to hypothesis |\n| **H2 (preflight)** | iron-limitation experiments ≥3 | ≥3 in Caulo FB | 0 | FAIL → descoped to envelope-only |\n| **H3** Sphingolipid + Lpt repurposing | CtpA upregulation in 4599-vs-4584 | FDR<0.05 OR ≥2× protein; BORDERLINE = 0.05<pvalue<0.15 AND protein detected | logFC +0.58, pvalue=0.048, FDR=0.109; protein NOT detected | **REJECTED at pre-registered bar** (cumulative 4599-vs-4580 FDR=0.035 noted as supplemental) |\n| **H3** | Sphingolipid pathway constitutive | 0 biosynthesis gene UP at FDR<0.05 | 0 up; spt/sphk slightly DOWN | PASS strongly |\n| **H3** | Canonical Lpt maintained (transcript) | 0 components DOWN at FDR<0.05 | 0 down; MsbA-like and LptC-related UP at transcript | PASS at transcript |\n| **H3** | Canonical Lpt at protein level (post-hoc check) | (not pre-registered) | LptD log2(4672/4659) = −0.47; LptE = −0.78 | DISCORDANT with transcript; single replicate |\n| **H3** | (pilot) *lptC2* protein induction | (post-hoc) | transcript -0.60 (FDR 0.034); protein log2 +1.08 vs intermediate, +0.66 vs WT — single replicate | PILOT OBSERVATION (needs replication) |\n| **H4** PG remodeling | ≥3 enzymes engaged | ≥3 FDR<0.05 transcript OR \\|log2\\|>1 protein | 28 unique loci (25 transcript, 6 protein) | PASS strongly |\n| **H4** | (post-hoc) Pal-Tol engagement | (post-hoc) | Pal +2.08 transcript, +2.84 protein | NOTABLE FINDING — interpretation see I5 reframe |\n| **Comparative** | Sphingolipid pathway Caulobacter-unique | (PaperBLAST presence/absence + NB06b NCBI confirmation) | spt: PB(7,0,0,0) + NCBI(7,0,0,0); cerR: PB(1,1,0,0) + NCBI(6,0,0,0) | **CONFIRMED by NCBI annotation in NB06b** + independent literature (Olea-Ozuna 2020/2024) |\n| **Comparative** | ChvG-ChvI alphaproteobacterial only | (PaperBLAST + NB06b NCBI) | NCBI: ChvG(5,0,0,0), ChvI(6,0,0,0) | **CONFIRMED** (consistent with Greenwich 2023) |\n| **Method check** | NB06 PaperBLAST false-negative rate | (NB06b NCBI cross-check) | LpxA/C/D/B/K all 0 in PB Cc, 11-18 in NCBI Cc | **PB false-negative rate ~80% for Caulobacter lipid A genes**; biological claims unaffected because they depend on absences in *comparator* species, where NCBI confirms |\n| **H2 (recalibrated)** | Path A hypergeometric enrichment vs background | (NB02b: p<0.05 AND fold≥1.5×) | fold=1.60×, p=0.016 | SUPPORTED |\n| **H2 (recalibrated)** | Path B hypergeometric enrichment vs background | (NB02b: p<0.05 AND fold≥1.5×) | fold=1.04×, p=0.515 | NOT SUPPORTED |\n\n### Phase A — orientation findings (NB00) that motivated the analysis plan\n\n![Sphingolipid locus heatmap from orientation notebook — neither induced nor strongly suppressed across the strain series](figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png)\n","numLines":120,"startLine":1,"totalLines":377}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01C92LTACVU9FyUrJk1z57nX","type":"tool_result","content":"200\t          ],\n201\t          \"edges\": [\n202\t            {\n203\t              \"from\": \"s4580\",\n204\t              \"to\": \"s4584\",\n205\t              \"kind\": \"straight\",\n206\t              \"label\": \"4584 vs 4580 = Fur arm\"\n207\t            },\n208\t            {\n209\t              \"from\": \"s4584\",\n210\t              \"to\": \"s4599\",\n211\t              \"kind\": \"straight\",\n212\t              \"label\": \"4599 vs 4584 = \\u0394lpxC arm\"\n213\t            }\n214\t          ]\n215\t        },\n216\t        \"step_caption\": [\n217\t          \"Baseline: \\u0394rsaA removes surface layer; Fur/SspB intact\",\n218\t          \"\\u0394fur + \\u0394sspB: dual-release switch; 4584-vs-4580 = Fur arm\",\n219\t          \"\\u0394lpxC: lipid A-deficient; Zik 2022 \\u0394fur required precondition\"\n220\t        ]\n221\t      },\n222\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"Before any transcriptomics, the strain-series logic must be clear \\u2014 every expression contrast in this talk derives from three genotypes, and the biological meaning of each contrast depends on understanding what each deletion contributes.\\n\\nStrain 4580 carries \\u0394rsaA, which removes the crystalline S-layer protein that normally dominates the Caulobacter outer membrane. This cleans up the transcriptomic and proteomic background \\u2014 the S-layer's extreme expression would otherwise mask subtler signals \\u2014 while leaving Fur, SspB, and lipid A synthesis fully intact. Strain 4580 is the denominator in every comparison shown in this talk.\\n\\nStrain 4584 adds \\u0394fur and \\u0394sspB on top of the 4580 background. \\u0394fur constitutively releases the Fur regulon: TonB-dependent transporters, iron-uptake systems, and iron-storage proteins that Fur normally represses under iron-replete conditions. \\u0394sspB removes the ClpXP adaptor that degrades SspB-tagged substrates; in Caulobacter this protects the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon at the transcript level \\u2014 visible as the orange buffered cluster on the concordance scatter on the next slide. Critically, strain 4584 is lipid A-replete: the organism grows normally with a full outer membrane. The 4584-vs-4580 contrast is the clean readout of the combined \\u0394fur + \\u0394sspB release, measured without the confound of lipid A loss.\\n\\nStrain 4599 adds \\u0394lpxC to the 4584 background, deleting the committed step in lipid A biosynthesis entirely. Zik et al. 2022 (PMID 35649364) established that this genotype is viable only in a \\u0394fur background \\u2014 Fur-intact strains with \\u0394lpxC are inviable. The 4599-vs-4584 contrast captures the \\u0394lpxC-specific envelope response layered on the Fur-set state, and that contrast is the substrate for substories S3 and S4.\\n\\nTwo design caveats belong here. First, the outer membrane proteome is single-replicate per strain. REPORT \\u00a7Limitations states: \\\"OM proteome is single-replicate per strain \\u2014 no per-protein statistics; only direction is interpretable.\\\" Proteomics in this talk are direction-only observations throughout; transcript-level DE (edgeR) is the statistically replicated layer. Second, both proteome contrasts involve the Ryan-lab strains in the \\u0394rsaA background, which may differ from the NA1000 background Leaden used \\u2014 a source of some of the unexplained variance in the concordance \\u03c1. The next slide presents the core concordance result and makes this variance interpretable.\",\n223\t      \"id\": 6,\n224\t      \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n225\t      \"position\": 6\n226\t    },\n227\t    {\n228\t      \"id\": 7,\n229\t      \"position\": 7,\n230\t      \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n231\t      \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n232\t      \"content\": {\n233\t        \"title\": \"Spearman \\u03c1=0.315 (p=2.08e-03, 71% sign concordance) confirms Fur derepression as a major component of our signal (n=93 Leaden DEGs)\",\n234\t        \"figure\": \"figures/NB01_fur_signature_scatter.png\",\n235\t        \"caption\": \"Leaden \\u0394fur logFC vs our 4584-vs-4580 logFC; concordant_strong in dark blue, SspB-buffered set in orange, discordant in red; n=93 \\u0394fur DEGs, Spearman \\u03c1=0.315, p=2.08e-03.\",\n236\t        \"data_source\": \"Leaden 2018 (PMID 30210482); NB01_leaden2018_fur_signature.ipynb cell 5\"\n237\t      },\n238\t      \"speaker_notes_seed\": \"This scatter is the central evidence for S1\\u2019s driver claim. X-axis: Leaden 2018 \\u0394fur logFC across 93 DEGs (PMID 30210482, supp. Table 2). Y-axis: our 4584-vs-4580 logFC for the same 93 genes. Spearman \\u03c1=0.315, p=2.08e-03, 71% sign concordance: REPORT \\u00a7Finding 1 frames this as \\u2018confirming Fur derepression as a major component of our signal\\u2019 \\u2014 not the sole driver, not a full explanation. The concordant-strong cluster (dark blue, top-right) shows amplified derepression relative to Leaden; HutA at +10.5 vs Leaden\\u2019s +2.2 is the extreme outlier reflecting the combined dual-release effect. The orange buffered cluster (n=53) near y\\u22480 spans Leaden\\u2019s full \\u22129 to \\u22125 range \\u2014 \\u0394sspB is shielding the cbb3/fix respiratory operon at the transcript level.\\n\\nThis slide claims Fur derepression is a major component of our signal. It does NOT yet claim the signal is constitutive rather than iron-status \\u2014 that discrimination is on the next slide (slide 8), where Leaden\\u2019s own iron-limitation comparison and the Zik 2022 genetic anchoring actually appear. For a \\u2018\\u03c1=0.315 is modest\\u2019 challenge: this is one of several converging lines of evidence, deliberately scoped.\",\n239\t      \"evidence_anchors\": [\n240\t        {\n241\t          \"kind\": \"report_section\",\n242\t          \"ref\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Finding 1\"\n243\t        },\n244\t        {\n245\t          \"kind\": \"report_section\",\n246\t          \"ref\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Literature Context (Leaden 2018)\"\n247\t        }\n248\t      ],\n249\t      \"revision_log\": [\n250\t        {\n251\t          \"revised_at\": \"2026-06-08T00:00:00Z\",\n252\t          \"finding_id\": \"F001\",\n253\t          \"finding_class\": \"register_drift\",\n254\t          \"summary\": \"Removed 'constitutive derepression' from title (claim belongs on slide 8 with the iron-discrimination evidence, not here); replaced with 'Fur derepression as a major component of our signal' (verbatim REPORT \\u00a7Literature Context, Leaden 2018 entry); added p=2.08e-03 and 71% sign concordance inline so the \\u03c1=0.315 claim is self-hedged; caption and data_source unchanged; speaker notes updated to make the constitutive-vs-iron hand-off to slide 8 explicit.\"\n255\t        }\n256\t      ]\n257\t    },\n258\t    {\n259\t      \"layout\": \"claim_evidence\",\n260\t      \"content\": {\n261\t        \"title\": \"Constitutive \\u0394fur derepression, not iron limitation, sets the permissive envelope state\",\n262\t        \"bullets\": [\n263\t          \"Leaden \\u0394fur-vs-iron-limitation: two responses are correlated but distinct \\u2014 signal is consistent with constitutive Fur allele derepression rather than an iron-status readout (single PYE-rich growth condition; multi-condition replication pending)\",\n264\t          \"53/93 Leaden \\u0394fur DEGs buffered in our \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB data \\u2014 dominated by the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ respiratory operon (CCNA_01466\\u201301476: ccoNOPQ, cydCDA, fixGHI) \\u2014 SspB masks this arm at the transcript level\",\n265\t          \"Zik 2022 (PMID 35649364): \\u0394lpxc viability requires \\u0394fur; 'Fur-regulated processes, not iron status per se, underlie the ability to survive when lipid A synthesis is blocked'\"\n266\t        ],\n267\t        \"figure\": \"figures/NB01_leaden_iron_vs_fur.png\",\n268\t        \"figure_caption\": \"Leaden 2018 internal: \\u0394fur vs iron-limitation logFC across the DEG set; responses are correlated but non-identical, consistent with constitutive Fur derepression rather than an iron-status readout.\",\n269\t        \"citations\": [\n270\t          \"Leaden2018\",\n271\t          \"Zik2022\"\n272\t        ]\n273\t      },\n274\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"This slide closes S1 with three converging pieces of evidence. Together they rule out iron limitation as the primary explanation for our signal and establish \\u0394fur as a genetic necessity for lipid A-loss viability \\u2014 not a correlate of low iron availability.\\n\\nThe grounding for the first piece comes from inside Leaden's own 2018 paper. Leaden measured both a \\u0394fur transcriptome and an iron-limitation transcriptome \\u2014 induced by 2,2'-dipyridyl chelation \\u2014 in the same C. crescentus NA1000 background. Comparing those two logFC axes directly, the figure shows the responses overlap but are not identical: the \\u0394fur genetic response includes gene movements that iron chelation alone does not produce. This non-identity, documented within a single paper and single genetic background, is Leaden's own internal evidence that constitutive \\u0394fur allele derepression is a biologically distinct state from iron-starvation response.\\n\\nThe second bullet makes the SspB arm concrete at the gene level. Of the 93 Leaden \\u0394fur DEGs, 53 are buffered in our \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB data \\u2014 near-zero logFC in our strain despite logFC \\u22125 to \\u22129 in Leaden. These 53 are dominated by the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon: CCNA_01466\\u201301476, encoding ccoNOPQ, cydCDA, fixGHI. \\u0394sspB protects this operon at the transcript level. Whether that protection is mechanistically critical for the \\u0394lpxc rescue is precisely what S2 tests with Caulobacter Fitness Browser enrichment analysis, so the speaker should name this as the bridge to S2 rather than claiming it here.\\n\\nThe third piece is the genetic anchor from Zik et al. 2022 (PMID 35649364). Their suppressor genetics established that \\u0394lpxc rescue requires the \\u0394fur allele. REPORT \\u00a7Literature Context quotes their language directly: \\\"Alterations in Fur-regulated processes, rather than iron status per se, underlie the ability to survive when lipid A synthesis is blocked.\\\" That genetic necessity \\u2014 \\u0394fur required, not merely correlated \\u2014 is the chain the rest of this talk pulls on.\\n\\nThe scope caveat on the iron-discrimination result must be stated plainly: REPORT \\u00a7Limitations names this as a single-condition scope boundary. The Leaden iron-limitation comparison was performed in the NA1000 background under dipyridyl chelation \\u2014 not in our Ryan-lab strain under our growth conditions. Whether the \\u0394fur-vs-iron-limitation distinction holds in magnitude or gene-membership under minimal medium or bipyridyl chelation in our strain background is untested. This is directional support \\u2014 consistent with constitutive derepression \\u2014 not a multi-condition proof. Iron-limitation experiments are also absent from the Caulobacter Fitness Browser compendium, so the fitness-based analysis in S2 is envelope-stress-only. With the Fur driver established, S2 asks which subset of the 32 Fur-released concordant-strong genes actually enriches for envelope-stress fitness phenotypes above the 33.25% genome background.\",\n275\t      \"id\": 8,\n276\t      \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n277\t      \"position\": 8\n278\t    },\n279\t    {\n280\t      \"layout\": \"section_divider\",\n281\t      \"content\": {\n282\t        \"punchline\": \"Calibrated against genome background, only the Fur-released Path A enriches for envelope-stress fitness.\",\n283\t        \"substory_number\": 2\n284\t      },\n285\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"S1 established that \\u0394fur derepression is the driver \\u2014 the Leaden concordance fingerprinted the program, the strain-design logic isolated it, and Zik 2022 showed it is genetically required for lipid A-loss viability. S2 narrows that driver claim by asking which arm of the Fur-released program actually carries the envelope-stress fitness signal. The answer divides cleanly along the Path A / Path B line, and the methodological lesson that makes the division interpretable is as important as the biology.\\n\\nThe pivot of the entire S2 argument is a single number: 33.25%. That is the genome-wide phenotype-bearing rate across 3,943 Caulobacter genes in the RB-TnSeq compendium \\u2014 K=1311 genes with |fitness t| > 4 in at least two envelope-stress experiments. Without that background rate, the enrichment analysis is uninterpretable. With it, the question transforms from \\\"do these Fur-released genes show fitness effects?\\\" \\u2014 which any random one-in-three Caulobacter genes would pass \\u2014 to \\\"are they enriched above what background predicts?\\\" That recalibration is the A6 methodological lesson from the plan inventory: the pre-registered \\u226510% threshold sat below the 33.25% background, making it a presence test rather than an enrichment test. The adversarial review surfaced this; notebook 02b corrected the H2 verdict to use hypergeometric fold-enrichment over background as the formal criterion.\\n\\nThe biological result is a clean two-arm contrast. Path A \\u2014 the 32-gene concordant-strong Fur-released TBDT subset \\u2014 clears the calibrated bar at fold 1.60\\u00d7 over background, p=0.016. Path B \\u2014 the 26-gene SspB-buffered cbb3/fix micro-aerobic respiratory arm \\u2014 falls to background at fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515, indistinguishable from any randomly drawn Caulobacter gene set under the same conditions. The Path A enrichment is real but REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 labels it explicitly \\\"marginally enriched\\\" \\u2014 the speaker should match that framing and not promote it beyond its stated grade. The Path B null is not a failure; it is the second half of the punchline, and it is biologically informative in its own right.\\n\\nThe adversarial reviewer independently reproduced the Path A enrichment result, confirming the STRONG tier classification despite the modest fold magnitude. The next slide walks through the method setup \\u2014 the experiment classification, the phenotype-bearing criterion, and the calibration arithmetic \\u2014 before the two-arm results table appears.\",\n286\t      \"id\": 9,\n287\t      \"substory_id\": \"S2\",\n288\t      \"position\": 9\n289\t    },\n290\t    {\n291\t      \"layout\": \"methods_summary\",\n292\t      \"content\": {\n293\t        \"title\": \"Hypergeometric enrichment test calibrated against Caulobacter genome background (H2 method)\",\n294\t        \"bullets\": [\n295\t          \"Fitness data: Caulobacter RB-TnSeq compendium, 198 experiments (kescience_fitnessbrowser, orgId=Caulo; Price et al. 2018)\",\n296\t          \"Envelope-stress subset selected: 22 of 198 experiments; iron-limitation experiments = 0 in compendium \\u2014 H2 iron arm descoped at preflight\",\n297\t          \"Phenotype-bearing criterion: |fitness t| > 4 in \\u2265 2 envelope-stress experiments\",\n298\t          \"Genome background calibration: K=1311 / N=3943 = 33.25% phenotype-bearing across all Caulobacter genes\",\n299\t          \"Pre-registered \\u226510% threshold sits below 33.25% background \\u2014 threshold-passing alone is uninformative without background correction (A6: miscalibration lesson)\",\n300\t          \"H2 verdict recalibrated in NB02b: hypergeometric enrichment vs background, requiring fold \\u2265 1.5\\u00d7 and p < 0.05\",\n301\t          \"Two arms tested: Path A (32 concordant_strong Fur-released genes) vs Path B (26 SspB-buffered cbb3/fix genes)\"\n302\t        ],\n303\t        \"tools_versions\": [\n304\t          {\n305\t            \"tool\": \"Fitness Browser\",\n306\t            \"version\": \"unknown\"\n307\t          }\n308\t        ],\n309\t        \"see_notes_footer\": true\n310\t      },\n311\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"The method here is a hypergeometric enrichment test, but the calibration step is where most of the analytical work happens, and it is the step that changed the H2 verdict from a presence check to a proper enrichment test.\\n\\nThe Caulobacter RB-TnSeq compendium (kescience_fitnessbrowser, orgId=Caulo, Price et al. 2018) covers 198 experiments in total: 95 stress conditions spanning envelope, drug, and metal stresses; 46 nitrogen-source experiments; 42 carbon-source experiments; 10 PYE controls; and 5 others. Of those 198, 22 are classified as envelope-stress experiments \\u2014 the phenotypic axis relevant to H2. Zero experiments are iron-limitation experiments for Caulobacter. REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 states this explicitly: \\\"the iron-limitation arm could not be tested \\u2014 zero iron-limitation experiments in the compendium; H2 was descoped to envelope-axis-only per the plan's preflight rule.\\\" Everything in this substory is envelope-stress-axis only; the iron-axis arm remains an open future direction.\\n\\nA gene is defined as phenotype-bearing if its absolute fitness t-statistic exceeds 4 in at least 2 of those 22 envelope-stress experiments. Applied genome-wide to 3,943 Caulobacter genes, 1,311 meet this criterion, giving a background rate of 33.25% (K=1311/N=3943). The pre-registered \\u226510% threshold in the original analysis plan sits comfortably below 33.25%, which means any randomly drawn Caulobacter gene set would on average show about one-in-three genes as phenotype-bearing \\u2014 well above the 10% bar. Threshold-passing alone is therefore uninformative about specific mechanistic importance. This is the miscalibration lesson the adversarial review surfaced. The H2 verdict was recalibrated in notebook 02b to require fold-enrichment of at least 1.5\\u00d7 over background with p < 0.05 as the formal criterion. Two arms were tested: Path A consists of the 32 concordant-strong Fur-released genes, led by TonB-dependent transporters; Path B consists of the 26 SspB-buffered cbb3/fix genes. The comparable sample sizes \\u2014 32 versus 26 \\u2014 mean statistical power to detect enrichment is roughly matched between the arms, which makes the Path B null interpretable as a genuine absence rather than a power gap.\\n\\nOne scope caveat must be stated clearly here: because iron-limitation experiments are absent from the compendium, the test speaks only to envelope-stress fitness. REPORT \\u00a7Limitations names this boundary explicitly, and REPORT \\u00a7Future Directions \\u00a76 lists iron-axis RB-TnSeq experiments as a needed follow-up. The next slide shows the two-arm results.\",\n312\t      \"id\": 10,\n313\t      \"substory_id\": \"S2\",\n314\t      \"position\": 10\n315\t    },\n316\t    {\n317\t      \"layout\": \"data_table\",\n318\t      \"content\": {\n319\t        \"title\": \"Path A enriched 1.60\\u00d7 over genome background; Path B falls to background\",\n320\t        \"columns\": [\n321\t          \"Gene set\",\n322\t          \"n\",\n323\t          \"Phenotype-bearing\",\n324\t          \"Fold vs background\",\n325\t          \"p-value\"\n326\t        ],\n327\t        \"rows\": [\n328\t          [\n329\t            \"Path A \\u2014 Fur-released TBDTs\",\n330\t            \"32\",\n331\t            \"53.1% (17/32)\",\n332\t            \"1.60\\u00d7\",\n333\t            \"0.016\"\n334\t          ],\n335\t          [\n336\t            \"Path B \\u2014 SspB-buffered cbb3/fix\",\n337\t            \"26\",\n338\t            \"34.6% (9/26)\",\n339\t            \"1.04\\u00d7\",\n340\t            \"0.515\"\n341\t          ]\n342\t        ],\n343\t        \"caption\": \"Genome background: 33.25% (K=1311/N=3943). Hypergeometric test vs background. Path B is indistinguishable from background.\",\n344\t        \"footnote\": \"Full analysis in REPORT.md \\u00a7Finding 2 and nb 02b_h2_hypergeometric_verdict.ipynb cell 2.\",\n345\t        \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Finding 2; notebooks/02b_h2_hypergeometric_verdict.ipynb cell 2\",\n346\t        \"highlight_rows\": [\n347\t          0\n348\t        ]\n349\t      },\n350\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"This two-row table is the core H2 result. The contrast between the rows is the biological message of S2, and every number in it is verbatim from REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 and notebook 02b_h2_hypergeometric_verdict.ipynb cell 2.\\n\\nThe genome background anchoring both tests is 33.25% (K=1311/N=3943). Path A \\u2014 the 32-gene concordant-strong Fur-released TBDT subset \\u2014 shows 53.1% phenotype-bearing (17 of 32 genes), fold 1.60\\u00d7 over background, hypergeometric p=0.016. REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 describes this as \\\"marginal but real enrichment.\\\" Path B \\u2014 the 26-gene SspB-buffered cbb3/fix micro-aerobic respiratory arm \\u2014 shows 34.6% phenotype-bearing (9 of 26 genes), fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515. REPORT labels this \\\"indistinguishable from background.\\\"\\n\\nThe top Path A hits by envelope-stress fitness signal are instructive. ChvT (CCNA_03108) has |t|=43.7 under envelope stress \\u2014 the single strongest signal in the set. Other Fur-derepressed TonB-dependent transporters (CCNA_02910, CCNA_00210, CCNA_02048, CCNA_00028) range from |t| 9 to 28. These are outer-membrane iron-acquisition transport machinery. Their envelope-stress fitness scores are consistent with the Uchendu et al. 2026 shared-component model, in which Lpt-paralog machinery participates in sphingolipid (CPG) trafficking in the lipid A-deficient state \\u2014 though that mechanistic participation is not directly demonstrated by the fitness data here. The fitness test identifies phenotype-bearing genes, not mechanism.\\n\\nThe speaker should call the Path A enrichment what REPORT calls it: marginal. Fold 1.60\\u00d7 is statistically distinguishable from random (p=0.016) and was independently reproduced by the adversarial reviewer, confirming the result's robustness. But the magnitude is modest, and we are not claiming dramatic positive selection. The Path B result at fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515 is unambiguously null \\u2014 not borderline. With n=26 tested against the same background using the same test as n=32 Path A, p=0.515 is a genuine absence of enrichment, not a power artifact. REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 states: \\\"Path B (the SspB-buffered respiratory chain) shows no enrichment relative to background.\\\" The distinction between the two arms is real and reproducible. The next slide develops the Path B demotion \\u2014 explaining what it means for the model and how to defend it in Q&A.\",\n351\t      \"id\": 11,\n352\t      \"substory_id\": \"S2\",\n353\t      \"position\": 11\n354\t    },\n355\t    {\n356\t      \"layout\": \"claim_evidence\",\n357\t      \"content\": {\n358\t        \"title\": \"Path B demotion: SspB-buffered respiratory arm is working hypothesis, not established mechanism\",\n359\t        \"bullets\": [\n360\t          \"Path B (cbb3/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory arm, n=26): 34.6% phenotype-bearing \\u2014 fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515, indistinguishable from genome background (33.25%)\",\n361\t          \"Transcript-level SspB buffering is real (NB01: 53/93 Leaden \\u0394fur DEGs blunted, dominated by cbb3/fix operon); fitness data do not selectively support this set over randomly drawn Caulobacter genes under envelope stress\",\n362\t          \"'Respiratory ATP required for envelope-remodeling work' is mechanistically plausible but not established by fitness data \\u2014 demoted from finding to working hypothesis\"\n363\t        ],\n364\t        \"citations\": [\n365\t          \"Price2018\"\n366\t        ]\n367\t      },\n368\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"The Path B null result is not a failure to detect something real \\u2014 it is telling us something specific and biologically important about where the mechanistic evidence reaches and where it stops.\\n\\nAt the transcript level, the SspB buffering effect is real and measurable. Notebook 01 cell 5 shows that 53 of the 93 Leaden \\u0394fur DEGs are blunted in our \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB 4584-vs-4580 data \\u2014 near-zero logFC in our strain despite logFC of \\u22125 to \\u22129 in Leaden's \\u0394fur-alone data. That buffered set is dominated by the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon (CCNA_01466\\u201301476: ccoNOPQ, cydCDA, fixGHI). This transcript-level buffering is what distinguishes the \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB double deletion from a \\u0394fur single in the Leaden comparison, and it is a clean novel transcriptomic observation that required our strain design to detect.\\n\\nBut the Caulobacter Fitness Browser data tell a different story about mechanistic specificity under envelope stress. At 34.6% phenotype-bearing (9 of 26 genes), fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515, the SspB-buffered set is indistinguishable from any randomly drawn 26 Caulobacter genes under the same 22 envelope-stress experiments. REPORT \\u00a7Limitations states: \\\"The fitness data do not selectively support the cbb3/fix genes as more critical than randomly drawn Caulobacter genes under envelope stress.\\\" REPORT \\u00a7Interpretation \\u00a72 demotes the respiratory arm explicitly: \\\"The 'respiratory ATP required' arm of the dual-release switch model is therefore a working hypothesis, not an established finding.\\\" The mechanistic rationale remains plausible \\u2014 cell division without lipid A, sphingolipid transport, and outer-membrane maintenance are energy-intensive processes \\u2014 but plausible is precisely where the evidence leaves it.\\n\\nWhen the audience asks \\\"doesn't the respiratory chain need to be active?\\\" the correct answer is yes, but needing to be active and being selectively enriched for phenotype under envelope stress are different claims. The fitness data test the latter; Path B fails that test. The transcript data and the fitness data are measuring different things: one shows \\u0394sspB stabilizes cbb3/fix transcripts, the other shows those transcripts do not map to genes enriched for fitness impact under envelope stress. We cannot currently distinguish \\\"respiratory protection matters but is too pleiotropic to appear as enrichment\\\" from \\\"respiratory protection is not specifically required here.\\\" That ambiguity is the honest state of the evidence. Having partitioned the Fur-released arms \\u2014 Path A carries the envelope-stress fitness signal, Path B does not \\u2014 the talk moves to S3, which asks what the Fur-set envelope state triggers downstream: the ChvI two-phase regulatory response.\",\n369\t      \"id\": 12,\n370\t      \"substory_id\": \"S2\",\n371\t      \"position\": 12\n372\t    },\n373\t    {\n374\t      \"layout\": \"section_divider\",\n375\t      \"content\": {\n376\t        \"punchline\": \"The Fur-set envelope state triggers a two-phase ChvI response; its late regulator stays open.\",\n377\t        \"substory_number\": 3\n378\t      },\n379\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"Coming off S2's Path A/B partition \\u2014 where we showed that only the Fur-released TBDT subset enriches for envelope-stress fitness at fold 1.60\\u00d7 over the 33.25% genome background, while the SspB-buffered respiratory arm falls to fold 1.04\\u00d7 \\u2014 we now follow the Fur-set envelope state into the regulatory signaling layer. S3 asks not which Fur targets carry the fitness signal, but what the Fur-established envelope state activates at the transcriptional-sensor level. The sensor is ChvG-ChvI, Caulobacter's dedicated two-component envelope-homeostasis system.\\n\\nThe argument of S3 divides into two honest halves. The first is what the driver demonstrably activates: the ChvI regulon partitions into three fully disjoint phases across our strain-series contrasts \\u2014 20 genes unique-to-early (Fur-release-coincident), 10 in both phases (cooperative continuation), and 49 late-consequence genes responding specifically to lipid-A loss. All three cohorts clear the pre-registered \\u226510-gene phase-structure threshold strongly, and the partition is robust and descriptive. The H1 phase-structure verdict is SUPPORTED. The second half is what we could not resolve: the SigU coherence test, the pre-registered sub-hypothesis for what drives the late 49-gene cohort, returned 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment with Fisher p=0.243 \\u2014 below both the statistical significance threshold and the 50% relaxed criterion. The late-cohort driver is genuinely unassigned in this work, and that is the honest state of the evidence.\\n\\nWhat makes this partition meaningful \\u2014 and what distinguishes it from any prior ChvI description \\u2014 is the three-strain design established in S1. By holding the Fur/SspB permissive state constant in the early contrast (4584-vs-4580, LpxC still present) and then comparing it to the lipid-A-deficient state (4599-vs-4584, LpxC deleted), we can separate what ChvI does because of Fur derepression from what it does specifically because lipid A is lost. That contrast design is what makes the early/late phase partition interpretable as a biological result rather than a condition-confounded composite. The adversarial review also raised ChvR sRNA as an untested post-transcriptional confound on the late cohort; we acknowledge it as an open question with no resolution in this dataset. The three content slides in this section walk through the method setup, the partition counts and exemplars, and the SigU/ChvR open question in order.\",\n380\t      \"id\": 13,\n381\t      \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n382\t      \"position\": 13\n383\t    },\n384\t    {\n385\t      \"layout\": \"methods_summary\",\n386\t      \"content\": {\n387\t        \"title\": \"ChvI phase partition: two published regulons cross-referenced against our strain-series contrasts\",\n388\t        \"bullets\": [\n389\t          \"ChvI reference regulon: union of Stein 2021 (PMID 34124942) + Quintero-Yanes 2022 (PMID 36480504) \\u2014 488 ChvI-induced genes in the C. crescentus NA1000 tested universe\",\n390\t          \"Early-phase contrast (4584-vs-4580): \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb \\u0394rsaA vs \\u0394rsaA \\u2014 captures co-release of Fur suppression and SspB buffering, LpxC still present\",\n391\t          \"Late-phase contrast (4599-vs-4584): \\u0394lpxc rescue vs dual-release intermediate \\u2014 isolates ChvI response to lipid-A loss with Fur/SspB permissive state already established\",\n392\t          \"Phase assignment: three fully disjoint sets (unique-to-early / both-phase / late-consequence); no gene counted in two cohorts; total engaged = 79 genes\",\n393\t          \"Pre-registered phase-structure threshold: \\u226510 genes per cohort required for H1 phase-structure verdict (RESEARCH_PLAN \\u00a7hypotheses)\",\n394\t          \"SigU coherence test: Fisher exact enrichment of envelope/transport/regulator categories in late cohort vs unique-to-early; relaxed pass bar = 50% enrichment + p<1e-3\",\n395\t          \"ChvR sRNA (Fr\\u00f6hlich 2018; adversarial review N3) acknowledged as untested post-transcriptional alternative \\u2014 not in this dataset\"\n396\t        ],\n397\t        \"tools_versions\": [\n398\t          {\n399\t            \"tool\": \"edgeR\",\n400\t            \"version\": \"unknown\"\n401\t          }\n402\t        ],\n403\t        \"see_notes_footer\": true\n404\t      },\n405\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"The foundation for this analysis is the ChvI reference regulon \\u2014 488 ChvI-induced genes assembled as the union of two independent published datasets. Stein 2021 characterized the ChvG-ChvI system via deletion in defined medium; Quintero-Yanes 2022 captured ChvI response under vancomycin and osmotic stress in C. crescentus NA1000. Taking their union gives the broadest possible ChvI-induced working universe, avoiding gene dropout caused by condition-specific induction in either study alone. Any ChvI-regulated gene appearing in at least one of those two published regulons is eligible for phase assignment in our data.\\n\\nThe early-phase contrast is 4584-vs-4580: \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB \\u0394rsaA versus the \\u0394rsaA parent. This captures the combined dual-release state \\u2014 Fur suppression and SspB buffering are both removed \\u2014 while LpxC remains fully intact. The cell is not yet lipid-A-deficient in this contrast; the Fur/SspB permissive state is established, but the envelope is structurally complete. The late-phase contrast is 4599-vs-4584: the \\u0394lpxC rescue state versus the dual-release intermediate. This isolates what ChvI does specifically in response to lipid-A loss, with the Fur/SspB permissive state already present and held constant across the comparison. The phase assignment is fully disjoint: every gene appears in exactly one cohort. The three counts \\u2014 20 unique-to-early, 10 both-phase, 49 late-consequence \\u2014 sum to 79 total engaged ChvI-regulon genes, and no gene is counted in two cohorts.\\n\\nThe pre-registered threshold for the H1 phase-structure verdict was \\u226510 genes per cohort (RESEARCH_PLAN \\u00a7hypotheses H1). This prevents a handful of coincidental regulon overlaps from being interpreted as a biological phase. All three cohorts clear the threshold strongly, and the H1 verdict is SUPPORTED. The SigU coherence test was the pre-registered H1 sub-hypothesis: if SigU is the late-cohort driver, the late 49 genes should enrich for envelope/transport/regulator functional categories relative to the early 20. The relaxed criterion \\u2014 50% enrichment instead of the original 75%, p<1e-3 instead of p<0.05 \\u2014 gave SigU the best possible inferential chance. The adversarial review (N3) flagged ChvR sRNA as a post-transcriptional alternative for late-cohort modulation; we lack ChvR expression data in our strain backgrounds, so this confound is acknowledged but unresolved. One scope caveat spanning the whole section: everything here describes the ChvI response to our specific Fur/SspB/LpxC perturbation series under PYE-rich conditions. The phase structure under other envelope stresses or growth media has not been measured. The next slide shows the three-phase cohort counts and their exemplar genes.\",\n406\t      \"id\": 14,\n407\t      \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n408\t      \"position\": 14\n409\t    },\n410\t    {\n411\t      \"layout\": \"data_table\",\n412\t      \"content\": {\n413\t        \"title\": \"ChvI two-phase partition: ChvI autoregulation sits in the both-phase cohort\",\n414\t        \"columns\": [\n415\t          \"Phase\",\n416\t          \"n genes\",\n417\t          \"Key exemplars (log2FC)\",\n418\t          \"Functional theme\"\n419\t        ],\n420\t        \"rows\": [\n421\t          [\n422\t            \"Unique-to-early\",\n423\t            \"20\",\n424\t            \"CCNA_02794 +8.6, ApbE +3.8, imuB +1.5\",\n425\t            \"Regulator/SOS (6.7% TCS)\"\n426\t          ],\n427\t          [\n428\t            \"Both-phase (cooperative)\",\n429\t            \"10\",\n430\t            \"ChvI +1.45, CCNA_02378 +1.9\\u2192+3.9, CpxP-like CCNA_03997\",\n431\t            \"Cooperative continuation\"\n432\t          ],\n433\t          [\n434\t            \"Late-consequence\",\n435\t            \"49\",\n436\t            \"LolA-family +2.89, Pal +2.08, multiple TBDTs\",\n437\t            \"Envelope/OM structural (10.2% OM, 12.2% TBDT)\"\n438\t          ]\n439\t        ],\n440\t        \"caption\": \"Disjoint ChvI partition (79 total); all cohorts clear \\u226510-gene threshold. Both-phase row: ChvI autoregulation (logFC +1.45) and CpxP-like chaperone engagement. Late row: shift to envelope-structural effectors.\",\n441\t        \"footnote\": \"Full gene-by-gene assignment in data/NB03_chvi_phase_cohorts.csv (n=89); theme breakdown in data/NB03_phase_cohort_themes.csv.\",\n442\t        \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Finding 3; nb 03_chvi_phase_partition_sigU.ipynb cell 7\",\n443\t        \"highlight_rows\": [\n444\t          2\n445\t        ]\n446\t      },\n447\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"The three-phase ChvI partition shown here \\u2014 20 unique-to-early, 10 both-phase, and 49 late-consequence genes \\u2014 is the core H1 result. All counts are verbatim from REPORT \\u00a7Finding 3 and NB03 cell 7; together they total 79 ChvI-induced genes engaged across at least one contrast in our strain series.\\n\\nThe unique-to-early cohort is notable for its stress-responder composition. The lasso peptide cyclase CCNA_02794 at logFC +8.6 is the highest-magnitude early hit. ApbE, the iron-sulfur cluster repair protein, registers at +3.8. ImuB, the SOS DNA polymerase, registers at +1.5. That imuB entry is mechanistically connecting \\u2014 Leaden 2018 documented SOS activation as part of the \\u0394fur transcriptional program, and seeing imuB at +1.5 in the early-phase ChvI cohort confirms that the SOS and ChvI regulatory responses share the same precipitating event: constitutive Fur derepression in our strain. These are not independent signals; they are two readouts of the same Fur-release event appearing in different analytical layers, and together they corroborate the S1 driver claim.\\n\\nThe both-phase cohort contains the mechanistically critical observation: ChvI itself, CCNA_00237 at logFC +1.45 in the 4584-vs-4580 early contrast, sits in this set \\u2014 direct autoregulation evidence. Once the ChvG-ChvI system activates during the Fur/SspB release phase, ChvI sustains its own transcription through the lipid-A-loss transition. The SIMPL-family CCNA_02378 shows progressive amplification: logFC +1.9 in the early contrast increasing to +3.9 in the late, consistent with continued engagement as LpxC is actually deleted. The amelogenin/CpxP-related CCNA_03997 is notable context \\u2014 CpxP in E. coli is the periplasmic chaperone partner of the CpxA envelope-stress sensor, making CCNA_03997 a Caulobacter echo of cross-sensor envelope-stress signaling.\\n\\nThe late cohort shows a functional theme shift toward envelope and outer-membrane structural effectors \\u2014 10.2% envelope/OM and 12.2% TBDT genes among the 49, versus 6.7% regulator/TCS in the unique-to-early 20. The LolA-family OM lipoprotein carrier CCNA_03820 registers at logFC +2.89; the Pal-like CCNA_00784 at +2.08. This theme shift is suggestive of a regulatory-to-structural handoff as lipid-A loss is established, but the Fisher exact test of envelope/transport/regulator enrichment in the late cohort versus the unique-to-early cohort returned p=0.243 \\u2014 the theme shift is descriptive and not statistically discriminated at these cohort sizes. The partition counts and exemplars are the robust, pre-registered result; thematic interpretation is illustrative and stated as such. The next slide addresses the key open question: what transcriptional driver controls the late 49-gene cohort.\",\n448\t      \"id\": 15,\n449\t      \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n450\t      \"position\": 15\n451\t    },\n452\t    {\n453\t      \"layout\": \"claim_evidence\",\n454\t      \"content\": {\n455\t        \"title\": \"SigU coherence fails the pre-registered bar (24.5%, p=0.243); late-cohort driver unassigned\",\n456\t        \"bullets\": [\n457\t          \"SigU coherence in late 49-gene cohort: 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment, Fisher p=0.243 \\u2014 below both the 50% relaxed criterion and statistical significance; H1 SigU sub-hypothesis is not supported\",\n458\t          \"SigU (CCNA_02977) has published alphaproteobacterial literature; targeted SigU-induction RNA-seq (Future Directions \\u00a72) is the pre-planned next step to resolve whether SigU drives this specific cohort\",\n459\t          \"ChvR sRNA (Fr\\u00f6hlich 2018, adversarial review N3) is an untested post-transcriptional alternative for late-cohort modulation; late-cohort regulatory attribution remains open pending both experiments\"\n460\t        ],\n461\t        \"citations\": [\n462\t          \"QuinteroYanes2022\",\n463\t          \"Greenwich2023\"\n464\t        ]\n465\t      },\n466\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"The largest ChvI cohort \\u2014 49 late-consequence genes induced only after lipid-A loss \\u2014 does not have an identified transcriptional driver in this dataset, and that is the honest result the speaker delivers without softening it in either direction.\\n\\nThe pre-registered SigU coherence test (RESEARCH_PLAN \\u00a7hypotheses H1, NB03 cell 10) returned 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment in the late 49 genes with Fisher p=0.243. From REPORT \\u00a7Finding 3: \\\"The reframed SigU coherence check on the late cohort returned 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment \\u2014 below the 50% relaxed criterion.\\\" From REPORT \\u00a7Limitations: \\\"even the relaxed criterion did not pass (Fisher p=0.243).\\\" This is a genuine negative at the pre-registered bar. The 24.5% figure means roughly one in four late-cohort genes fall into the expected functional categories. For a membrane-centric organism where those categories represent a substantial fraction of the genome, this offers no discriminatory signal above what a random draw of 49 genes would produce.\\n\\nThe test does not falsify SigU as a regulator of the Caulobacter envelope-stress response more broadly. Adversarial review N2 corrected an earlier framing in this project: SigU does have published characterization in alphaproteobacteria, so the accurate framing is \\\"late-cohort driver unassigned\\\" rather than \\\"no candidate identified.\\\" The coherence test asks whether this specific 49-gene set, under this specific lipid-A-loss perturbation, shows the functional composition expected of a SigU-driven regulon. At 24.5% and p=0.243, the answer is no. The planned next experiment is ectopic vanillate-inducible SigU overexpression RNA-seq in the 4599 background (REPORT Future Directions \\u00a72). That experiment would directly test whether a SigU-induced regulon overlaps the late 49-gene cohort and resolve the attribution question. What we have here is an honest absence of support for a specific mechanistic claim, not a disproven hypothesis about SigU's biology.\\n\\nThe ChvR sRNA layer, flagged by adversarial review N3, adds a second source of late-cohort uncertainty. ChvR provides post-transcriptional modulation of ChvI-pathway output in Caulobacter and could sculpt late-cohort composition independently of any sigma-factor logic. We have no ChvR expression data in our strain backgrounds; this gap is explicitly acknowledged and represents a known next experiment, not a failure of the current design. When the audience asks what drives the late cohort, the correct answer is: we do not know, the pre-registered test did not support SigU, and two experiments \\u2014 SigU-induction RNA-seq and ChvR characterization in this background \\u2014 are the planned resolution path. With the ChvI two-phase response characterized and its late driver acknowledged as open, S4 takes over to ask what the cell physically does to maintain the envelope without lipid A. Constitutive sphingolipids and reorganized peptidoglycan carry cleaner direct-tier evidence than the signaling layer just covered, and they are the structural-effector complement to the regulatory picture S3 has built.\",\n467\t      \"id\": 16,\n468\t      \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n469\t      \"position\": 16\n470\t    },\n471\t    {\n472\t      \"layout\": \"section_divider\",\n473\t      \"content\": {\n474\t        \"punchline\": \"Without lipid A, constitutive sphingolipids and reorganized peptidoglycan hold the envelope together.\",\n475\t        \"substory_number\": 4\n476\t      },\n477\t      \"speaker_notes\": \"S3 established the signaling layer: the Fur-set envelope state triggers a two-phase ChvI response \\u2014 20 unique-to-early genes, 10 both-phase, and 49 late-consequence \\u2014 and closed with one honest gap: the late-cohort driver was not supported at the pre-registered bar, with SigU coherence at 24.5% and Fisher p=0.243. S4 leaves that open regulatory question behind and asks the structural question that follows it: once lipid A is physically absent from the outer membrane, what holds the envelope together?\\n\\nThe experimental lens is the 4599-vs-4584 contrast \\u2014 strain 4599 (\\u0394fur \\u0394sspB \\u0394lpxC \\u0394rsaA) against its direct precursor 4584 (\\u0394fur \\u0394sspB \\u0394rsaA) \\u2014 designed to isolate the \\u0394lpxC-specific structural response with the Fur and SspB permissive state already present and constant across both sides of the comparison. Zik et al. 2022 established the biological preconditions for this comparison: \\u0394fur is genetically required for \\u0394lpxC viability, and anionic sphingolipid ceramide phosphoglycerate is required as well. S4 asks which molecular changes at the lipid and peptidoglycan layers explain why a cell meeting those two conditions can survive without lipid A.\\n\\nThe evidence yields two answers with direct-tier support and two with important caveats. The well-supported answers are sphingolipid constitutivity \\u2014 the biosynthesis pathway was already running at baseline, with zero of six core genes induced when lipid A is lost \\u2014 and peptidoglycan reorganization, where a specific lytic transglycosylase and the Pal-Tol complex engage against a backdrop of broad synthesis suppression. The partial answers are the Lpt transport apparatus, where transcript and protein evidence point in opposite directions and require replicated proteomics to resolve, and the CtpA processing step predicted by Zik 2022, which is rejected at our pre-registered evidential bar. Keeping those grades distinct \\u2014 not flattening them into a uniform \\\"supported\\\" story \\u2014 is the core responsibility of S4's delivery. The methods slide establishes both modalities before any results appear.\",\n478\t      \"id\": 17,\n479\t      \"substory_id\": \"S4\",\n480\t      \"position\": 17\n481\t    },\n482\t    {\n483\t      \"layout\": \"methods_summary\",\n484\t      \"content\": {\n485\t        \"title\": \"Measuring the structural-effector response: transcript panel and single-replicate OM proteome\",\n486\t        \"bullets\": [\n487\t          \"Strain contrast: 4599 (delta-fur delta-sspB delta-lpxc delta-rsaA) vs 4584 (delta-fur delta-sspB delta-rsaA) \\u2014 isolates the delta-lpxc-specific response net of Fur and SspB co-deletions\",\n488\t          \"Transcriptomics: edgeR differential expression, FDR < 0.05 threshold; 3,943 Caulobacter protein-coding genes tested\",\n489\t          \"Sphingolipid panel: 6 core biosynthesis genes (spt, sphk, cerS, cerR, cpgB, cpgD) + 3 Uchendu 2026 IM transporter genes (lptG2/F2/C2) tested for induction vs constitutivity\",\n490\t          \"Canonical Lpt apparatus: 6 transport components (MsbA, LptA-G) checked for maintenance vs remodeling in delta-lpxc state\",\n491\t          \"PG remodeling gene set: 53 loci pre-curated before DE analysis (transpeptidase, transglycosylase, amidase, hydrolase families); 28 meet H4 threshold (FDR < 0.05 OR |log2| > 1 at protein)\",\n492\t          \"OM proteome: single-replicate mass-spectrometry per strain (4580 WT, 4584 intermediate, 4672 rescued); direction interpretable, no per-protein statistics\",\n493\t          \"CtpA test: pre-registered BORDERLINE criterion (0.05 < pvalue < 0.15 AND protein detected in OM proteome) applied to 4599-vs-4584 contrast exclusively\"\n494\t        ],\n495\t        \"tools_versions\": [\n496\t          {\n497\t            \"tool\": \"edgeR\",\n498\t            \"version\": \"unknown\"\n499\t          }"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57c7cd12-ce3b-4c50-865d-721855d63587","uuid":"69f5cc4b-f622-4526-82fa-76b3e76ee6bb","timestamp":"2026-06-08T23:42:56.165Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_2/working/slide_spec.json","content":"          ],\n          \"edges\": [\n            {\n              \"from\": \"s4580\",\n              \"to\": \"s4584\",\n              \"kind\": \"straight\",\n              \"label\": \"4584 vs 4580 = Fur arm\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"from\": \"s4584\",\n              \"to\": \"s4599\",\n              \"kind\": \"straight\",\n              \"label\": \"4599 vs 4584 = \\u0394lpxC arm\"\n            }\n          ]\n        },\n        \"step_caption\": [\n          \"Baseline: \\u0394rsaA removes surface layer; Fur/SspB intact\",\n          \"\\u0394fur + \\u0394sspB: dual-release switch; 4584-vs-4580 = Fur arm\",\n          \"\\u0394lpxC: lipid A-deficient; Zik 2022 \\u0394fur required precondition\"\n        ]\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"Before any transcriptomics, the strain-series logic must be clear \\u2014 every expression contrast in this talk derives from three genotypes, and the biological meaning of each contrast depends on understanding what each deletion contributes.\\n\\nStrain 4580 carries \\u0394rsaA, which removes the crystalline S-layer protein that normally dominates the Caulobacter outer membrane. This cleans up the transcriptomic and proteomic background \\u2014 the S-layer's extreme expression would otherwise mask subtler signals \\u2014 while leaving Fur, SspB, and lipid A synthesis fully intact. Strain 4580 is the denominator in every comparison shown in this talk.\\n\\nStrain 4584 adds \\u0394fur and \\u0394sspB on top of the 4580 background. \\u0394fur constitutively releases the Fur regulon: TonB-dependent transporters, iron-uptake systems, and iron-storage proteins that Fur normally represses under iron-replete conditions. \\u0394sspB removes the ClpXP adaptor that degrades SspB-tagged substrates; in Caulobacter this protects the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon at the transcript level \\u2014 visible as the orange buffered cluster on the concordance scatter on the next slide. Critically, strain 4584 is lipid A-replete: the organism grows normally with a full outer membrane. The 4584-vs-4580 contrast is the clean readout of the combined \\u0394fur + \\u0394sspB release, measured without the confound of lipid A loss.\\n\\nStrain 4599 adds \\u0394lpxC to the 4584 background, deleting the committed step in lipid A biosynthesis entirely. Zik et al. 2022 (PMID 35649364) established that this genotype is viable only in a \\u0394fur background \\u2014 Fur-intact strains with \\u0394lpxC are inviable. The 4599-vs-4584 contrast captures the \\u0394lpxC-specific envelope response layered on the Fur-set state, and that contrast is the substrate for substories S3 and S4.\\n\\nTwo design caveats belong here. First, the outer membrane proteome is single-replicate per strain. REPORT \\u00a7Limitations states: \\\"OM proteome is single-replicate per strain \\u2014 no per-protein statistics; only direction is interpretable.\\\" Proteomics in this talk are direction-only observations throughout; transcript-level DE (edgeR) is the statistically replicated layer. Second, both proteome contrasts involve the Ryan-lab strains in the \\u0394rsaA background, which may differ from the NA1000 background Leaden used \\u2014 a source of some of the unexplained variance in the concordance \\u03c1. The next slide presents the core concordance result and makes this variance interpretable.\",\n      \"id\": 6,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n      \"position\": 6\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": 7,\n      \"position\": 7,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n      \"layout\": \"data_figure\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"Spearman \\u03c1=0.315 (p=2.08e-03, 71% sign concordance) confirms Fur derepression as a major component of our signal (n=93 Leaden DEGs)\",\n        \"figure\": \"figures/NB01_fur_signature_scatter.png\",\n        \"caption\": \"Leaden \\u0394fur logFC vs our 4584-vs-4580 logFC; concordant_strong in dark blue, SspB-buffered set in orange, discordant in red; n=93 \\u0394fur DEGs, Spearman \\u03c1=0.315, p=2.08e-03.\",\n        \"data_source\": \"Leaden 2018 (PMID 30210482); NB01_leaden2018_fur_signature.ipynb cell 5\"\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes_seed\": \"This scatter is the central evidence for S1\\u2019s driver claim. X-axis: Leaden 2018 \\u0394fur logFC across 93 DEGs (PMID 30210482, supp. Table 2). Y-axis: our 4584-vs-4580 logFC for the same 93 genes. Spearman \\u03c1=0.315, p=2.08e-03, 71% sign concordance: REPORT \\u00a7Finding 1 frames this as \\u2018confirming Fur derepression as a major component of our signal\\u2019 \\u2014 not the sole driver, not a full explanation. The concordant-strong cluster (dark blue, top-right) shows amplified derepression relative to Leaden; HutA at +10.5 vs Leaden\\u2019s +2.2 is the extreme outlier reflecting the combined dual-release effect. The orange buffered cluster (n=53) near y\\u22480 spans Leaden\\u2019s full \\u22129 to \\u22125 range \\u2014 \\u0394sspB is shielding the cbb3/fix respiratory operon at the transcript level.\\n\\nThis slide claims Fur derepression is a major component of our signal. It does NOT yet claim the signal is constitutive rather than iron-status \\u2014 that discrimination is on the next slide (slide 8), where Leaden\\u2019s own iron-limitation comparison and the Zik 2022 genetic anchoring actually appear. For a \\u2018\\u03c1=0.315 is modest\\u2019 challenge: this is one of several converging lines of evidence, deliberately scoped.\",\n      \"evidence_anchors\": [\n        {\n          \"kind\": \"report_section\",\n          \"ref\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Finding 1\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"kind\": \"report_section\",\n          \"ref\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Literature Context (Leaden 2018)\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"revision_log\": [\n        {\n          \"revised_at\": \"2026-06-08T00:00:00Z\",\n          \"finding_id\": \"F001\",\n          \"finding_class\": \"register_drift\",\n          \"summary\": \"Removed 'constitutive derepression' from title (claim belongs on slide 8 with the iron-discrimination evidence, not here); replaced with 'Fur derepression as a major component of our signal' (verbatim REPORT \\u00a7Literature Context, Leaden 2018 entry); added p=2.08e-03 and 71% sign concordance inline so the \\u03c1=0.315 claim is self-hedged; caption and data_source unchanged; speaker notes updated to make the constitutive-vs-iron hand-off to slide 8 explicit.\"\n        }\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"claim_evidence\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"Constitutive \\u0394fur derepression, not iron limitation, sets the permissive envelope state\",\n        \"bullets\": [\n          \"Leaden \\u0394fur-vs-iron-limitation: two responses are correlated but distinct \\u2014 signal is consistent with constitutive Fur allele derepression rather than an iron-status readout (single PYE-rich growth condition; multi-condition replication pending)\",\n          \"53/93 Leaden \\u0394fur DEGs buffered in our \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB data \\u2014 dominated by the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ respiratory operon (CCNA_01466\\u201301476: ccoNOPQ, cydCDA, fixGHI) \\u2014 SspB masks this arm at the transcript level\",\n          \"Zik 2022 (PMID 35649364): \\u0394lpxc viability requires \\u0394fur; 'Fur-regulated processes, not iron status per se, underlie the ability to survive when lipid A synthesis is blocked'\"\n        ],\n        \"figure\": \"figures/NB01_leaden_iron_vs_fur.png\",\n        \"figure_caption\": \"Leaden 2018 internal: \\u0394fur vs iron-limitation logFC across the DEG set; responses are correlated but non-identical, consistent with constitutive Fur derepression rather than an iron-status readout.\",\n        \"citations\": [\n          \"Leaden2018\",\n          \"Zik2022\"\n        ]\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"This slide closes S1 with three converging pieces of evidence. Together they rule out iron limitation as the primary explanation for our signal and establish \\u0394fur as a genetic necessity for lipid A-loss viability \\u2014 not a correlate of low iron availability.\\n\\nThe grounding for the first piece comes from inside Leaden's own 2018 paper. Leaden measured both a \\u0394fur transcriptome and an iron-limitation transcriptome \\u2014 induced by 2,2'-dipyridyl chelation \\u2014 in the same C. crescentus NA1000 background. Comparing those two logFC axes directly, the figure shows the responses overlap but are not identical: the \\u0394fur genetic response includes gene movements that iron chelation alone does not produce. This non-identity, documented within a single paper and single genetic background, is Leaden's own internal evidence that constitutive \\u0394fur allele derepression is a biologically distinct state from iron-starvation response.\\n\\nThe second bullet makes the SspB arm concrete at the gene level. Of the 93 Leaden \\u0394fur DEGs, 53 are buffered in our \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB data \\u2014 near-zero logFC in our strain despite logFC \\u22125 to \\u22129 in Leaden. These 53 are dominated by the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon: CCNA_01466\\u201301476, encoding ccoNOPQ, cydCDA, fixGHI. \\u0394sspB protects this operon at the transcript level. Whether that protection is mechanistically critical for the \\u0394lpxc rescue is precisely what S2 tests with Caulobacter Fitness Browser enrichment analysis, so the speaker should name this as the bridge to S2 rather than claiming it here.\\n\\nThe third piece is the genetic anchor from Zik et al. 2022 (PMID 35649364). Their suppressor genetics established that \\u0394lpxc rescue requires the \\u0394fur allele. REPORT \\u00a7Literature Context quotes their language directly: \\\"Alterations in Fur-regulated processes, rather than iron status per se, underlie the ability to survive when lipid A synthesis is blocked.\\\" That genetic necessity \\u2014 \\u0394fur required, not merely correlated \\u2014 is the chain the rest of this talk pulls on.\\n\\nThe scope caveat on the iron-discrimination result must be stated plainly: REPORT \\u00a7Limitations names this as a single-condition scope boundary. The Leaden iron-limitation comparison was performed in the NA1000 background under dipyridyl chelation \\u2014 not in our Ryan-lab strain under our growth conditions. Whether the \\u0394fur-vs-iron-limitation distinction holds in magnitude or gene-membership under minimal medium or bipyridyl chelation in our strain background is untested. This is directional support \\u2014 consistent with constitutive derepression \\u2014 not a multi-condition proof. Iron-limitation experiments are also absent from the Caulobacter Fitness Browser compendium, so the fitness-based analysis in S2 is envelope-stress-only. With the Fur driver established, S2 asks which subset of the 32 Fur-released concordant-strong genes actually enriches for envelope-stress fitness phenotypes above the 33.25% genome background.\",\n      \"id\": 8,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S1\",\n      \"position\": 8\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"section_divider\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"punchline\": \"Calibrated against genome background, only the Fur-released Path A enriches for envelope-stress fitness.\",\n        \"substory_number\": 2\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"S1 established that \\u0394fur derepression is the driver \\u2014 the Leaden concordance fingerprinted the program, the strain-design logic isolated it, and Zik 2022 showed it is genetically required for lipid A-loss viability. S2 narrows that driver claim by asking which arm of the Fur-released program actually carries the envelope-stress fitness signal. The answer divides cleanly along the Path A / Path B line, and the methodological lesson that makes the division interpretable is as important as the biology.\\n\\nThe pivot of the entire S2 argument is a single number: 33.25%. That is the genome-wide phenotype-bearing rate across 3,943 Caulobacter genes in the RB-TnSeq compendium \\u2014 K=1311 genes with |fitness t| > 4 in at least two envelope-stress experiments. Without that background rate, the enrichment analysis is uninterpretable. With it, the question transforms from \\\"do these Fur-released genes show fitness effects?\\\" \\u2014 which any random one-in-three Caulobacter genes would pass \\u2014 to \\\"are they enriched above what background predicts?\\\" That recalibration is the A6 methodological lesson from the plan inventory: the pre-registered \\u226510% threshold sat below the 33.25% background, making it a presence test rather than an enrichment test. The adversarial review surfaced this; notebook 02b corrected the H2 verdict to use hypergeometric fold-enrichment over background as the formal criterion.\\n\\nThe biological result is a clean two-arm contrast. Path A \\u2014 the 32-gene concordant-strong Fur-released TBDT subset \\u2014 clears the calibrated bar at fold 1.60\\u00d7 over background, p=0.016. Path B \\u2014 the 26-gene SspB-buffered cbb3/fix micro-aerobic respiratory arm \\u2014 falls to background at fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515, indistinguishable from any randomly drawn Caulobacter gene set under the same conditions. The Path A enrichment is real but REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 labels it explicitly \\\"marginally enriched\\\" \\u2014 the speaker should match that framing and not promote it beyond its stated grade. The Path B null is not a failure; it is the second half of the punchline, and it is biologically informative in its own right.\\n\\nThe adversarial reviewer independently reproduced the Path A enrichment result, confirming the STRONG tier classification despite the modest fold magnitude. The next slide walks through the method setup \\u2014 the experiment classification, the phenotype-bearing criterion, and the calibration arithmetic \\u2014 before the two-arm results table appears.\",\n      \"id\": 9,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S2\",\n      \"position\": 9\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"methods_summary\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"Hypergeometric enrichment test calibrated against Caulobacter genome background (H2 method)\",\n        \"bullets\": [\n          \"Fitness data: Caulobacter RB-TnSeq compendium, 198 experiments (kescience_fitnessbrowser, orgId=Caulo; Price et al. 2018)\",\n          \"Envelope-stress subset selected: 22 of 198 experiments; iron-limitation experiments = 0 in compendium \\u2014 H2 iron arm descoped at preflight\",\n          \"Phenotype-bearing criterion: |fitness t| > 4 in \\u2265 2 envelope-stress experiments\",\n          \"Genome background calibration: K=1311 / N=3943 = 33.25% phenotype-bearing across all Caulobacter genes\",\n          \"Pre-registered \\u226510% threshold sits below 33.25% background \\u2014 threshold-passing alone is uninformative without background correction (A6: miscalibration lesson)\",\n          \"H2 verdict recalibrated in NB02b: hypergeometric enrichment vs background, requiring fold \\u2265 1.5\\u00d7 and p < 0.05\",\n          \"Two arms tested: Path A (32 concordant_strong Fur-released genes) vs Path B (26 SspB-buffered cbb3/fix genes)\"\n        ],\n        \"tools_versions\": [\n          {\n            \"tool\": \"Fitness Browser\",\n            \"version\": \"unknown\"\n          }\n        ],\n        \"see_notes_footer\": true\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"The method here is a hypergeometric enrichment test, but the calibration step is where most of the analytical work happens, and it is the step that changed the H2 verdict from a presence check to a proper enrichment test.\\n\\nThe Caulobacter RB-TnSeq compendium (kescience_fitnessbrowser, orgId=Caulo, Price et al. 2018) covers 198 experiments in total: 95 stress conditions spanning envelope, drug, and metal stresses; 46 nitrogen-source experiments; 42 carbon-source experiments; 10 PYE controls; and 5 others. Of those 198, 22 are classified as envelope-stress experiments \\u2014 the phenotypic axis relevant to H2. Zero experiments are iron-limitation experiments for Caulobacter. REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 states this explicitly: \\\"the iron-limitation arm could not be tested \\u2014 zero iron-limitation experiments in the compendium; H2 was descoped to envelope-axis-only per the plan's preflight rule.\\\" Everything in this substory is envelope-stress-axis only; the iron-axis arm remains an open future direction.\\n\\nA gene is defined as phenotype-bearing if its absolute fitness t-statistic exceeds 4 in at least 2 of those 22 envelope-stress experiments. Applied genome-wide to 3,943 Caulobacter genes, 1,311 meet this criterion, giving a background rate of 33.25% (K=1311/N=3943). The pre-registered \\u226510% threshold in the original analysis plan sits comfortably below 33.25%, which means any randomly drawn Caulobacter gene set would on average show about one-in-three genes as phenotype-bearing \\u2014 well above the 10% bar. Threshold-passing alone is therefore uninformative about specific mechanistic importance. This is the miscalibration lesson the adversarial review surfaced. The H2 verdict was recalibrated in notebook 02b to require fold-enrichment of at least 1.5\\u00d7 over background with p < 0.05 as the formal criterion. Two arms were tested: Path A consists of the 32 concordant-strong Fur-released genes, led by TonB-dependent transporters; Path B consists of the 26 SspB-buffered cbb3/fix genes. The comparable sample sizes \\u2014 32 versus 26 \\u2014 mean statistical power to detect enrichment is roughly matched between the arms, which makes the Path B null interpretable as a genuine absence rather than a power gap.\\n\\nOne scope caveat must be stated clearly here: because iron-limitation experiments are absent from the compendium, the test speaks only to envelope-stress fitness. REPORT \\u00a7Limitations names this boundary explicitly, and REPORT \\u00a7Future Directions \\u00a76 lists iron-axis RB-TnSeq experiments as a needed follow-up. The next slide shows the two-arm results.\",\n      \"id\": 10,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S2\",\n      \"position\": 10\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"data_table\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"Path A enriched 1.60\\u00d7 over genome background; Path B falls to background\",\n        \"columns\": [\n          \"Gene set\",\n          \"n\",\n          \"Phenotype-bearing\",\n          \"Fold vs background\",\n          \"p-value\"\n        ],\n        \"rows\": [\n          [\n            \"Path A \\u2014 Fur-released TBDTs\",\n            \"32\",\n            \"53.1% (17/32)\",\n            \"1.60\\u00d7\",\n            \"0.016\"\n          ],\n          [\n            \"Path B \\u2014 SspB-buffered cbb3/fix\",\n            \"26\",\n            \"34.6% (9/26)\",\n            \"1.04\\u00d7\",\n            \"0.515\"\n          ]\n        ],\n        \"caption\": \"Genome background: 33.25% (K=1311/N=3943). Hypergeometric test vs background. Path B is indistinguishable from background.\",\n        \"footnote\": \"Full analysis in REPORT.md \\u00a7Finding 2 and nb 02b_h2_hypergeometric_verdict.ipynb cell 2.\",\n        \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Finding 2; notebooks/02b_h2_hypergeometric_verdict.ipynb cell 2\",\n        \"highlight_rows\": [\n          0\n        ]\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"This two-row table is the core H2 result. The contrast between the rows is the biological message of S2, and every number in it is verbatim from REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 and notebook 02b_h2_hypergeometric_verdict.ipynb cell 2.\\n\\nThe genome background anchoring both tests is 33.25% (K=1311/N=3943). Path A \\u2014 the 32-gene concordant-strong Fur-released TBDT subset \\u2014 shows 53.1% phenotype-bearing (17 of 32 genes), fold 1.60\\u00d7 over background, hypergeometric p=0.016. REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 describes this as \\\"marginal but real enrichment.\\\" Path B \\u2014 the 26-gene SspB-buffered cbb3/fix micro-aerobic respiratory arm \\u2014 shows 34.6% phenotype-bearing (9 of 26 genes), fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515. REPORT labels this \\\"indistinguishable from background.\\\"\\n\\nThe top Path A hits by envelope-stress fitness signal are instructive. ChvT (CCNA_03108) has |t|=43.7 under envelope stress \\u2014 the single strongest signal in the set. Other Fur-derepressed TonB-dependent transporters (CCNA_02910, CCNA_00210, CCNA_02048, CCNA_00028) range from |t| 9 to 28. These are outer-membrane iron-acquisition transport machinery. Their envelope-stress fitness scores are consistent with the Uchendu et al. 2026 shared-component model, in which Lpt-paralog machinery participates in sphingolipid (CPG) trafficking in the lipid A-deficient state \\u2014 though that mechanistic participation is not directly demonstrated by the fitness data here. The fitness test identifies phenotype-bearing genes, not mechanism.\\n\\nThe speaker should call the Path A enrichment what REPORT calls it: marginal. Fold 1.60\\u00d7 is statistically distinguishable from random (p=0.016) and was independently reproduced by the adversarial reviewer, confirming the result's robustness. But the magnitude is modest, and we are not claiming dramatic positive selection. The Path B result at fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515 is unambiguously null \\u2014 not borderline. With n=26 tested against the same background using the same test as n=32 Path A, p=0.515 is a genuine absence of enrichment, not a power artifact. REPORT \\u00a7Finding 2 states: \\\"Path B (the SspB-buffered respiratory chain) shows no enrichment relative to background.\\\" The distinction between the two arms is real and reproducible. The next slide develops the Path B demotion \\u2014 explaining what it means for the model and how to defend it in Q&A.\",\n      \"id\": 11,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S2\",\n      \"position\": 11\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"claim_evidence\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"Path B demotion: SspB-buffered respiratory arm is working hypothesis, not established mechanism\",\n        \"bullets\": [\n          \"Path B (cbb3/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory arm, n=26): 34.6% phenotype-bearing \\u2014 fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515, indistinguishable from genome background (33.25%)\",\n          \"Transcript-level SspB buffering is real (NB01: 53/93 Leaden \\u0394fur DEGs blunted, dominated by cbb3/fix operon); fitness data do not selectively support this set over randomly drawn Caulobacter genes under envelope stress\",\n          \"'Respiratory ATP required for envelope-remodeling work' is mechanistically plausible but not established by fitness data \\u2014 demoted from finding to working hypothesis\"\n        ],\n        \"citations\": [\n          \"Price2018\"\n        ]\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"The Path B null result is not a failure to detect something real \\u2014 it is telling us something specific and biologically important about where the mechanistic evidence reaches and where it stops.\\n\\nAt the transcript level, the SspB buffering effect is real and measurable. Notebook 01 cell 5 shows that 53 of the 93 Leaden \\u0394fur DEGs are blunted in our \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB 4584-vs-4580 data \\u2014 near-zero logFC in our strain despite logFC of \\u22125 to \\u22129 in Leaden's \\u0394fur-alone data. That buffered set is dominated by the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon (CCNA_01466\\u201301476: ccoNOPQ, cydCDA, fixGHI). This transcript-level buffering is what distinguishes the \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB double deletion from a \\u0394fur single in the Leaden comparison, and it is a clean novel transcriptomic observation that required our strain design to detect.\\n\\nBut the Caulobacter Fitness Browser data tell a different story about mechanistic specificity under envelope stress. At 34.6% phenotype-bearing (9 of 26 genes), fold 1.04\\u00d7, p=0.515, the SspB-buffered set is indistinguishable from any randomly drawn 26 Caulobacter genes under the same 22 envelope-stress experiments. REPORT \\u00a7Limitations states: \\\"The fitness data do not selectively support the cbb3/fix genes as more critical than randomly drawn Caulobacter genes under envelope stress.\\\" REPORT \\u00a7Interpretation \\u00a72 demotes the respiratory arm explicitly: \\\"The 'respiratory ATP required' arm of the dual-release switch model is therefore a working hypothesis, not an established finding.\\\" The mechanistic rationale remains plausible \\u2014 cell division without lipid A, sphingolipid transport, and outer-membrane maintenance are energy-intensive processes \\u2014 but plausible is precisely where the evidence leaves it.\\n\\nWhen the audience asks \\\"doesn't the respiratory chain need to be active?\\\" the correct answer is yes, but needing to be active and being selectively enriched for phenotype under envelope stress are different claims. The fitness data test the latter; Path B fails that test. The transcript data and the fitness data are measuring different things: one shows \\u0394sspB stabilizes cbb3/fix transcripts, the other shows those transcripts do not map to genes enriched for fitness impact under envelope stress. We cannot currently distinguish \\\"respiratory protection matters but is too pleiotropic to appear as enrichment\\\" from \\\"respiratory protection is not specifically required here.\\\" That ambiguity is the honest state of the evidence. Having partitioned the Fur-released arms \\u2014 Path A carries the envelope-stress fitness signal, Path B does not \\u2014 the talk moves to S3, which asks what the Fur-set envelope state triggers downstream: the ChvI two-phase regulatory response.\",\n      \"id\": 12,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S2\",\n      \"position\": 12\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"section_divider\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"punchline\": \"The Fur-set envelope state triggers a two-phase ChvI response; its late regulator stays open.\",\n        \"substory_number\": 3\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"Coming off S2's Path A/B partition \\u2014 where we showed that only the Fur-released TBDT subset enriches for envelope-stress fitness at fold 1.60\\u00d7 over the 33.25% genome background, while the SspB-buffered respiratory arm falls to fold 1.04\\u00d7 \\u2014 we now follow the Fur-set envelope state into the regulatory signaling layer. S3 asks not which Fur targets carry the fitness signal, but what the Fur-established envelope state activates at the transcriptional-sensor level. The sensor is ChvG-ChvI, Caulobacter's dedicated two-component envelope-homeostasis system.\\n\\nThe argument of S3 divides into two honest halves. The first is what the driver demonstrably activates: the ChvI regulon partitions into three fully disjoint phases across our strain-series contrasts \\u2014 20 genes unique-to-early (Fur-release-coincident), 10 in both phases (cooperative continuation), and 49 late-consequence genes responding specifically to lipid-A loss. All three cohorts clear the pre-registered \\u226510-gene phase-structure threshold strongly, and the partition is robust and descriptive. The H1 phase-structure verdict is SUPPORTED. The second half is what we could not resolve: the SigU coherence test, the pre-registered sub-hypothesis for what drives the late 49-gene cohort, returned 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment with Fisher p=0.243 \\u2014 below both the statistical significance threshold and the 50% relaxed criterion. The late-cohort driver is genuinely unassigned in this work, and that is the honest state of the evidence.\\n\\nWhat makes this partition meaningful \\u2014 and what distinguishes it from any prior ChvI description \\u2014 is the three-strain design established in S1. By holding the Fur/SspB permissive state constant in the early contrast (4584-vs-4580, LpxC still present) and then comparing it to the lipid-A-deficient state (4599-vs-4584, LpxC deleted), we can separate what ChvI does because of Fur derepression from what it does specifically because lipid A is lost. That contrast design is what makes the early/late phase partition interpretable as a biological result rather than a condition-confounded composite. The adversarial review also raised ChvR sRNA as an untested post-transcriptional confound on the late cohort; we acknowledge it as an open question with no resolution in this dataset. The three content slides in this section walk through the method setup, the partition counts and exemplars, and the SigU/ChvR open question in order.\",\n      \"id\": 13,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n      \"position\": 13\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"methods_summary\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"ChvI phase partition: two published regulons cross-referenced against our strain-series contrasts\",\n        \"bullets\": [\n          \"ChvI reference regulon: union of Stein 2021 (PMID 34124942) + Quintero-Yanes 2022 (PMID 36480504) \\u2014 488 ChvI-induced genes in the C. crescentus NA1000 tested universe\",\n          \"Early-phase contrast (4584-vs-4580): \\u0394fur \\u0394sspb \\u0394rsaA vs \\u0394rsaA \\u2014 captures co-release of Fur suppression and SspB buffering, LpxC still present\",\n          \"Late-phase contrast (4599-vs-4584): \\u0394lpxc rescue vs dual-release intermediate \\u2014 isolates ChvI response to lipid-A loss with Fur/SspB permissive state already established\",\n          \"Phase assignment: three fully disjoint sets (unique-to-early / both-phase / late-consequence); no gene counted in two cohorts; total engaged = 79 genes\",\n          \"Pre-registered phase-structure threshold: \\u226510 genes per cohort required for H1 phase-structure verdict (RESEARCH_PLAN \\u00a7hypotheses)\",\n          \"SigU coherence test: Fisher exact enrichment of envelope/transport/regulator categories in late cohort vs unique-to-early; relaxed pass bar = 50% enrichment + p<1e-3\",\n          \"ChvR sRNA (Fr\\u00f6hlich 2018; adversarial review N3) acknowledged as untested post-transcriptional alternative \\u2014 not in this dataset\"\n        ],\n        \"tools_versions\": [\n          {\n            \"tool\": \"edgeR\",\n            \"version\": \"unknown\"\n          }\n        ],\n        \"see_notes_footer\": true\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"The foundation for this analysis is the ChvI reference regulon \\u2014 488 ChvI-induced genes assembled as the union of two independent published datasets. Stein 2021 characterized the ChvG-ChvI system via deletion in defined medium; Quintero-Yanes 2022 captured ChvI response under vancomycin and osmotic stress in C. crescentus NA1000. Taking their union gives the broadest possible ChvI-induced working universe, avoiding gene dropout caused by condition-specific induction in either study alone. Any ChvI-regulated gene appearing in at least one of those two published regulons is eligible for phase assignment in our data.\\n\\nThe early-phase contrast is 4584-vs-4580: \\u0394fur \\u0394sspB \\u0394rsaA versus the \\u0394rsaA parent. This captures the combined dual-release state \\u2014 Fur suppression and SspB buffering are both removed \\u2014 while LpxC remains fully intact. The cell is not yet lipid-A-deficient in this contrast; the Fur/SspB permissive state is established, but the envelope is structurally complete. The late-phase contrast is 4599-vs-4584: the \\u0394lpxC rescue state versus the dual-release intermediate. This isolates what ChvI does specifically in response to lipid-A loss, with the Fur/SspB permissive state already present and held constant across the comparison. The phase assignment is fully disjoint: every gene appears in exactly one cohort. The three counts \\u2014 20 unique-to-early, 10 both-phase, 49 late-consequence \\u2014 sum to 79 total engaged ChvI-regulon genes, and no gene is counted in two cohorts.\\n\\nThe pre-registered threshold for the H1 phase-structure verdict was \\u226510 genes per cohort (RESEARCH_PLAN \\u00a7hypotheses H1). This prevents a handful of coincidental regulon overlaps from being interpreted as a biological phase. All three cohorts clear the threshold strongly, and the H1 verdict is SUPPORTED. The SigU coherence test was the pre-registered H1 sub-hypothesis: if SigU is the late-cohort driver, the late 49 genes should enrich for envelope/transport/regulator functional categories relative to the early 20. The relaxed criterion \\u2014 50% enrichment instead of the original 75%, p<1e-3 instead of p<0.05 \\u2014 gave SigU the best possible inferential chance. The adversarial review (N3) flagged ChvR sRNA as a post-transcriptional alternative for late-cohort modulation; we lack ChvR expression data in our strain backgrounds, so this confound is acknowledged but unresolved. One scope caveat spanning the whole section: everything here describes the ChvI response to our specific Fur/SspB/LpxC perturbation series under PYE-rich conditions. The phase structure under other envelope stresses or growth media has not been measured. The next slide shows the three-phase cohort counts and their exemplar genes.\",\n      \"id\": 14,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n      \"position\": 14\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"data_table\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"ChvI two-phase partition: ChvI autoregulation sits in the both-phase cohort\",\n        \"columns\": [\n          \"Phase\",\n          \"n genes\",\n          \"Key exemplars (log2FC)\",\n          \"Functional theme\"\n        ],\n        \"rows\": [\n          [\n            \"Unique-to-early\",\n            \"20\",\n            \"CCNA_02794 +8.6, ApbE +3.8, imuB +1.5\",\n            \"Regulator/SOS (6.7% TCS)\"\n          ],\n          [\n            \"Both-phase (cooperative)\",\n            \"10\",\n            \"ChvI +1.45, CCNA_02378 +1.9\\u2192+3.9, CpxP-like CCNA_03997\",\n            \"Cooperative continuation\"\n          ],\n          [\n            \"Late-consequence\",\n            \"49\",\n            \"LolA-family +2.89, Pal +2.08, multiple TBDTs\",\n            \"Envelope/OM structural (10.2% OM, 12.2% TBDT)\"\n          ]\n        ],\n        \"caption\": \"Disjoint ChvI partition (79 total); all cohorts clear \\u226510-gene threshold. Both-phase row: ChvI autoregulation (logFC +1.45) and CpxP-like chaperone engagement. Late row: shift to envelope-structural effectors.\",\n        \"footnote\": \"Full gene-by-gene assignment in data/NB03_chvi_phase_cohorts.csv (n=89); theme breakdown in data/NB03_phase_cohort_themes.csv.\",\n        \"data_source\": \"REPORT.md \\u00a7Finding 3; nb 03_chvi_phase_partition_sigU.ipynb cell 7\",\n        \"highlight_rows\": [\n          2\n        ]\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"The three-phase ChvI partition shown here \\u2014 20 unique-to-early, 10 both-phase, and 49 late-consequence genes \\u2014 is the core H1 result. All counts are verbatim from REPORT \\u00a7Finding 3 and NB03 cell 7; together they total 79 ChvI-induced genes engaged across at least one contrast in our strain series.\\n\\nThe unique-to-early cohort is notable for its stress-responder composition. The lasso peptide cyclase CCNA_02794 at logFC +8.6 is the highest-magnitude early hit. ApbE, the iron-sulfur cluster repair protein, registers at +3.8. ImuB, the SOS DNA polymerase, registers at +1.5. That imuB entry is mechanistically connecting \\u2014 Leaden 2018 documented SOS activation as part of the \\u0394fur transcriptional program, and seeing imuB at +1.5 in the early-phase ChvI cohort confirms that the SOS and ChvI regulatory responses share the same precipitating event: constitutive Fur derepression in our strain. These are not independent signals; they are two readouts of the same Fur-release event appearing in different analytical layers, and together they corroborate the S1 driver claim.\\n\\nThe both-phase cohort contains the mechanistically critical observation: ChvI itself, CCNA_00237 at logFC +1.45 in the 4584-vs-4580 early contrast, sits in this set \\u2014 direct autoregulation evidence. Once the ChvG-ChvI system activates during the Fur/SspB release phase, ChvI sustains its own transcription through the lipid-A-loss transition. The SIMPL-family CCNA_02378 shows progressive amplification: logFC +1.9 in the early contrast increasing to +3.9 in the late, consistent with continued engagement as LpxC is actually deleted. The amelogenin/CpxP-related CCNA_03997 is notable context \\u2014 CpxP in E. coli is the periplasmic chaperone partner of the CpxA envelope-stress sensor, making CCNA_03997 a Caulobacter echo of cross-sensor envelope-stress signaling.\\n\\nThe late cohort shows a functional theme shift toward envelope and outer-membrane structural effectors \\u2014 10.2% envelope/OM and 12.2% TBDT genes among the 49, versus 6.7% regulator/TCS in the unique-to-early 20. The LolA-family OM lipoprotein carrier CCNA_03820 registers at logFC +2.89; the Pal-like CCNA_00784 at +2.08. This theme shift is suggestive of a regulatory-to-structural handoff as lipid-A loss is established, but the Fisher exact test of envelope/transport/regulator enrichment in the late cohort versus the unique-to-early cohort returned p=0.243 \\u2014 the theme shift is descriptive and not statistically discriminated at these cohort sizes. The partition counts and exemplars are the robust, pre-registered result; thematic interpretation is illustrative and stated as such. The next slide addresses the key open question: what transcriptional driver controls the late 49-gene cohort.\",\n      \"id\": 15,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n      \"position\": 15\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"claim_evidence\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"SigU coherence fails the pre-registered bar (24.5%, p=0.243); late-cohort driver unassigned\",\n        \"bullets\": [\n          \"SigU coherence in late 49-gene cohort: 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment, Fisher p=0.243 \\u2014 below both the 50% relaxed criterion and statistical significance; H1 SigU sub-hypothesis is not supported\",\n          \"SigU (CCNA_02977) has published alphaproteobacterial literature; targeted SigU-induction RNA-seq (Future Directions \\u00a72) is the pre-planned next step to resolve whether SigU drives this specific cohort\",\n          \"ChvR sRNA (Fr\\u00f6hlich 2018, adversarial review N3) is an untested post-transcriptional alternative for late-cohort modulation; late-cohort regulatory attribution remains open pending both experiments\"\n        ],\n        \"citations\": [\n          \"QuinteroYanes2022\",\n          \"Greenwich2023\"\n        ]\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"The largest ChvI cohort \\u2014 49 late-consequence genes induced only after lipid-A loss \\u2014 does not have an identified transcriptional driver in this dataset, and that is the honest result the speaker delivers without softening it in either direction.\\n\\nThe pre-registered SigU coherence test (RESEARCH_PLAN \\u00a7hypotheses H1, NB03 cell 10) returned 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment in the late 49 genes with Fisher p=0.243. From REPORT \\u00a7Finding 3: \\\"The reframed SigU coherence check on the late cohort returned 24.5% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment \\u2014 below the 50% relaxed criterion.\\\" From REPORT \\u00a7Limitations: \\\"even the relaxed criterion did not pass (Fisher p=0.243).\\\" This is a genuine negative at the pre-registered bar. The 24.5% figure means roughly one in four late-cohort genes fall into the expected functional categories. For a membrane-centric organism where those categories represent a substantial fraction of the genome, this offers no discriminatory signal above what a random draw of 49 genes would produce.\\n\\nThe test does not falsify SigU as a regulator of the Caulobacter envelope-stress response more broadly. Adversarial review N2 corrected an earlier framing in this project: SigU does have published characterization in alphaproteobacteria, so the accurate framing is \\\"late-cohort driver unassigned\\\" rather than \\\"no candidate identified.\\\" The coherence test asks whether this specific 49-gene set, under this specific lipid-A-loss perturbation, shows the functional composition expected of a SigU-driven regulon. At 24.5% and p=0.243, the answer is no. The planned next experiment is ectopic vanillate-inducible SigU overexpression RNA-seq in the 4599 background (REPORT Future Directions \\u00a72). That experiment would directly test whether a SigU-induced regulon overlaps the late 49-gene cohort and resolve the attribution question. What we have here is an honest absence of support for a specific mechanistic claim, not a disproven hypothesis about SigU's biology.\\n\\nThe ChvR sRNA layer, flagged by adversarial review N3, adds a second source of late-cohort uncertainty. ChvR provides post-transcriptional modulation of ChvI-pathway output in Caulobacter and could sculpt late-cohort composition independently of any sigma-factor logic. We have no ChvR expression data in our strain backgrounds; this gap is explicitly acknowledged and represents a known next experiment, not a failure of the current design. When the audience asks what drives the late cohort, the correct answer is: we do not know, the pre-registered test did not support SigU, and two experiments \\u2014 SigU-induction RNA-seq and ChvR characterization in this background \\u2014 are the planned resolution path. With the ChvI two-phase response characterized and its late driver acknowledged as open, S4 takes over to ask what the cell physically does to maintain the envelope without lipid A. Constitutive sphingolipids and reorganized peptidoglycan carry cleaner direct-tier evidence than the signaling layer just covered, and they are the structural-effector complement to the regulatory picture S3 has built.\",\n      \"id\": 16,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S3\",\n      \"position\": 16\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"section_divider\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"punchline\": \"Without lipid A, constitutive sphingolipids and reorganized peptidoglycan hold the envelope together.\",\n        \"substory_number\": 4\n      },\n      \"speaker_notes\": \"S3 established the signaling layer: the Fur-set envelope state triggers a two-phase ChvI response \\u2014 20 unique-to-early genes, 10 both-phase, and 49 late-consequence \\u2014 and closed with one honest gap: the late-cohort driver was not supported at the pre-registered bar, with SigU coherence at 24.5% and Fisher p=0.243. S4 leaves that open regulatory question behind and asks the structural question that follows it: once lipid A is physically absent from the outer membrane, what holds the envelope together?\\n\\nThe experimental lens is the 4599-vs-4584 contrast \\u2014 strain 4599 (\\u0394fur \\u0394sspB \\u0394lpxC \\u0394rsaA) against its direct precursor 4584 (\\u0394fur \\u0394sspB \\u0394rsaA) \\u2014 designed to isolate the \\u0394lpxC-specific structural response with the Fur and SspB permissive state already present and constant across both sides of the comparison. Zik et al. 2022 established the biological preconditions for this comparison: \\u0394fur is genetically required for \\u0394lpxC viability, and anionic sphingolipid ceramide phosphoglycerate is required as well. S4 asks which molecular changes at the lipid and peptidoglycan layers explain why a cell meeting those two conditions can survive without lipid A.\\n\\nThe evidence yields two answers with direct-tier support and two with important caveats. The well-supported answers are sphingolipid constitutivity \\u2014 the biosynthesis pathway was already running at baseline, with zero of six core genes induced when lipid A is lost \\u2014 and peptidoglycan reorganization, where a specific lytic transglycosylase and the Pal-Tol complex engage against a backdrop of broad synthesis suppression. The partial answers are the Lpt transport apparatus, where transcript and protein evidence point in opposite directions and require replicated proteomics to resolve, and the CtpA processing step predicted by Zik 2022, which is rejected at our pre-registered evidential bar. Keeping those grades distinct \\u2014 not flattening them into a uniform \\\"supported\\\" story \\u2014 is the core responsibility of S4's delivery. The methods slide establishes both modalities before any results appear.\",\n      \"id\": 17,\n      \"substory_id\": \"S4\",\n      \"position\": 17\n    },\n    {\n      \"layout\": \"methods_summary\",\n      \"content\": {\n        \"title\": \"Measuring the structural-effector response: transcript panel and single-replicate OM proteome\",\n        \"bullets\": [\n          \"Strain contrast: 4599 (delta-fur delta-sspB delta-lpxc delta-rsaA) vs 4584 (delta-fur delta-sspB delta-rsaA) \\u2014 isolates the delta-lpxc-specific response net of Fur and SspB co-deletions\",\n          \"Transcriptomics: edgeR differential expression, FDR < 0.05 threshold; 3,943 Caulobacter protein-coding genes tested\",\n          \"Sphingolipid panel: 6 core biosynthesis genes (spt, sphk, cerS, cerR, cpgB, cpgD) + 3 Uchendu 2026 IM transporter genes (lptG2/F2/C2) tested for induction vs constitutivity\",\n          \"Canonical Lpt apparatus: 6 transport components (MsbA, LptA-G) checked for maintenance vs remodeling in delta-lpxc state\",\n          \"PG remodeling gene set: 53 loci pre-curated before DE analysis (transpeptidase, transglycosylase, amidase, hydrolase families); 28 meet H4 threshold (FDR < 0.05 OR |log2| > 1 at protein)\",\n          \"OM proteome: single-replicate mass-spectrometry per strain (4580 WT, 4584 intermediate, 4672 rescued); direction interpretable, no per-protein statistics\",\n          \"CtpA test: pre-registered BORDERLINE criterion (0.05 < pvalue < 0.15 AND protein detected in OM proteome) applied to 4599-vs-4584 contrast exclusively\"\n        ],\n        \"tools_versions\": [\n          {\n            \"tool\": \"edgeR\",\n            \"version\": \"unknown\"\n          }","numLines":300,"startLine":200,"totalLines":817}}}
