{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01Ccju4sVAkVKmsKRHmVAKTP","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"entries\": [\n3\t    {\n4\t      \"authors\": [\n5\t        \"Raetz CRH\",\n6\t        \"Whitfield C\"\n7\t      ],\n8\t      \"year\": 2002,\n9\t      \"title\": \"Lipopolysaccharide endotoxins\",\n10\t      \"venue\": \"Annu Rev Biochem 71:635-700\",\n11\t      \"doi\": \"10.1146/annurev.biochem.71.110601.135414\",\n12\t      \"pmid\": \"12045108\",\n13\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2569852\",\n14\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n15\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n16\t      \"studied\": \"Gram-negative bacteria broadly; lipid A structure, biosynthesis (Raetz pathway), transport, and TLR4 signaling\",\n17\t      \"finding\": \"Lipid A biosynthesis follows the conserved nine-step Raetz pathway; lipid A-Kdo2 is the minimal LPS structure required for outer membrane biogenesis in most Gram-negatives. LpxC validated as an antibiotic target.\",\n18\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n19\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n20\t      \"is_review_article\": true,\n21\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n22\t      \"notes\": \"Foundational LPS review; establishes the lipid A essentiality paradigm that Caulobacter violates. Serves Introduction background.\",\n23\t      \"bib_key\": \"Raetz2002\"\n24\t    },\n25\t    {\n26\t      \"authors\": [\n27\t        \"Zik JJ\",\n28\t        \"Yoon SH\",\n29\t        \"Guan Z\",\n30\t        \"Stankeviciute Skidmore G\",\n31\t        \"Gudoor RR\",\n32\t        \"Davies KM\",\n33\t        \"Deutschbauer AM\",\n34\t        \"Goodlett DR\",\n35\t        \"Klein EA\",\n36\t        \"Ryan KR\"\n37\t      ],\n38\t      \"year\": 2022,\n39\t      \"title\": \"Caulobacter lipid A is conditionally dispensable in the absence of fur and in the presence of anionic sphingolipids\",\n40\t      \"venue\": \"Cell Rep 39(9):110888\",\n41\t      \"doi\": \"10.1016/j.celrep.2022.110888\",\n42\t      \"pmid\": \"35649364\",\n43\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC9393093\",\n44\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n45\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n46\t      \"studied\": \"Caulobacter crescentus NA1000; Δfur, ΔlpxC, ΔctpA mutants; genetics, lipidomics, suppressor analysis\",\n47\t      \"finding\": \"Mutations in fur allow C. crescentus to survive without LpxC or CtpA; viability requires anionic sphingolipid ceramide phosphoglycerate (CPG). 'Alterations in Fur-regulated processes, rather than iron status per se, underlie the ability to survive when lipid A synthesis is blocked.'\",\n48\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n49\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n50\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n51\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n52\t      \"notes\": \"Keystone paper for the entire throughline. Establishes the Δfur + sphingolipid mechanism. Ryan lab collaboration source.\",\n53\t      \"bib_key\": \"Zik2022\"\n54\t    },\n55\t    {\n56\t      \"authors\": [\n57\t        \"Uchendu CG\",\n58\t        \"Isom GL\",\n59\t        \"Klein EA\"\n60\t      ],\n61\t      \"year\": 2026,\n62\t      \"title\": \"Homologues of the inner-membrane LPS transport proteins are required for sphingolipid transport in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n63\t      \"venue\": \"bioRxiv 2026.04.12.717747\",\n64\t      \"doi\": \"10.1101/2026.04.12.717747\",\n65\t      \"pmid\": null,\n66\t      \"pmcid\": null,\n67\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n68\t      \"biorxiv\": \"2026.04.12.717747\",\n69\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus lipid-A-deficient strains; inner membrane lipid transport complex\",\n70\t      \"finding\": \"Homologues of inner-membrane LPS transport proteins (Lpt paralogs) are required for sphingolipid transport in lipid-A-deficient Caulobacter; identifies shared Lpt machinery components for CPG trafficking.\",\n71\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n72\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n73\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n74\t      \"is_preprint\": true,\n75\t      \"notes\": \"Directly supports throughline sub-claim on Lpt apparatus repurposing for sphingolipid transport. Most recent Klein lab follow-up.\",\n76\t      \"bib_key\": \"Uchendu2026\"\n77\t    },\n78\t    {\n79\t      \"authors\": [\n80\t        \"Dhakephalkar T\",\n81\t        \"Stukey GJ\",\n82\t        \"Guan Z\",\n83\t        \"Carman GM\",\n84\t        \"Klein EA\"\n85\t      ],\n86\t      \"year\": 2023,\n87\t      \"title\": \"Characterization of an evolutionarily distinct bacterial ceramide kinase from Caulobacter crescentus\",\n88\t      \"venue\": \"J Biol Chem 299(7):104894\",\n89\t      \"doi\": \"10.1016/j.jbc.2023.104894\",\n90\t      \"pmid\": \"37286040\",\n91\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC10331486\",\n92\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n93\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n94\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus CpgB recombinant protein; enzyme kinetics in vitro\",\n95\t      \"finding\": \"CpgB is an evolutionarily distinct bacterial ceramide kinase: Km = 19.2 +/- 5.5 uM for NBD C6-ceramide, Vmax = 2590 +/- 230 pmol/min/mg. Phylogenetically distinct from eukaryotic ceramide kinases; NVP-231 inhibitor has no effect.\",\n96\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n97\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n98\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n99\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n100\t      \"notes\": \"First step in CPG head-group biosynthesis. Supports constitutive sphingolipid biosynthesis sub-claim.\",\n101\t      \"bib_key\": \"Dhakephalkar2023\"\n102\t    },\n103\t    {\n104\t      \"authors\": [\n105\t        \"Dhakephalkar T\",\n106\t        \"Guan Z\",\n107\t        \"Klein EA\"\n108\t      ],\n109\t      \"year\": 2025,\n110\t      \"title\": \"CpgD is a phosphoglycerate cytidylyltransferase required for ceramide diphosphoglycerate synthesis\",\n111\t      \"venue\": \"bioRxiv 2025.01.09.632243\",\n112\t      \"doi\": \"10.1101/2025.01.09.632243\",\n113\t      \"pmid\": \"39829823\",\n114\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC11741362\",\n115\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n116\t      \"biorxiv\": \"2025.01.09.632243\",\n117\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus CpgD (CCNA_01210) recombinant protein; enzyme kinetics in vitro\",\n118\t      \"finding\": \"CpgD is a phosphoglycerate cytidylyltransferase producing CDP-glycerate from CTP and 3-phosphoglycerate (Km,app = 10.9 +/- 0.7 mM for 3-PG); required for ceramide diphosphoglycerate (CPG2) synthesis.\",\n119\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n120\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n121\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n122\t      \"is_preprint\": true,\n123\t      \"notes\": \"PubMed-indexed as preprint (bioRxiv). Supports constitutive sphingolipid biosynthesis sub-claim.\",\n124\t      \"bib_key\": \"Dhakephalkar2025\"\n125\t    },\n126\t    {\n127\t      \"authors\": [\n128\t        \"Olea-Ozuna RJ\",\n129\t        \"Poggio S\",\n130\t        \"Bergstrom E\",\n131\t        \"Quiroz-Rocha E\",\n132\t        \"Garcia-Soriano DA\",\n133\t        \"Sahonero-Canavesi DX\",\n134\t        \"Padilla-Gomez J\",\n135\t        \"Martinez-Aguilar L\",\n136\t        \"Lopez-Lara IM\",\n137\t        \"Thomas-Oates J\",\n138\t        \"Geiger O\"\n139\t      ],\n140\t      \"year\": 2021,\n141\t      \"title\": \"Five structural genes required for ceramide synthesis in Caulobacter and for bacterial survival\",\n142\t      \"venue\": \"Environ Microbiol 23(1):143-159\",\n143\t      \"doi\": \"10.1111/1462-2920.15280\",\n144\t      \"pmid\": \"33063925\",\n145\t      \"pmcid\": null,\n146\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n147\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n148\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; Δspt and cofitness-linked mutants; lipid analysis, growth/survival assays\",\n149\t      \"finding\": \"Five structural genes required for dihydroceramide biosynthesis; sphingolipid biosynthesis needed for stationary-phase survival and OM integrity. Δspt mutant has much reduced survival at elevated temperatures.\",\n150\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n151\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n152\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n153\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n154\t      \"notes\": \"Establishes the ceramide biosynthetic pathway including spt. Supports constitutive sphingolipid biosynthesis sub-claim (evidence map row 6).\",\n155\t      \"bib_key\": \"OleaOzuna2021\"\n156\t    },\n157\t    {\n158\t      \"authors\": [\n159\t        \"Olea-Ozuna RJ\",\n160\t        \"Poggio S\",\n161\t        \"Bergstrom E\",\n162\t        \"Osorio A\",\n163\t        \"Elufisan TO\",\n164\t        \"Padilla-Gomez J\",\n165\t        \"Martinez-Aguilar L\",\n166\t        \"Lopez-Lara IM\",\n167\t        \"Thomas-Oates J\",\n168\t        \"Geiger O\"\n169\t      ],\n170\t      \"year\": 2024,\n171\t      \"title\": \"Genes required for phosphosphingolipid formation in Caulobacter crescentus contribute to bacterial virulence\",\n172\t      \"venue\": \"PLoS Pathog 20(8):e1012401\",\n173\t      \"doi\": \"10.1371/journal.ppat.1012401\",\n174\t      \"pmid\": \"39093898\",\n175\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC11324152\",\n176\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n177\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n178\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; 11 sphingolipid biosynthesis genes; polymyxin B sensitivity; Galleria mellonella virulence model\",\n179\t      \"finding\": \"At least 11 genes participate in phosphosphingolipid formation; all required for membrane stability and polymyxin B sensitivity. Sphingolipid genes contribute to C. crescentus virulence on G. mellonella.\",\n180\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n181\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n182\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n183\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n184\t      \"notes\": \"Extends sphingolipid pathway from 5 to 11 genes. Supports constitutive sphingolipid biosynthesis sub-claim.\",\n185\t      \"bib_key\": \"OleaOzuna2024\"\n186\t    },\n187\t    {\n188\t      \"authors\": [\n189\t        \"Hummels KR\"\n190\t      ],\n191\t      \"year\": 2024,\n192\t      \"title\": \"mSphere of Influence: Celebrating exceptions to the rule of lipid A essentiality\",\n193\t      \"venue\": \"mSphere 9(3):e0063323\",\n194\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/msphere.00633-23\",\n195\t      \"pmid\": \"38421175\",\n196\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC10964400\",\n197\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n198\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n199\t      \"studied\": \"Comparative review of A. baumannii (Boll lab, PG-remodeling route) and C. crescentus (Zik/Ryan, fur + sphingolipid route) lipid A dispensability\",\n200\t      \"finding\": \"Exceptions to lipid A essentiality illuminate distinct bacterial strategies: A. baumannii uses PBP1A loss + ld-transpeptidase PG remodeling, while C. crescentus relies on Fur derepression + anionic sphingolipid substitution.\",\n201\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n202\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n203\t      \"is_review_article\": true,\n204\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n205\t      \"notes\": \"Commentary framing piece; directly compares the two known lipid A dispensability routes. Serves Introduction + Discussion context.\",\n206\t      \"bib_key\": \"Hummels2024\"\n207\t    },\n208\t    {\n209\t      \"authors\": [\n210\t        \"Langklotz S\",\n211\t        \"Schakermann M\",\n212\t        \"Narberhaus F\"\n213\t      ],\n214\t      \"year\": 2011,\n215\t      \"title\": \"Control of lipopolysaccharide biosynthesis by FtsH-mediated proteolysis of LpxC is conserved in enterobacteria but not in all gram-negative bacteria\",\n216\t      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 193(5):1090-1097\",\n217\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.01043-10\",\n218\t      \"pmid\": \"21193611\",\n219\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC3067583\",\n220\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n221\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n222\t      \"studied\": \"E. coli, Salmonella, Yersinia, Vibrio, Agrobacterium tumefaciens, Rhodobacter capsulatus, Pseudomonas aeruginosa; FtsH-mediated LpxC proteolysis\",\n223\t      \"finding\": \"FtsH-mediated LpxC proteolysis is conserved in Enterobacteriaceae but NOT in all Gram-negatives. A. tumefaciens and R. capsulatus LpxC degraded by Lon protease; P. aeruginosa LpxC is stable. Alphaproteobacteria may use non-FtsH mechanisms.\",\n224\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n225\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n226\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n227\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n228\t      \"notes\": \"Relevant to why LpxC dynamics in Caulobacter differ from E. coli. Supports species-specificity sub-claim.\",\n229\t      \"bib_key\": \"Langklotz2011\"\n230\t    },\n231\t    {\n232\t      \"authors\": [\n233\t        \"Leaden L\",\n234\t        \"Silva LG\",\n235\t        \"Ribeiro RA\",\n236\t        \"Dos Santos NM\",\n237\t        \"Lorenzetti APR\",\n238\t        \"Alegria TGP\",\n239\t        \"Schulz ML\",\n240\t        \"Medeiros MHG\",\n241\t        \"Koide T\",\n242\t        \"Marques MV\"\n243\t      ],\n244\t      \"year\": 2018,\n245\t      \"title\": \"Iron Deficiency Generates Oxidative Stress and Activation of the SOS Response in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n246\t      \"venue\": \"Front Microbiol 9:2014\",\n247\t      \"doi\": \"10.3389/fmicb.2018.02014\",\n248\t      \"pmid\": \"30210482\",\n249\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC6120978\",\n250\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n251\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n252\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000 wild type under iron limitation (2,2'-dipyridyl) and Δfur mutant; RNA-seq\",\n253\t      \"finding\": \"Identified 256 upregulated and 236 downregulated genes under iron limitation; 176 and 204 newly identified respectively. Sixteen transcription factors and seven sRNAs upregulated. Iron deficiency causes endogenous oxidative stress and SOS response activation.\",\n254\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n255\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n256\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n257\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n258\t      \"notes\": \"Primary reference for Caulobacter Fur regulon RNA-seq. Directly used in NB01 for Leaden DEG set comparison (evidence map row 3).\",\n259\t      \"bib_key\": \"Leaden2018\"\n260\t    },\n261\t    {\n262\t      \"authors\": [\n263\t        \"da Silva Neto JF\",\n264\t        \"Braz VS\",\n265\t        \"Italiani VCS\",\n266\t        \"Marques MV\"\n267\t      ],\n268\t      \"year\": 2009,\n269\t      \"title\": \"Fur controls iron homeostasis and oxidative stress defense in the oligotrophic alpha-proteobacterium Caulobacter crescentus\",\n270\t      \"venue\": \"Nucleic Acids Res 37(14):4812-4825\",\n271\t      \"doi\": \"10.1093/nar/gkp509\",\n272\t      \"pmid\": \"19520766\",\n273\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2724300\",\n274\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n275\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n276\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000 Δfur mutant; ChIP + microarray + bioinformatics for Fur-binding sites\",\n277\t      \"finding\": \"Fur functions as both activator and repressor, integrating iron metabolism and oxidative stress response. Iron uptake genes repressed by iron-Fur and induced under iron limitation; iron-using protein genes activated by Fur under iron sufficiency.\",\n278\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n279\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n280\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n281\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n282\t      \"notes\": \"Earlier ChIP/microarray Caulobacter Fur regulon paper; frequently cited by the Klein/Ryan group. Supports Fur-released transport sub-claim (evidence map row 1).\",\n283\t      \"bib_key\": \"Neto2009\"\n284\t    },\n285\t    {\n286\t      \"authors\": [\n287\t        \"Dos Santos NM\",\n288\t        \"Picinato BA\",\n289\t        \"Santos LS\",\n290\t        \"de Araujo HL\",\n291\t        \"Balan A\",\n292\t        \"Koide T\",\n293\t        \"Marques MV\"\n294\t      ],\n295\t      \"year\": 2024,\n296\t      \"title\": \"Mapping the IscR regulon sheds light on the regulation of iron homeostasis in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n297\t      \"venue\": \"Front Microbiol 15:1463854\",\n298\t      \"doi\": \"10.3389/fmicb.2024.1463854\",\n299\t      \"pmid\": \"39411446\",\n300\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC11475020\",\n301\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n302\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n303\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000 ΔiscR mutant; RNA-seq + ChIP-seq; 302-gene IscR regulon\",\n304\t      \"finding\": \"IscR regulon comprises 302 genes with partial Fur overlap. IscR represses the respiration regulator FixK, fine-tuning gene regulation in response to iron and redox balance. Two distinct IscR binding motifs identified.\",\n305\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n306\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n307\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n308\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n309\t      \"notes\": \"IscR/Fur overlap relevant to partitioning Fur-specific vs broader iron-regulon contributions. Supports evidence map row 1.\",\n310\t      \"bib_key\": \"Santos2024\"\n311\t    },\n312\t    {\n313\t      \"authors\": [\n314\t        \"Hernandez-Ortiz S\",\n315\t        \"Ok K\",\n316\t        \"O'Halloran TV\",\n317\t        \"Fiebig A\",\n318\t        \"Crosson S\"\n319\t      ],\n320\t      \"year\": 2025,\n321\t      \"title\": \"A co-conserved gene pair supports Caulobacter iron homeostasis during chelation stress\",\n322\t      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 207(4):e0048424\",\n323\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/jb.00484-24\",\n324\t      \"pmid\": \"40084995\",\n325\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC12004947\",\n326\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n327\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n328\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; RB-TnSeq under EDTA chelation; CciT (TBDT) and CciO dioxygenase\",\n329\t      \"finding\": \"CciT is a Fur-regulated TonB-dependent transporter that supports iron homeostasis during chelation stress; strictly requires co-conserved CciO (Fe2+ dioxygenase). Gene pair broadly co-conserved in Proteobacteria.\",\n330\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n331\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n332\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n333\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n334\t      \"notes\": \"Defines a specific Fur-regulated TBDT pair in Caulobacter. Supports Fur-released transport sub-claim (evidence map row 1).\",\n335\t      \"bib_key\": \"HernandezOrtiz2025\"\n336\t    },\n337\t    {\n338\t      \"authors\": [\n339\t        \"de Castro Ferreira IG\",\n340\t        \"Rodrigues MM\",\n341\t        \"da Silva Neto JF\",\n342\t        \"Mazzon RR\",\n343\t        \"do Valle Marques M\"\n344\t      ],\n345\t      \"year\": 2016,\n346\t      \"title\": \"Role and regulation of ferritin-like proteins in iron homeostasis and oxidative stress survival of Caulobacter crescentus\",\n347\t      \"venue\": \"Biometals 29(5):851-862\",\n348\t      \"doi\": \"10.1007/s10534-016-9956-y\",\n349\t      \"pmid\": \"27484774\",\n350\t      \"pmcid\": null,\n351\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n352\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n353\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; Bfr, Dps, CC_0557 ferritin-like proteins; Δbfr, Δdps mutants\",\n354\t      \"finding\": \"bfr expression positively regulated (2.5-fold) by Fe-Fur. Δdps very sensitive to H2O2; Bfr contributes to iron homeostasis, Dps to oxidative stress protection. Ferritins link Fur regulation to iron storage.\",\n355\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n356\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n357\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n358\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n359\t      \"notes\": \"Caulobacter-specific Fur-regulated iron storage. Supports Fur regulon context (evidence map row 1).\",\n360\t      \"bib_key\": \"Ferreira2016\"\n361\t    },\n362\t    {\n363\t      \"authors\": [\n364\t        \"Balhesteros H\",\n365\t        \"Shipelskiy Y\",\n366\t        \"Long NJ\",\n367\t        \"Majumdar A\",\n368\t        \"Katz BB\",\n369\t        \"Santos NM\",\n370\t        \"Leaden L\",\n371\t        \"Newton SM\",\n372\t        \"Marques MV\",\n373\t        \"Klebba PE\"\n374\t      ],\n375\t      \"year\": 2017,\n376\t      \"title\": \"TonB-Dependent Heme/Hemoglobin Utilization by Caulobacter crescentus HutA\",\n377\t      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 199(6):e00723-16\",\n378\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.00723-16\",\n379\t      \"pmid\": \"28031282\",\n380\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC5331666\",\n381\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n382\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n383\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; 62 putative TBDTs; iron transport kinetics; sarcosinate extracts + mass spectrometry\",\n384\t      \"finding\": \"Identified five TBDTs with regulated expression: three overexpressed during iron deficiency (CCNA_00028, 02277, 03023), two during iron repletion. HutA (CCNA_02277) is the first characterized C. crescentus heme/hemoglobin transporter.\",\n385\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n386\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n387\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n388\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n389\t      \"notes\": \"Fur-regulated TBDTs in Caulobacter; relevant to the n=32 TBDT subset derepressed in Δfur (evidence map row 1).\",\n390\t      \"bib_key\": \"Balhesteros2017\"\n391\t    },\n392\t    {\n393\t      \"authors\": [\n394\t        \"Silva LG\",\n395\t        \"Lorenzetti APR\",\n396\t        \"Ribeiro RA\",\n397\t        \"Alves IR\",\n398\t        \"Leaden L\",\n399\t        \"Galhardo RS\",\n400\t        \"Koide T\",\n401\t        \"Marques MV\"\n402\t      ],\n403\t      \"year\": 2019,\n404\t      \"title\": \"OxyR and the hydrogen peroxide stress response in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n405\t      \"venue\": \"Gene 700:70-84\",\n406\t      \"doi\": \"10.1016/j.gene.2019.03.003\",\n407\t      \"pmid\": \"30880241\",\n408\t      \"pmcid\": null,\n409\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n410\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n411\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000 wild type and ΔoxyR; H2O2 exposure at two time points; RNA-seq\",\n412\t      \"finding\": \"Fur and part of its regulon were differentially expressed in response to H2O2 independently of OxyR. OxyR required for expression of 103 genes in H2O2 response. Demonstrates Fur-OxyR cross-regulation under oxidative stress.\",\n413\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n414\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n415\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n416\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n417\t      \"notes\": \"Fur cross-talk with oxidative stress response; relevant to envelope stress phenotypes in the TBDT subset (evidence map row 1).\",\n418\t      \"bib_key\": \"Silva2019\"\n419\t    },\n420\t    {\n421\t      \"authors\": [\n422\t        \"Stein BJ\",\n423\t        \"Fiebig A\",\n424\t        \"Crosson S\"\n425\t      ],\n426\t      \"year\": 2021,\n427\t      \"title\": \"The ChvG-ChvI and NtrY-NtrX Two-Component Systems Coordinately Regulate Growth of Caulobacter crescentus\",\n428\t      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 203(17):e0019921\",\n429\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.00199-21\",\n430\t      \"pmid\": \"34124942\",\n431\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC8351639\",\n432\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n433\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n434\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; ΔchvG, ΔchvI, ΔntrY, ΔntrX mutants; RNA-seq for ChvI regulon; genetic suppressor analysis\",\n435\t      \"finding\": \"Defined the ChvI transcriptional regulon in C. crescentus; significant overlap with NtrX regulon. chvGI deletion limits growth in defined medium. NtrZ identified as periplasmic inhibitor of NtrY phosphatase activity.\",\n436\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n437\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n438\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n439\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n440\t      \"notes\": \"Primary ChvI regulon reference; used in NB03 for ChvI two-phase partition (evidence map row 4). Dataset in clean/chvi_overexpression_regulon_stein_2021.csv.\",\n441\t      \"bib_key\": \"Stein2021\"\n442\t    },\n443\t    {\n444\t      \"authors\": [\n445\t        \"Quintero-Yanes A\",\n446\t        \"Mayard A\",\n447\t        \"Hallez R\"\n448\t      ],\n449\t      \"year\": 2022,\n450\t      \"title\": \"The two-component system ChvGI maintains cell envelope homeostasis in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n451\t      \"venue\": \"PLoS Genet 18(12):e1010465\",\n452\t      \"doi\": \"10.1371/journal.pgen.1010465\",\n453\t      \"pmid\": \"36480504\",\n454\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC9731502\",\n455\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n456\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n457\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; chv mutants under vancomycin + osmotic stress; ChvI regulon via RNA-seq\",\n458\t      \"finding\": \"ChvI regulates cell envelope architecture controlling OM, PG assembly/recycling, and IM proteins. ChvI phosphorylation activated by vancomycin. ChvGI TCS monitors osmotic imbalances and PG damage to maintain envelope homeostasis.\",\n459\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n460\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n461\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n462\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n463\t      \"notes\": \"Independent ChvI regulon confirmation; dataset in clean/chvi_regulon_quintero_yanes_2022.csv. Supports evidence map row 4.\",\n464\t      \"bib_key\": \"QuinteroYanes2022\"\n465\t    },\n466\t    {\n467\t      \"authors\": [\n468\t        \"Greenwich JL\",\n469\t        \"Heckel BC\",\n470\t        \"Alakavuklar MA\",\n471\t        \"Fuqua C\"\n472\t      ],\n473\t      \"year\": 2023,\n474\t      \"title\": \"The ChvG-ChvI Regulatory Network: A Conserved Global Regulatory Circuit Among the Alphaproteobacteria with Pervasive Impacts on Host Interactions and Diverse Cellular Processes\",\n475\t      \"venue\": \"Annu Rev Microbiol 77:131-148\",\n476\t      \"doi\": \"10.1146/annurev-micro-120822-102714\",\n477\t      \"pmid\": \"37040790\",\n478\t      \"pmcid\": null,\n479\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n480\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n481\t      \"studied\": \"Alphaproteobacteria broadly; ChvG-ChvI conservation, ExoR regulation, regulon targets across species\",\n482\t      \"finding\": \"ChvG-ChvI is a conserved global regulatory circuit in alphaproteobacteria controlling envelope composition, virulence, biofilm, motility. Acidic pH stimulates ExoR proteolysis, activating ChvG-ChvI. Envelope stress may also generally activate.\",\n483\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n484\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n485\t      \"is_review_article\": true,\n486\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n487\t      \"notes\": \"Authoritative synthesis of ChvG-ChvI biology. Conceptual scaffold for ChvI two-phase signaling sub-claim (evidence map row 4).\",\n488\t      \"bib_key\": \"Greenwich2023\"\n489\t    },\n490\t    {\n491\t      \"authors\": [\n492\t        \"Tan WB\",\n493\t        \"Chng SS\"\n494\t      ],\n495\t      \"year\": 2025,\n496\t      \"title\": \"Primary role of the Tol-Pal complex in bacterial outer membrane lipid homeostasis\",\n497\t      \"venue\": \"Nat Commun 16(1):2293\",\n498\t      \"doi\": \"10.1038/s41467-025-57630-y\",\n499\t      \"pmid\": \"40055349\",\n500\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC11889096\",\n501\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n502\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n503\t      \"studied\": \"E. coli; chimeric Tol-Pal complex engineered to lose septal enrichment but retain OM function\",\n504\t      \"finding\": \"Primary function of Tol-Pal complex is OM lipid homeostasis (retrograde phospholipid transport), independent of its role during division. Peripherally-localized Tol-Pal fully capable of maintaining OM lipid balance.\",\n505\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n506\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n507\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n508\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n509\t      \"notes\": \"Basis for revised Pal-upregulation interpretation in Discussion (evidence map row 8). E. coli system, not Caulobacter.\",\n510\t      \"bib_key\": \"Tan2025\"\n511\t    },\n512\t    {\n513\t      \"authors\": [\n514\t        \"Yeh YC\",\n515\t        \"Comolli LR\",\n516\t        \"Downing KH\",\n517\t        \"Shapiro L\",\n518\t        \"McAdams HH\"\n519\t      ],\n520\t      \"year\": 2010,\n521\t      \"title\": \"The caulobacter Tol-Pal complex is essential for outer membrane integrity and the positioning of a polar localization factor\",\n522\t      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 192(19):4847-4858\",\n523\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.00607-10\",\n524\t      \"pmid\": \"20693330\",\n525\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2944545\",\n526\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n527\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n528\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus; TolA, TolB, Pal depletion/mutant strains; cryo-EM, fluorescence microscopy\",\n529\t      \"finding\": \"Caulobacter Tol-Pal complex is essential for OM integrity and cell division (unlike E. coli where dispensable). Components localize to division plane; Pal interacts with TipN polar localization factor.\",\n530\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n531\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n532\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n533\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n534\t      \"notes\": \"Caulobacter-specific Tol-Pal essentiality context. Pal upregulation in Δfur must be interpreted against this essential-complex background (evidence map row 8).\",\n535\t      \"bib_key\": \"Yeh2010\"\n536\t    },\n537\t    {\n538\t      \"authors\": [\n539\t        \"Kang KN\",\n540\t        \"Kazi MI\",\n541\t        \"Biboy J\",\n542\t        \"Gray J\",\n543\t        \"Bovermann H\",\n544\t        \"Ausman J\",\n545\t        \"Boutte CC\",\n546\t        \"Vollmer W\",\n547\t        \"Boll JM\"\n548\t      ],\n549\t      \"year\": 2021,\n550\t      \"title\": \"Septal Class A Penicillin-Binding Protein Activity and ld-Transpeptidases Mediate Selection of Colistin-Resistant Lipooligosaccharide-Deficient Acinetobacter baumannii\",\n551\t      \"venue\": \"mBio 12(1):e02185-20\",\n552\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/mBio.02185-20\",\n553\t      \"pmid\": \"33402533\",\n554\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC8545086\",\n555\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n556\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n557\t      \"studied\": \"A. baumannii ATCC 19606; PBP1A, LdtJ, LdtK mutants; colistin-resistant LOS-deficient isolates; transposon mutagenesis\",\n558\t      \"finding\": \"PBP1A inactivation is a compensatory mutation supporting LOS-deficient A. baumannii isolation. Both LdtJ and LdtK ld-transpeptidases required for LOS-deficient colony selection. PG remodeling is the tolerance route, NOT Fur.\",\n559\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n560\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n561\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n562\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n563\t      \"notes\": \"Direct A. baumannii comparator: PG-remodeling route vs Caulobacter sphingolipid route. Supports cross-species pathway absence sub-claim (evidence map row 9).\",\n564\t      \"bib_key\": \"Kang2021\"\n565\t    },\n566\t    {\n567\t      \"authors\": [\n568\t        \"Steeghs L\",\n569\t        \"de Cock H\",\n570\t        \"Evers E\",\n571\t        \"Zomer B\",\n572\t        \"Tommassen J\",\n573\t        \"van der Ley P\"\n574\t      ],\n575\t      \"year\": 2001,\n576\t      \"title\": \"Outer membrane composition of a lipopolysaccharide-deficient Neisseria meningitidis mutant\",\n577\t      \"venue\": \"EMBO J 20(24):6937-6945\",\n578\t      \"doi\": \"10.1093/emboj/20.24.6937\",\n579\t      \"pmid\": \"11742971\",\n580\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC125796\",\n581\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n582\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n583\t      \"studied\": \"N. meningitidis; ΔlpxA mutant; OM composition, phospholipid analysis, capsule requirement\",\n584\t      \"finding\": \"Viable lpxA-null N. meningitidis; OMP assembly largely unaffected but iron-limitation-inducible lipoprotein expression greatly reduced. Capsular polysaccharide essential for viability without LPS. PL composition shifted to shorter-chain saturated fatty acids.\",\n585\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n586\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n587\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n588\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n589\t      \"notes\": \"N. meningitidis cross-species comparator: capsule-dependent route, not Fur/sphingolipid. Supports evidence map row 9.\",\n590\t      \"bib_key\": \"Steeghs2001\"\n591\t    },\n592\t    {\n593\t      \"authors\": [\n594\t        \"Gao S\",\n595\t        \"Peng D\",\n596\t        \"Zhang W\",\n597\t        \"Muszynski A\",\n598\t        \"Carlson RW\",\n599\t        \"Gu XX\"\n600\t      ],\n601\t      \"year\": 2008,\n602\t      \"title\": \"Identification of two late acyltransferase genes responsible for lipid A biosynthesis in Moraxella catarrhalis\",\n603\t      \"venue\": \"FEBS J 275(20):5201-5214\",\n604\t      \"doi\": \"10.1111/j.1742-4658.2008.06651.x\",\n605\t      \"pmid\": \"18795947\",\n606\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2585779\",\n607\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n608\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n609\t      \"studied\": \"M. catarrhalis O35E; ΔlpxX, ΔlpxL single mutants; lipid A structural analysis, serum sensitivity, mouse model\",\n610\t      \"finding\": \"Identified lpxX (decanoyl transferase) and lpxL (dodecanoyl transferase) for lipid A biosynthesis. ΔlpxX sensitive to serum and hydrophobic reagents with reduced growth; ΔlpxL largely unaffected.\",\n611\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n612\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n613\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n614\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n615\t      \"notes\": \"M. catarrhalis cross-species comparator: late acyltransferase mutants viable without Fur involvement. Supports evidence map row 9.\",\n616\t      \"bib_key\": \"Gao2008\"\n617\t    },\n618\t    {\n619\t      \"authors\": [\n620\t        \"Gao S\",\n621\t        \"Ren D\",\n622\t        \"Peng D\",\n623\t        \"Zhang W\",\n624\t        \"Muszynski A\",\n625\t        \"Carlson RW\",\n626\t        \"Gu XX\"\n627\t      ],\n628\t      \"year\": 2013,\n629\t      \"title\": \"Late acyltransferase genes lpxX and lpxL jointly contribute to the biological activities of Moraxella catarrhalis\",\n630\t      \"venue\": \"J Med Microbiol 62(Pt 6):807-812\",\n631\t      \"doi\": \"10.1099/jmm.0.056846-0\",\n632\t      \"pmid\": \"23475908\",\n633\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC3709554\",\n634\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n635\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n636\t      \"studied\": \"M. catarrhalis O35E; ΔlpxXΔlpxL double mutant; lipid A analysis, serum resistance, mouse pulmonary clearance\",\n637\t      \"finding\": \"Double mutant ΔlpxXL lacks three secondary acyl chains from lipid A; dramatically reduced endotoxin content, reduced serum resistance, and accelerated bacterial clearance at 0, 3, and 6 h in mouse model.\",\n638\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n639\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n640\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n641\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n642\t      \"notes\": \"M. catarrhalis double mutant comparator. Supports evidence map row 9.\",\n643\t      \"bib_key\": \"Gao2013\"\n644\t    },\n645\t    {\n646\t      \"authors\": [\n647\t        \"Moffatt JH\",\n648\t        \"Harper M\",\n649\t        \"Harrison P\",\n650\t        \"Hale JDF\",\n651\t        \"Vinogradov E\",\n652\t        \"Seemann T\",\n653\t        \"Henry R\",\n654\t        \"Crane B\",\n655\t        \"St Michael F\",\n656\t        \"Cox AD\",\n657\t        \"Adler B\",\n658\t        \"Nation RL\",\n659\t        \"Li J\",\n660\t        \"Boyce JD\"\n661\t      ],\n662\t      \"year\": 2010,\n663\t      \"title\": \"Colistin resistance in Acinetobacter baumannii is mediated by complete loss of lipopolysaccharide production\",\n664\t      \"venue\": \"Antimicrob Agents Chemother 54(12):4971-4977\",\n665\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/AAC.00834-10\",\n666\t      \"pmid\": \"20855724\",\n667\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2981238\",\n668\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n669\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n670\t      \"studied\": \"A. baumannii ATCC 19606; 13 independent colistin-resistant derivatives; lpxA, lpxC, lpxD mutations\",\n671\t      \"finding\": \"A. baumannii can develop colistin resistance by complete loss of LPS production via mutations in lpxA, lpxC, or lpxD. First report of spontaneously occurring LPS-deficient Gram-negative bacterium.\",\n672\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n673\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n674\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n675\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n676\t      \"notes\": \"Original A. baumannii LPS-loss demonstration. Cross-species comparator (no Fur). Supports evidence map row 9.\",\n677\t      \"bib_key\": \"Moffatt2010\"\n678\t    },\n679\t    {\n680\t      \"authors\": [\n681\t        \"Moffatt JH\",\n682\t        \"Harper M\",\n683\t        \"Adler B\",\n684\t        \"Nation RL\",\n685\t        \"Li J\",\n686\t        \"Boyce JD\"\n687\t      ],\n688\t      \"year\": 2011,\n689\t      \"title\": \"Insertion sequence ISAba11 is involved in colistin resistance and loss of lipopolysaccharide in Acinetobacter baumannii\",\n690\t      \"venue\": \"Antimicrob Agents Chemother 55(6):3022-3024\",\n691\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/AAC.01732-10\",\n692\t      \"pmid\": \"21402838\",\n693\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC3101452\",\n694\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n695\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n696\t      \"studied\": \"A. baumannii clinical isolates; ISAba11 insertion sequence in lpxA and lpxC\",\n697\t      \"finding\": \"ISAba11 insertion sequence movement inactivates lpxA and lpxC in A. baumannii, causing complete LPS loss and high-level colistin resistance in clinical isolates.\",\n698\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n699\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n700\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n701\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n702\t      \"notes\": \"IS-driven mechanism in clinical A. baumannii. Supports evidence map row 9 (alternative LPS-loss route without Fur).\",\n703\t      \"bib_key\": \"Moffatt2011\"\n704\t    },\n705\t    {\n706\t      \"authors\": [\n707\t        \"van der Ley P\",\n708\t        \"Steeghs L\"\n709\t      ],\n710\t      \"year\": 2003,\n711\t      \"title\": \"Lessons from an LPS-deficient Neisseria meningitidis mutant\",\n712\t      \"venue\": \"J Endotoxin Res 9(2):124-128\",\n713\t      \"doi\": \"10.1179/096805103125001522\",\n714\t      \"pmid\": \"12803887\",\n715\t      \"pmcid\": null,\n716\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n717\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n718\t      \"studied\": \"N. meningitidis ΔlpxA; review of OM composition, immunogenicity, and inflammatory response\",\n719\t      \"finding\": \"LPS-deficient N. meningitidis retains OMP assembly but has reduced iron-limitation-inducible lipoprotein expression and reduced OM protein immunogenicity. Capsule essential for viability without LPS.\",\n720\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n721\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n722\t      \"is_review_article\": true,\n723\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n724\t      \"notes\": \"Companion review to Steeghs 2001. Notes reduced iron-limitation-inducible lipoproteins (oblique iron connection). Supports evidence map row 9.\",\n725\t      \"bib_key\": \"Ley2003\"\n726\t    },\n727\t    {\n728\t      \"authors\": [\n729\t        \"Flynn JM\",\n730\t        \"Levchenko I\",\n731\t        \"Sauer RT\",\n732\t        \"Baker TA\"\n733\t      ],\n734\t      \"year\": 2004,\n735\t      \"title\": \"Modulating substrate choice: the SspB adaptor delivers a regulator of the extracytoplasmic-stress response to the AAA+ protease ClpXP for degradation\",\n736\t      \"venue\": \"Genes Dev 18(18):2292-2301\",\n737\t      \"doi\": \"10.1101/gad.1240104\",\n738\t      \"pmid\": \"15371343\",\n739\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC517522\",\n740\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n741\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n742\t      \"studied\": \"E. coli; SspB adaptor, ClpXP protease, RseA anti-sigma-E factor; trapping + biochemical + genetic studies\",\n743\t      \"finding\": \"SspB delivers RseA (anti-sigma-E) to ClpXP for degradation, directly coupling SspB to envelope-stress (sigma-E) signaling. ClpX and SspB participate in induction of the sigma-E regulon in vivo.\",\n744\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n745\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n746\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n747\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n748\t      \"notes\": \"Foundational SspB biology in E. coli. Relevant because project strains carry ΔsspB (evidence map rows 2-3). Does this logic apply in Caulobacter?\",\n749\t      \"bib_key\": \"Flynn2004\"\n750\t    },\n751\t    {\n752\t      \"authors\": [\n753\t        \"Bhat NH\",\n754\t        \"Vass RH\",\n755\t        \"Stoddard PR\",\n756\t        \"Shin DK\",\n757\t        \"Chien P\"\n758\t      ],\n759\t      \"year\": 2013,\n760\t      \"title\": \"Identification of ClpP substrates in Caulobacter crescentus reveals a role for regulated proteolysis in bacterial development\",\n761\t      \"venue\": \"Mol Microbiol 88(6):1083-1092\",\n762\t      \"doi\": \"10.1111/mmi.12241\",\n763\t      \"pmid\": \"23647068\",\n764\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC3681837\",\n765\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n766\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n767\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus; ClpP substrate trapping + biochemical validation; TacA, CtrA, GcrA, SocB substrates\",\n768\t      \"finding\": \"Identified and validated ClpXP substrates in C. crescentus including TacA (stalk synthesis TF), CtrA, GcrA, SocB. Regulated proteolysis critical for cell cycle progression and Caulobacter development.\",\n769\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n770\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n771\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n772\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n773\t      \"notes\": \"Caulobacter-direct ClpP substrate catalog. SspB is in the substrate set. Supports SspB/ClpXP context (evidence map rows 2-3).\",\n774\t      \"bib_key\": \"Bhat2013\"\n775\t    },\n776\t    {\n777\t      \"authors\": [\n778\t        \"Chowdhury T\",\n779\t        \"Chien P\",\n780\t        \"Ebrahim S\",\n781\t        \"Sauer RT\",\n782\t        \"Baker TA\"\n783\t      ],\n784\t      \"year\": 2010,\n785\t      \"title\": \"Versatile modes of peptide recognition by the ClpX N domain mediate alternative adaptor-binding specificities in different bacterial species\",\n786\t      \"venue\": \"Protein Sci 19(2):242-254\",\n787\t      \"doi\": \"10.1002/pro.306\",\n788\t      \"pmid\": \"20014030\",\n789\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2865724\",\n790\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n791\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n792\t      \"studied\": \"E. coli and C. crescentus SspB-alpha; ClpX N domain recognition; cross-species substrate delivery\",\n793\t      \"finding\": \"E. coli SspB can deliver substrates to Caulobacter ClpXP despite very limited sequence homology between SspB orthologs. ClpX N domain is a versatile platform for peptide recognition with alternative adaptor-binding specificities.\",\n794\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n795\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n796\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n797\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n798\t      \"notes\": \"Explicitly compares E. coli and C. crescentus SspB; confirms functional conservation of adaptor-protease coupling across species (evidence map rows 2-3).\",\n799\t      \"bib_key\": \"Chowdhury2010\"\n800\t    },\n801\t    {\n802\t      \"authors\": [\n803\t        \"Martorana AM\",\n804\t        \"Benedet M\",\n805\t        \"Maccagni EA\",\n806\t        \"Sperandeo P\",\n807\t        \"Villa R\",\n808\t        \"Deho G\",\n809\t        \"Polissi A\"\n810\t      ],\n811\t      \"year\": 2016,\n812\t      \"title\": \"Functional Interaction between the Cytoplasmic ABC Protein LptB and the Inner Membrane LptC Protein, Components of the Lipopolysaccharide Transport Machinery in Escherichia coli\",\n813\t      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 198(16):2192-2203\",\n814\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.00329-16\",\n815\t      \"pmid\": \"27246575\",\n816\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC4966433\",\n817\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n818\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n819\t      \"studied\": \"E. coli; LptBCFG complex; LptB-LptC functional interaction; LptC truncation mutants; Pa-LptC chimera\",\n820\t      \"finding\": \"LptB and LptC functionally interact; LptB overexpression suppresses lethality of C-terminal LptC deletions and supports hybrid Lpt machinery carrying P. aeruginosa LptC. LptB key for Lpt machine assembly.\",\n821\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n822\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n823\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n824\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n825\t      \"notes\": \"E. coli Lpt machinery context. Relevant to interpreting Caulobacter MsbA-like/LptC-related transcript upregulation (evidence map row 7).\",\n826\t      \"bib_key\": \"Martorana2016\"\n827\t    },\n828\t    {\n829\t      \"authors\": [\n830\t        \"Price MN\",\n831\t        \"Wetmore KM\",\n832\t        \"Waters RJ\",\n833\t        \"Callaghan M\",\n834\t        \"Ray J\",\n835\t        \"Liu H\",\n836\t        \"Kuehl JV\",\n837\t        \"Melnyk RA\",\n838\t        \"Lamson JS\",\n839\t        \"Suh Y\",\n840\t        \"Carlson HK\",\n841\t        \"Esquivel Z\",\n842\t        \"Sadeeshkumar H\",\n843\t        \"Chakraborty R\",\n844\t        \"Zane GM\",\n845\t        \"Rubin BE\",\n846\t        \"Wall JD\",\n847\t        \"Visel A\",\n848\t        \"Bristow J\",\n849\t        \"Blow MJ\",\n850\t        \"Arkin AP\",\n851\t        \"Deutschbauer AM\"\n852\t      ],\n853\t      \"year\": 2018,\n854\t      \"title\": \"Mutant phenotypes for thousands of bacterial genes of unknown function\",\n855\t      \"venue\": \"Nature 557(7706):503-509\",\n856\t      \"doi\": \"10.1038/s41586-018-0124-0\",\n857\t      \"pmid\": \"29769716\",\n858\t      \"pmcid\": null,\n859\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n860\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n861\t      \"studied\": \"32 phylogenetically diverse bacteria including C. crescentus; RB-TnSeq across dozens of growth conditions\",\n862\t      \"finding\": \"Identified mutant phenotypes for 11,779 protein-coding genes lacking functional annotation; 2,316 conserved high-confidence associations. Demonstrates scalability of microbial genetics for improving gene annotations.\",\n863\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n864\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n865\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n866\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n867\t      \"notes\": \"Methods provenance: primary citation for RB-TnSeq methodology and BERDL kescience_fitnessbrowser data source used in NB02/NB02b.\",\n868\t      \"bib_key\": \"Price2018\"\n869\t    },\n870\t    {\n871\t      \"authors\": [\n872\t        \"Price MN\",\n873\t        \"Arkin AP\"\n874\t      ],\n875\t      \"year\": 2017,\n876\t      \"title\": \"PaperBLAST: Text Mining Papers for Information about Homologs\",\n877\t      \"venue\": \"mSystems 2(4):e00039-17\",\n878\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/mSystems.00039-17\",\n879\t      \"pmid\": \"28845458\",\n880\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC5557654\",\n881\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n882\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n883\t      \"studied\": \"Text mining of >700,000 scientific articles linked to >400,000 protein sequences via EuropePMC + curated databases\",\n884\t      \"finding\": \"PaperBLAST rapidly finds similar proteins discussed in literature and presents text snippets from relevant articles. Links EuropePMC full-text search with Swiss-Prot, GeneRIF, and EcoCyc curated annotations.\",\n885\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n886\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n887\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n888\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n889\t      \"notes\": \"Methods provenance: primary citation for PaperBLAST (BERDL kescience_paperblast). Used in NB06 cross-species analysis. REPORT.md PMID was wrong (33531404); correct is 28845458.\",\n890\t      \"bib_key\": \"Price2017\"\n891\t    },\n892\t    {\n893\t      \"authors\": [\n894\t        \"Arkin AP\",\n895\t        \"Cottingham RW\",\n896\t        \"Henry CS\",\n897\t        \"Harris NL\",\n898\t        \"Stevens RL\",\n899\t        \"Maslov S\",\n900\t        \"Dehal P\",\n901\t        \"Ware D\",\n902\t        \"Perez F\",\n903\t        \"Canon S\",\n904\t        \"Sneddon MW\",\n905\t        \"Henderson ML\",\n906\t        \"Riehl WJ\",\n907\t        \"Murphy-Olson D\",\n908\t        \"Chan SY\",\n909\t        \"Kamimura RT\",\n910\t        \"Kumari S\",\n911\t        \"Drake MM\",\n912\t        \"Brettin TS\",\n913\t        \"Glass EM\",\n914\t        \"Chivian D\",\n915\t        \"Gunter D\",\n916\t        \"Weston DJ\",\n917\t        \"Allen BH\",\n918\t        \"Baumohl J\",\n919\t        \"Best AA\",\n920\t        \"Bowen B\",\n921\t        \"Brenner SE\",\n922\t        \"Bun CC\",\n923\t        \"Chandonia JM\"\n924\t      ],\n925\t      \"year\": 2018,\n926\t      \"title\": \"KBase: The United States Department of Energy Systems Biology Knowledgebase\",\n927\t      \"venue\": \"Nat Biotechnol 36(7):566-569\",\n928\t      \"doi\": \"10.1038/nbt.4163\",\n929\t      \"pmid\": \"29979655\",\n930\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC6870991\",\n931\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n932\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n933\t      \"studied\": \"KBase systems biology knowledgebase platform; integrated tools for genome assembly, annotation, metabolic modeling, multi-omics analysis\",\n934\t      \"finding\": \"KBase is the DOE Systems Biology Knowledgebase providing integrated computational tools for systems biology research; enables reproducible, collaborative genome-scale data analysis.\",\n935\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n936\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n937\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n938\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n939\t      \"notes\": \"Methods provenance: primary citation for KBase infrastructure. BERDL is built on KBase.\",\n940\t      \"bib_key\": \"Arkin2018\"\n941\t    },\n942\t    {\n943\t      \"authors\": [\n944\t        \"Robinson MD\",\n945\t        \"McCarthy DJ\",\n946\t        \"Smyth GK\"\n947\t      ],\n948\t      \"year\": 2010,\n949\t      \"title\": \"edgeR: a Bioconductor package for differential expression analysis of digital gene expression data\",\n950\t      \"venue\": \"Bioinformatics 26(1):139-140\",\n951\t      \"doi\": \"10.1093/bioinformatics/btp616\",\n952\t      \"pmid\": \"19910308\",\n953\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2796818\",\n954\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n955\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n956\t      \"studied\": \"Computational methodology for differential expression analysis of replicated count data (RNA-seq, DGE)\",\n957\t      \"finding\": \"edgeR uses an overdispersed Poisson model with empirical Bayes moderation of dispersion across transcripts to analyze differential expression of digital gene expression data; works with minimal replication levels.\",\n958\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n959\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n960\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n961\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n962\t      \"notes\": \"Methods provenance: edgeR used for DE analysis in project notebooks (methods_provenance.md lists edgeR as statistical test).\",\n963\t      \"bib_key\": \"Robinson2010\"\n964\t    },\n965\t    {\n966\t      \"authors\": [\n967\t        \"Choi U\",\n968\t        \"Lee CR\"\n969\t      ],\n970\t      \"year\": 2019,\n971\t      \"title\": \"Antimicrobial Agents That Inhibit the Outer Membrane Assembly Machines of Gram-Negative Bacteria\",\n972\t      \"venue\": \"J Microbiol Biotechnol 29(1):1-10\",\n973\t      \"doi\": \"10.4014/jmb.1804.03051\",\n974\t      \"pmid\": \"29996592\",\n975\t      \"pmcid\": null,\n976\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n977\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n978\t      \"studied\": \"Gram-negative bacteria broadly; Lol (lipoprotein), BAM (OMP), and Lpt (LPS) OM assembly pathways; inhibitor development\",\n979\t      \"finding\": \"Reviews OM component transport machinery (Lol for lipoproteins, BAM for OMPs, Lpt for LPS) and development of inhibitors targeting these systems. OM assembly machines are potential novel antibiotic targets.\",\n980\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n981\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n982\t      \"is_review_article\": true,\n983\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n984\t      \"notes\": \"Background review of OM assembly machines; provides context for Lpt pathway repurposing in Caulobacter (evidence map row 7).\",\n985\t      \"bib_key\": \"Choi2019\"\n986\t    },\n987\t    {\n988\t      \"authors\": [\n989\t        \"Barrows JM\",\n990\t        \"Goley ED\"\n991\t      ],\n992\t      \"year\": 2023,\n993\t      \"title\": \"Synchronized Swarmers and Sticky Stalks: Caulobacter crescentus as a Model for Bacterial Cell Biology\",\n994\t      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 205(2):e0038422\",\n995\t      \"doi\": \"10.1128/jb.00384-22\",\n996\t      \"pmid\": \"36715542\",\n997\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC9945503\",\n998\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n999\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n1000\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus as model organism; review of dimorphic life cycle, swarmer/stalked cell biology, appendage biogenesis, cell cycle control, and developmental regulators\",\n1001\t      \"finding\": \"C. crescentus exhibits a dimorphic life cycle of motile swarmer and nonmotile stalked cells with tightly controlled biogenesis of appendages and distinct localization of developmental regulators; populations can be synchronized, making it ideal for studies of bacterial differentiation at the single-cell level.\",\n1002\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n1003\t      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n1004\t      \"is_review_article\": true,\n1005\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n1006\t      \"notes\": \"Caulobacter model organism review for talk introduction slides; audience orientation to organism context. added by talk\",\n1007\t      \"bib_key\": \"Barrows2023\"\n1008\t    },\n1009\t    {\n1010\t      \"authors\": [\n1011\t        \"Nierman WC\",\n1012\t        \"Feldblyum TV\",\n1013\t        \"Laub MT\",\n1014\t        \"Paulsen IT\",\n1015\t        \"Nelson KE\",\n1016\t        \"Eisen JA\",\n1017\t        \"Heidelberg JF\",\n1018\t        \"Alley MR\",\n1019\t        \"Ohta N\",\n1020\t        \"Maddock JR\",\n1021\t        \"Potocka I\",\n1022\t        \"Nelson WC\",\n1023\t        \"Newton A\",\n1024\t        \"Stephens C\",\n1025\t        \"Phadke ND\",\n1026\t        \"Ely B\",\n1027\t        \"DeBoy RT\",\n1028\t        \"Dodson RJ\",\n1029\t        \"Durkin AS\",\n1030\t        \"Gwinn ML\",\n1031\t        \"Haft DH\",\n1032\t        \"Kolonay JF\",\n1033\t        \"Smit J\",\n1034\t        \"Craven MB\",\n1035\t        \"Khouri H\",\n1036\t        \"Shetty J\",\n1037\t        \"Berry K\",\n1038\t        \"Utterback T\",\n1039\t        \"Tran K\",\n1040\t        \"Wolf A\",\n1041\t        \"Vamathevan J\",\n1042\t        \"Ermolaeva M\",\n1043\t        \"White O\",\n1044\t        \"Salzberg SL\",\n1045\t        \"Venter JC\",\n1046\t        \"Shapiro L\",\n1047\t        \"Fraser CM\"\n1048\t      ],\n1049\t      \"year\": 2001,\n1050\t      \"title\": \"Complete genome sequence of Caulobacter crescentus\",\n1051\t      \"venue\": \"Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A 98(7):4136-4141\",\n1052\t      \"doi\": \"10.1073/pnas.061029298\",\n1053\t      \"pmid\": \"11259647\",\n1054\t      \"pmcid\": \"PMC31192\",\n1055\t      \"arxiv\": null,\n1056\t      \"biorxiv\": null,\n1057\t      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus CB15; 4,016,942 bp single circular chromosome, 3,767 genes; first free-living alphaproteobacterium genome sequenced\",\n1058\t      \"finding\": \"Complete genome sequence of C. crescentus CB15: 4,016,942 bp encoding 3,767 genes, including 105 two-component signal transduction proteins (highest of any bacterial genome at the time). First free-living alpha-proteobacterium to be fully sequenced.\",\n1059\t      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n1060\t      \"assessment\": \"orthogonal\",\n1061\t      \"is_review_article\": false,\n1062\t      \"is_preprint\": false,\n1063\t      \"notes\": \"Reference genome for Caulobacter CB15; NA1000 strain used in this project is a synchronizable derivative of CB15. Cited on organism background slides for genome-scale context. added by talk\",\n1064\t      \"bib_key\": \"Nierman2001\"\n1065\t    }\n1066\t  ],\n1067\t  \"citation_map\": {},\n1068\t  \"first_cited_at\": {},\n1069\t  \"summary\": {\n1070\t    \"size\": 39,\n1071\t    \"cap\": 80,\n1072\t    \"remaining\": 41\n1073\t  }\n1074\t}\n1075\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57c7cd12-ce3b-4c50-865d-721855d63587","uuid":"c1cf415a-1380-4c8b-b52a-9b40009cc079","timestamp":"2026-06-08T23:43:07.674Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/aparkin/BERIL-research-observatory/projects/caulobacter_fur_lipida_loss/talks/draft_2/working/citation_pool.json","content":"{\n  \"entries\": [\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Raetz CRH\",\n        \"Whitfield C\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2002,\n      \"title\": \"Lipopolysaccharide endotoxins\",\n      \"venue\": \"Annu Rev Biochem 71:635-700\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1146/annurev.biochem.71.110601.135414\",\n      \"pmid\": \"12045108\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2569852\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"Gram-negative bacteria broadly; lipid A structure, biosynthesis (Raetz pathway), transport, and TLR4 signaling\",\n      \"finding\": \"Lipid A biosynthesis follows the conserved nine-step Raetz pathway; lipid A-Kdo2 is the minimal LPS structure required for outer membrane biogenesis in most Gram-negatives. LpxC validated as an antibiotic target.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": true,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Foundational LPS review; establishes the lipid A essentiality paradigm that Caulobacter violates. Serves Introduction background.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Raetz2002\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Zik JJ\",\n        \"Yoon SH\",\n        \"Guan Z\",\n        \"Stankeviciute Skidmore G\",\n        \"Gudoor RR\",\n        \"Davies KM\",\n        \"Deutschbauer AM\",\n        \"Goodlett DR\",\n        \"Klein EA\",\n        \"Ryan KR\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2022,\n      \"title\": \"Caulobacter lipid A is conditionally dispensable in the absence of fur and in the presence of anionic sphingolipids\",\n      \"venue\": \"Cell Rep 39(9):110888\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1016/j.celrep.2022.110888\",\n      \"pmid\": \"35649364\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC9393093\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"Caulobacter crescentus NA1000; Δfur, ΔlpxC, ΔctpA mutants; genetics, lipidomics, suppressor analysis\",\n      \"finding\": \"Mutations in fur allow C. crescentus to survive without LpxC or CtpA; viability requires anionic sphingolipid ceramide phosphoglycerate (CPG). 'Alterations in Fur-regulated processes, rather than iron status per se, underlie the ability to survive when lipid A synthesis is blocked.'\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Keystone paper for the entire throughline. Establishes the Δfur + sphingolipid mechanism. Ryan lab collaboration source.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Zik2022\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Uchendu CG\",\n        \"Isom GL\",\n        \"Klein EA\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2026,\n      \"title\": \"Homologues of the inner-membrane LPS transport proteins are required for sphingolipid transport in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"bioRxiv 2026.04.12.717747\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1101/2026.04.12.717747\",\n      \"pmid\": null,\n      \"pmcid\": null,\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": \"2026.04.12.717747\",\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus lipid-A-deficient strains; inner membrane lipid transport complex\",\n      \"finding\": \"Homologues of inner-membrane LPS transport proteins (Lpt paralogs) are required for sphingolipid transport in lipid-A-deficient Caulobacter; identifies shared Lpt machinery components for CPG trafficking.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"Directly supports throughline sub-claim on Lpt apparatus repurposing for sphingolipid transport. Most recent Klein lab follow-up.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Uchendu2026\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Dhakephalkar T\",\n        \"Stukey GJ\",\n        \"Guan Z\",\n        \"Carman GM\",\n        \"Klein EA\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2023,\n      \"title\": \"Characterization of an evolutionarily distinct bacterial ceramide kinase from Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"J Biol Chem 299(7):104894\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1016/j.jbc.2023.104894\",\n      \"pmid\": \"37286040\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC10331486\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus CpgB recombinant protein; enzyme kinetics in vitro\",\n      \"finding\": \"CpgB is an evolutionarily distinct bacterial ceramide kinase: Km = 19.2 +/- 5.5 uM for NBD C6-ceramide, Vmax = 2590 +/- 230 pmol/min/mg. Phylogenetically distinct from eukaryotic ceramide kinases; NVP-231 inhibitor has no effect.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"First step in CPG head-group biosynthesis. Supports constitutive sphingolipid biosynthesis sub-claim.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Dhakephalkar2023\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Dhakephalkar T\",\n        \"Guan Z\",\n        \"Klein EA\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2025,\n      \"title\": \"CpgD is a phosphoglycerate cytidylyltransferase required for ceramide diphosphoglycerate synthesis\",\n      \"venue\": \"bioRxiv 2025.01.09.632243\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1101/2025.01.09.632243\",\n      \"pmid\": \"39829823\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC11741362\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": \"2025.01.09.632243\",\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus CpgD (CCNA_01210) recombinant protein; enzyme kinetics in vitro\",\n      \"finding\": \"CpgD is a phosphoglycerate cytidylyltransferase producing CDP-glycerate from CTP and 3-phosphoglycerate (Km,app = 10.9 +/- 0.7 mM for 3-PG); required for ceramide diphosphoglycerate (CPG2) synthesis.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": true,\n      \"notes\": \"PubMed-indexed as preprint (bioRxiv). Supports constitutive sphingolipid biosynthesis sub-claim.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Dhakephalkar2025\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Olea-Ozuna RJ\",\n        \"Poggio S\",\n        \"Bergstrom E\",\n        \"Quiroz-Rocha E\",\n        \"Garcia-Soriano DA\",\n        \"Sahonero-Canavesi DX\",\n        \"Padilla-Gomez J\",\n        \"Martinez-Aguilar L\",\n        \"Lopez-Lara IM\",\n        \"Thomas-Oates J\",\n        \"Geiger O\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2021,\n      \"title\": \"Five structural genes required for ceramide synthesis in Caulobacter and for bacterial survival\",\n      \"venue\": \"Environ Microbiol 23(1):143-159\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1111/1462-2920.15280\",\n      \"pmid\": \"33063925\",\n      \"pmcid\": null,\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; Δspt and cofitness-linked mutants; lipid analysis, growth/survival assays\",\n      \"finding\": \"Five structural genes required for dihydroceramide biosynthesis; sphingolipid biosynthesis needed for stationary-phase survival and OM integrity. Δspt mutant has much reduced survival at elevated temperatures.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Establishes the ceramide biosynthetic pathway including spt. Supports constitutive sphingolipid biosynthesis sub-claim (evidence map row 6).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"OleaOzuna2021\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Olea-Ozuna RJ\",\n        \"Poggio S\",\n        \"Bergstrom E\",\n        \"Osorio A\",\n        \"Elufisan TO\",\n        \"Padilla-Gomez J\",\n        \"Martinez-Aguilar L\",\n        \"Lopez-Lara IM\",\n        \"Thomas-Oates J\",\n        \"Geiger O\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2024,\n      \"title\": \"Genes required for phosphosphingolipid formation in Caulobacter crescentus contribute to bacterial virulence\",\n      \"venue\": \"PLoS Pathog 20(8):e1012401\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1371/journal.ppat.1012401\",\n      \"pmid\": \"39093898\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC11324152\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; 11 sphingolipid biosynthesis genes; polymyxin B sensitivity; Galleria mellonella virulence model\",\n      \"finding\": \"At least 11 genes participate in phosphosphingolipid formation; all required for membrane stability and polymyxin B sensitivity. Sphingolipid genes contribute to C. crescentus virulence on G. mellonella.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Extends sphingolipid pathway from 5 to 11 genes. Supports constitutive sphingolipid biosynthesis sub-claim.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"OleaOzuna2024\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Hummels KR\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2024,\n      \"title\": \"mSphere of Influence: Celebrating exceptions to the rule of lipid A essentiality\",\n      \"venue\": \"mSphere 9(3):e0063323\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1128/msphere.00633-23\",\n      \"pmid\": \"38421175\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC10964400\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"Comparative review of A. baumannii (Boll lab, PG-remodeling route) and C. crescentus (Zik/Ryan, fur + sphingolipid route) lipid A dispensability\",\n      \"finding\": \"Exceptions to lipid A essentiality illuminate distinct bacterial strategies: A. baumannii uses PBP1A loss + ld-transpeptidase PG remodeling, while C. crescentus relies on Fur derepression + anionic sphingolipid substitution.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": true,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Commentary framing piece; directly compares the two known lipid A dispensability routes. Serves Introduction + Discussion context.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Hummels2024\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Langklotz S\",\n        \"Schakermann M\",\n        \"Narberhaus F\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2011,\n      \"title\": \"Control of lipopolysaccharide biosynthesis by FtsH-mediated proteolysis of LpxC is conserved in enterobacteria but not in all gram-negative bacteria\",\n      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 193(5):1090-1097\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.01043-10\",\n      \"pmid\": \"21193611\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC3067583\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"E. coli, Salmonella, Yersinia, Vibrio, Agrobacterium tumefaciens, Rhodobacter capsulatus, Pseudomonas aeruginosa; FtsH-mediated LpxC proteolysis\",\n      \"finding\": \"FtsH-mediated LpxC proteolysis is conserved in Enterobacteriaceae but NOT in all Gram-negatives. A. tumefaciens and R. capsulatus LpxC degraded by Lon protease; P. aeruginosa LpxC is stable. Alphaproteobacteria may use non-FtsH mechanisms.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Relevant to why LpxC dynamics in Caulobacter differ from E. coli. Supports species-specificity sub-claim.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Langklotz2011\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Leaden L\",\n        \"Silva LG\",\n        \"Ribeiro RA\",\n        \"Dos Santos NM\",\n        \"Lorenzetti APR\",\n        \"Alegria TGP\",\n        \"Schulz ML\",\n        \"Medeiros MHG\",\n        \"Koide T\",\n        \"Marques MV\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2018,\n      \"title\": \"Iron Deficiency Generates Oxidative Stress and Activation of the SOS Response in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"Front Microbiol 9:2014\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.3389/fmicb.2018.02014\",\n      \"pmid\": \"30210482\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC6120978\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000 wild type under iron limitation (2,2'-dipyridyl) and Δfur mutant; RNA-seq\",\n      \"finding\": \"Identified 256 upregulated and 236 downregulated genes under iron limitation; 176 and 204 newly identified respectively. Sixteen transcription factors and seven sRNAs upregulated. Iron deficiency causes endogenous oxidative stress and SOS response activation.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Primary reference for Caulobacter Fur regulon RNA-seq. Directly used in NB01 for Leaden DEG set comparison (evidence map row 3).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Leaden2018\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"da Silva Neto JF\",\n        \"Braz VS\",\n        \"Italiani VCS\",\n        \"Marques MV\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2009,\n      \"title\": \"Fur controls iron homeostasis and oxidative stress defense in the oligotrophic alpha-proteobacterium Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"Nucleic Acids Res 37(14):4812-4825\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1093/nar/gkp509\",\n      \"pmid\": \"19520766\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2724300\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000 Δfur mutant; ChIP + microarray + bioinformatics for Fur-binding sites\",\n      \"finding\": \"Fur functions as both activator and repressor, integrating iron metabolism and oxidative stress response. Iron uptake genes repressed by iron-Fur and induced under iron limitation; iron-using protein genes activated by Fur under iron sufficiency.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Earlier ChIP/microarray Caulobacter Fur regulon paper; frequently cited by the Klein/Ryan group. Supports Fur-released transport sub-claim (evidence map row 1).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Neto2009\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Dos Santos NM\",\n        \"Picinato BA\",\n        \"Santos LS\",\n        \"de Araujo HL\",\n        \"Balan A\",\n        \"Koide T\",\n        \"Marques MV\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2024,\n      \"title\": \"Mapping the IscR regulon sheds light on the regulation of iron homeostasis in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"Front Microbiol 15:1463854\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.3389/fmicb.2024.1463854\",\n      \"pmid\": \"39411446\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC11475020\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000 ΔiscR mutant; RNA-seq + ChIP-seq; 302-gene IscR regulon\",\n      \"finding\": \"IscR regulon comprises 302 genes with partial Fur overlap. IscR represses the respiration regulator FixK, fine-tuning gene regulation in response to iron and redox balance. Two distinct IscR binding motifs identified.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"IscR/Fur overlap relevant to partitioning Fur-specific vs broader iron-regulon contributions. Supports evidence map row 1.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Santos2024\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Hernandez-Ortiz S\",\n        \"Ok K\",\n        \"O'Halloran TV\",\n        \"Fiebig A\",\n        \"Crosson S\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2025,\n      \"title\": \"A co-conserved gene pair supports Caulobacter iron homeostasis during chelation stress\",\n      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 207(4):e0048424\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1128/jb.00484-24\",\n      \"pmid\": \"40084995\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC12004947\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; RB-TnSeq under EDTA chelation; CciT (TBDT) and CciO dioxygenase\",\n      \"finding\": \"CciT is a Fur-regulated TonB-dependent transporter that supports iron homeostasis during chelation stress; strictly requires co-conserved CciO (Fe2+ dioxygenase). Gene pair broadly co-conserved in Proteobacteria.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Defines a specific Fur-regulated TBDT pair in Caulobacter. Supports Fur-released transport sub-claim (evidence map row 1).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"HernandezOrtiz2025\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"de Castro Ferreira IG\",\n        \"Rodrigues MM\",\n        \"da Silva Neto JF\",\n        \"Mazzon RR\",\n        \"do Valle Marques M\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2016,\n      \"title\": \"Role and regulation of ferritin-like proteins in iron homeostasis and oxidative stress survival of Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"Biometals 29(5):851-862\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1007/s10534-016-9956-y\",\n      \"pmid\": \"27484774\",\n      \"pmcid\": null,\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; Bfr, Dps, CC_0557 ferritin-like proteins; Δbfr, Δdps mutants\",\n      \"finding\": \"bfr expression positively regulated (2.5-fold) by Fe-Fur. Δdps very sensitive to H2O2; Bfr contributes to iron homeostasis, Dps to oxidative stress protection. Ferritins link Fur regulation to iron storage.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Caulobacter-specific Fur-regulated iron storage. Supports Fur regulon context (evidence map row 1).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Ferreira2016\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Balhesteros H\",\n        \"Shipelskiy Y\",\n        \"Long NJ\",\n        \"Majumdar A\",\n        \"Katz BB\",\n        \"Santos NM\",\n        \"Leaden L\",\n        \"Newton SM\",\n        \"Marques MV\",\n        \"Klebba PE\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2017,\n      \"title\": \"TonB-Dependent Heme/Hemoglobin Utilization by Caulobacter crescentus HutA\",\n      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 199(6):e00723-16\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.00723-16\",\n      \"pmid\": \"28031282\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC5331666\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; 62 putative TBDTs; iron transport kinetics; sarcosinate extracts + mass spectrometry\",\n      \"finding\": \"Identified five TBDTs with regulated expression: three overexpressed during iron deficiency (CCNA_00028, 02277, 03023), two during iron repletion. HutA (CCNA_02277) is the first characterized C. crescentus heme/hemoglobin transporter.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Fur-regulated TBDTs in Caulobacter; relevant to the n=32 TBDT subset derepressed in Δfur (evidence map row 1).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Balhesteros2017\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Silva LG\",\n        \"Lorenzetti APR\",\n        \"Ribeiro RA\",\n        \"Alves IR\",\n        \"Leaden L\",\n        \"Galhardo RS\",\n        \"Koide T\",\n        \"Marques MV\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2019,\n      \"title\": \"OxyR and the hydrogen peroxide stress response in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"Gene 700:70-84\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1016/j.gene.2019.03.003\",\n      \"pmid\": \"30880241\",\n      \"pmcid\": null,\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000 wild type and ΔoxyR; H2O2 exposure at two time points; RNA-seq\",\n      \"finding\": \"Fur and part of its regulon were differentially expressed in response to H2O2 independently of OxyR. OxyR required for expression of 103 genes in H2O2 response. Demonstrates Fur-OxyR cross-regulation under oxidative stress.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Fur cross-talk with oxidative stress response; relevant to envelope stress phenotypes in the TBDT subset (evidence map row 1).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Silva2019\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Stein BJ\",\n        \"Fiebig A\",\n        \"Crosson S\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2021,\n      \"title\": \"The ChvG-ChvI and NtrY-NtrX Two-Component Systems Coordinately Regulate Growth of Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 203(17):e0019921\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.00199-21\",\n      \"pmid\": \"34124942\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC8351639\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; ΔchvG, ΔchvI, ΔntrY, ΔntrX mutants; RNA-seq for ChvI regulon; genetic suppressor analysis\",\n      \"finding\": \"Defined the ChvI transcriptional regulon in C. crescentus; significant overlap with NtrX regulon. chvGI deletion limits growth in defined medium. NtrZ identified as periplasmic inhibitor of NtrY phosphatase activity.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Primary ChvI regulon reference; used in NB03 for ChvI two-phase partition (evidence map row 4). Dataset in clean/chvi_overexpression_regulon_stein_2021.csv.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Stein2021\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Quintero-Yanes A\",\n        \"Mayard A\",\n        \"Hallez R\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2022,\n      \"title\": \"The two-component system ChvGI maintains cell envelope homeostasis in Caulobacter crescentus\",\n      \"venue\": \"PLoS Genet 18(12):e1010465\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1371/journal.pgen.1010465\",\n      \"pmid\": \"36480504\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC9731502\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus NA1000; chv mutants under vancomycin + osmotic stress; ChvI regulon via RNA-seq\",\n      \"finding\": \"ChvI regulates cell envelope architecture controlling OM, PG assembly/recycling, and IM proteins. ChvI phosphorylation activated by vancomycin. ChvGI TCS monitors osmotic imbalances and PG damage to maintain envelope homeostasis.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Independent ChvI regulon confirmation; dataset in clean/chvi_regulon_quintero_yanes_2022.csv. Supports evidence map row 4.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"QuinteroYanes2022\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Greenwich JL\",\n        \"Heckel BC\",\n        \"Alakavuklar MA\",\n        \"Fuqua C\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2023,\n      \"title\": \"The ChvG-ChvI Regulatory Network: A Conserved Global Regulatory Circuit Among the Alphaproteobacteria with Pervasive Impacts on Host Interactions and Diverse Cellular Processes\",\n      \"venue\": \"Annu Rev Microbiol 77:131-148\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1146/annurev-micro-120822-102714\",\n      \"pmid\": \"37040790\",\n      \"pmcid\": null,\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"Alphaproteobacteria broadly; ChvG-ChvI conservation, ExoR regulation, regulon targets across species\",\n      \"finding\": \"ChvG-ChvI is a conserved global regulatory circuit in alphaproteobacteria controlling envelope composition, virulence, biofilm, motility. Acidic pH stimulates ExoR proteolysis, activating ChvG-ChvI. Envelope stress may also generally activate.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": true,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Authoritative synthesis of ChvG-ChvI biology. Conceptual scaffold for ChvI two-phase signaling sub-claim (evidence map row 4).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Greenwich2023\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Tan WB\",\n        \"Chng SS\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2025,\n      \"title\": \"Primary role of the Tol-Pal complex in bacterial outer membrane lipid homeostasis\",\n      \"venue\": \"Nat Commun 16(1):2293\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1038/s41467-025-57630-y\",\n      \"pmid\": \"40055349\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC11889096\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"E. coli; chimeric Tol-Pal complex engineered to lose septal enrichment but retain OM function\",\n      \"finding\": \"Primary function of Tol-Pal complex is OM lipid homeostasis (retrograde phospholipid transport), independent of its role during division. Peripherally-localized Tol-Pal fully capable of maintaining OM lipid balance.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Basis for revised Pal-upregulation interpretation in Discussion (evidence map row 8). E. coli system, not Caulobacter.\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Tan2025\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Yeh YC\",\n        \"Comolli LR\",\n        \"Downing KH\",\n        \"Shapiro L\",\n        \"McAdams HH\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2010,\n      \"title\": \"The caulobacter Tol-Pal complex is essential for outer membrane integrity and the positioning of a polar localization factor\",\n      \"venue\": \"J Bacteriol 192(19):4847-4858\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1128/JB.00607-10\",\n      \"pmid\": \"20693330\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC2944545\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"C. crescentus; TolA, TolB, Pal depletion/mutant strains; cryo-EM, fluorescence microscopy\",\n      \"finding\": \"Caulobacter Tol-Pal complex is essential for OM integrity and cell division (unlike E. coli where dispensable). Components localize to division plane; Pal interacts with TipN polar localization factor.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"direct\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Caulobacter-specific Tol-Pal essentiality context. Pal upregulation in Δfur must be interpreted against this essential-complex background (evidence map row 8).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Yeh2010\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Kang KN\",\n        \"Kazi MI\",\n        \"Biboy J\",\n        \"Gray J\",\n        \"Bovermann H\",\n        \"Ausman J\",\n        \"Boutte CC\",\n        \"Vollmer W\",\n        \"Boll JM\"\n      ],\n      \"year\": 2021,\n      \"title\": \"Septal Class A Penicillin-Binding Protein Activity and ld-Transpeptidases Mediate Selection of Colistin-Resistant Lipooligosaccharide-Deficient Acinetobacter baumannii\",\n      \"venue\": \"mBio 12(1):e02185-20\",\n      \"doi\": \"10.1128/mBio.02185-20\",\n      \"pmid\": \"33402533\",\n      \"pmcid\": \"PMC8545086\",\n      \"arxiv\": null,\n      \"biorxiv\": null,\n      \"studied\": \"A. baumannii ATCC 19606; PBP1A, LdtJ, LdtK mutants; colistin-resistant LOS-deficient isolates; transposon mutagenesis\",\n      \"finding\": \"PBP1A inactivation is a compensatory mutation supporting LOS-deficient A. baumannii isolation. Both LdtJ and LdtK ld-transpeptidases required for LOS-deficient colony selection. PG remodeling is the tolerance route, NOT Fur.\",\n      \"scope_alignment\": \"partial\",\n      \"assessment\": \"supports\",\n      \"is_review_article\": false,\n      \"is_preprint\": false,\n      \"notes\": \"Direct A. baumannii comparator: PG-remodeling route vs Caulobacter sphingolipid route. Supports cross-species pathway absence sub-claim (evidence map row 9).\",\n      \"bib_key\": \"Kang2021\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"authors\": [\n        \"Steeghs L\",\n        \"de Cock H\",\n  